<FIRST>u i AM-PrisonRevolt 1stLd-Writethru a0675 03-28 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison Revolt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,0819</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prison Negotiations Reach Impasse, Food and Water May Be Cut Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with government setting deadline
before prison water, food cut off. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CATARINA PINULA, Guatemala (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said they
will cut off water and food to heavily armed rebellious convicts
and about 600 family members inside a besieged prison if no accord
is reached Wednesday.
   Negotiations with the inmates stalled Tuesday night as food for
the nearly 2,000 people in the prison complex grew scarce.
   ``We're at an impasse,'' the Rev. Antonio Lopez Martin, chaplain
of Guatemalan prisons and one of the negotiators, told journalists
upon leaving the prison after dark.
   The rebellion began on Easter Sunday, and prison spokesman
Conrado Monroy said Tuesday night that as many as 12 people may
have been killed. The inmates armed themselves with carbines taken
from the prison armory.
   Authorities had removed seven bodies from the grounds _ those of
four guards and three convicts _ by Tuesday. About 20 people were
wounded.
   Prisoners told negotiators three bodies remained on prison
grounds and inmates buried two others after the fighting, Monroy
said.
   About 20 inmates not among the rebels were shipped to another
jail Tuesday. They were seen leaving the prison, handcuffed by
twos, and placed on a bus.
   Another six visitors who had been inside the prison since the
Sunday afternoon uprising also made their way out Tuesday.
   Gonzalo Menendez de la Riva, special attorney general for human
rights, indicated the main stumbling block in talks between
government representatives and inmates was government unwillingness
or inability to assure prisoners pardons for acts since seizing the
Pavon prison farm, 14 miles east of Guatemala City.
   He said that the prisoners have the right to ask for pardons,
but the government is not in a position to award pardons.
   Rebels also have demanded reduced sentences, better food and
treatment and new prison management.
   Menendez gave the prison rebels a government promise not to beat
or kill the rebellious prisoners and to intercede on their behalf
with the Supreme Court, which can offer judicial pardons.
   Monroy said Tuesday night that if the rebels do not accept the
offer Wednesday, water and food will be cut off.
   He said much food was delivered Monday night, but it is almost
all gone because of the large number of people inside.
   President Vinicio Cerezo said the 1,000 or more soldiers and
police ringing the prison had orders to use force ``only if the
prisoners try to shoot their way out.''
   About 600 Easter visitors, including hundreds of women and
children, have remained inside since the takeover.
   Cerezo said Tuesday that drug traffickers may have sponsored the
rebellion by up to 100 inmates who took over the central buildings
of the 2{-square-mile prison farm.
   Authorities say the mutinous prisoners took over about 65
percent of the facility, including most important buildings. Lopez
said the rebel leader was a military man who wore a hood and gave
orders to the other mutineers.
   Pavon was designed for 800 inmates but now holds more than 1,350.
   ``They are desperate,'' the Rev. Jose Maria Varela said of the
rebels when he left the facility.
   He said inmates told him any negotiator who returned without an
acceptable government offer would be taken hostage.
   ``They are criminals who killed people and committed that same
violent crime during the uprising,'' he told reporters in the
capital.
   Cerezo said, ``There was probably a certain sum of money paid in
the effort to gain access to the weapons and try a massive escape
in which prisoners convicted of drug trafficking would take part,
but that was frustrated. No prison guard personnel were involved in
the plot.''
   He said traffickers involved in a shipment of cocaine seized in
Amatique Bay in 1987 were part of the rebellion.
   Authorities disagreed whether visitors still inside were
hostages or were there to support and protect the rebels.
   Lopez said he considered most of them ``virtual hostages.''
   ``Though some are there by choice, the rebellious prisoners know
they (the family members) are their protection,'' he said. ``They
know that once they are gone, the armed forces could try to retake
the facility.''
   Carlos Ramos Moncada, inspector general of prisons, told The
Associated Press he believed the visitors stayed of their own free
will.
   Esmirla Cheti, 19, walked out Tuesday with her nephew Edgar, 13.
She said they were visiting a friend when the uprising began, and
stayed voluntarily.
   ``But we were also afraid about what might happen if we tried to
leave,'' she told reporters. ``We were going to leave last night,
but they (the prisoners) told us to wait until morning.''
</TEXT>
