<HEAD>Pentagon Fraud Toll: 13 Convictions Before Even the First Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private consultant who is a central
figure in the Pentagon contract fraud scandal is the 13th defendant
to plead guilty in the case before even the first trial is held.
   William A. Parkin, 65, admitted Monday in U.S. District Court
that he bribed a public official and conspired to defraud the
government. He was to have been one of five defendants next week in
the firing from a 33-month investigation that has
uncovered abuses in the Pentagon's $150-billion-a-year purchasing
system.
   Parkred at the court despite his hospitalization a week
ago becauseping pills.
   Parkin faces a maximum of 25 years in prison and fines of up to
$750,000 at his sentencing, which is scheduled for June 3. He has
agreed to cooperate in the e with prosecutors preparing for
the trial next Monday in which he was to have been a defendant.
   Parkin admitted that he bribed a Navy official, Stuart E.
Berlin, by chaing money to him in exchange forformation and
favors that might help the consultant's clients omillion-dollar contracts.
   Appearing subdued and speaking in a soft voice, Parkin told
Judge Claude Hilton that the charges against him wer accurate ``as
far as it pertains to me.'' His sentencing date is June 3.
   Parkin pleaded guilty to conspiracy to defraud the United States
and wire fraud in addition to the charge of bribing a public
official. In exchange for his pleas, the government dropped other
charges against him.
   U.S. Attorney Joseph Aronica said he was pleased wi
plea.
   On Friday, Berlin pleaded guilty, asd Teledyne Electronics of
Newbury Park, Calif.,mpany that had agreed to pay Parkin
$160,000 fog a contract.
   Teledyne Electronics, a division of Teledyne Industries,
actually turned oveabout $30,000 to Parkin between November 1985
and May 1988.
   Prosecutors said in court documents that Parkin and Teledyne
officials discussed having Parkin help the company obtain a $24
