<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 0135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     03-28 0821</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sugar Stops Salmonella in Chickens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laboratory experiments by Agriculture
Department scientists are raising hopes that contamination of
chickens by food poisoning organisms can be reduced by adding a bit
of sugar to their drinking water.
   The encouraging tests involved ordinary lactose _ milk sugar _
and another sugar from a Mediterranean plant.
   Preliminary results showed that the number of salmonella
bacteria in infected chickens can be reduced by 99.9 percent in a
significant number of the birds, for a cost of pennies a day, said
USDA biochemist John R. DeLoach of the Agricultural Research
Service, College Station, Texas.
   DeLoach said in a report issued here Monday that lactose and
D-mannose were added to the drinking water of chicks dosed with 100
million Salmonella typhirmurium bacteria.
   When the 10-day-old chicks were compared with birds that had
received the bacteria but no sugars, only 53 percent of the birds
on lactose and only 26 percent of those on D-mannose had any
salmonella bacteria, he said.
   ``It's not only important how many birds had salmonella, but how
many salmonella bacteria those birds had,'' DeLoach said. ``The
birds treated with either mannose or lactose had 99.9 percent fewer
salmonella than the control birds in those experiments.''
   Other sugars were tested, too, including glucose, sucrose from
cane sugar, and maltose, or malt sugar. After 10 days, all of the
bacteria-dosed birds on sucrose and glucose were infected, as were
90 percent of those treated with maltose.
   ``Lactose worked just as well as mannose, and the cost of
lactose in drinking water might be no more than two cents per
bird,'' DeLoach said. ``Right now, if the poultry producer put his
birds on D-mannose for 10 days, it would cost him 50 cents a bird.''
   The exact amount of bacterial contamination in poultry is
unclear, but USDA and private estimates have ranged from 35 percent
to 60 percent nationally. Salmonella and other organisms can be
spread when slaughtered birds are put through eviscerating machines
and their intestinal contents are spilled.
   DeLoach was part of a team studying salmonella at the agency's
veterinary toxicology research unit at College Station.
   D-mannose is produced naturally by the Fraxinus ornus plant
along the Mediterranean basin, the report said. The sugar _
seminose and carubinose _ is available commercially in the United
States. A sister compound, mannitol, has been used for years as a
stabilizer and preservative in pharmaceutical products.
   The report said D-mannose reduces the ability of salmonella
bacteria to settle in a chicken's intestines, forcing the organisms
to pass harmlessly out of the bird. Studies are still under way on
how lactose works.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of volunteers are needed again this
year to help farmers comply with new federal conservation
requirements, according to Agriculture Department officials.
   A record 8,222 volunteers helped the department's Soil
Conservation Service in the 1988 fiscal year that ended last Sept.
30, almost a fourfold increase from 2,223 the previous year.
   Wilson Scaling, chief of the agency, said Monday the unpaid
helpers will be recognized during National Volunteer Week, April
9-15.
   ``We're in the midst of one of the biggest conservation efforts
in history, and volunteers are playing a key role,'' he said.
   Scaling referred to provisions in the 1985 farm law requiring
farmers with highly erodible crop land to have a conservation plan
approved by the agency no later than Dec. 31, 1989, and to have it
implemented by Dec. 31, 1994.
   The volunteers, called the Earth Team by the agency, range from
college students to retired people. They're used for a variety of
jobs, including design and layout of conservation practices on
individual farms, educational activities, and computer and general
office assistance.
   Scaling said anyone interested in joining the program can call a
toll-free number, 1-800-THE SOIL to find out more information, or
they can contact local SCS offices, which are located in nearly all
counties.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has set up a gene
and data bank for shrubs and other woody landscape plants at the
national aboretum here.
   Arboretum director H. Marc Cathey said Monday that plant
researchers and nurseries will use the bank to find and obtain
landscape specimens at other arboretums and nurseries around the
country _ as well as in the national arboretum.
   Cathey also said that collections of plants at the 444-acre
arboretum will be expanded as part of a new national woody
landscape plant repository. A computer bank will make it easier to
develop new and better specimens.
   The new repository is the first of its kind at the national
level, he said. The arboretum is operated by the department's
Agricultural Research Service.
   Cathey said public interest in gardening has expanded rapidly
since 1978, including an increase of almost a third in the sales of
landscape plants. Those sales were estimated at more than $7
billion last year.
