<FIRST>u a AM-LivingInSin     03-28 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Living In Sin,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Council Amends `Living-in-Sin' Zoning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Denver City Council voted Monday to loosen its
``living-in-sin'' zoning law so that unrelated people could legally
live together in family-zoned areas.
   The council voted 8-5 to initially approval to plans to change
two types of zoning: R-0, which bans boarders or unrelated people
from living in the same house and R-1, which allows a boarder with
a city permit.
   The changes would allow two unrelated people plus close
relatives, with some exceptions, to live together in areas zoned
R-0 and would permit one boarder, related or unrelated, without a
city permit.
   About 60 percent of the city 505,000 people live under R-1
zoning and 7 percent fall under R-0.
   The changes in the so-called ``living-in-sin'' law come up for
second and final action April 24.
   The amended laws would still forbid nieces, nephews, aunts,
uncles and in-laws from living together, said City Councilwoman
Cathy Donohue.
   ``Right now you have to carry your marriage certificate in your
pocket in Denver,'' Donohue said before the vote.
   ``There are some people who go around and deliberately turn
other people in,'' she said. ``There is even one real estate agent
who sells houses based on the current law, telling buyers that no
one can move in next to them that isn't married. This appeals
particularly to families.''
   The penalty for violating the city's ordinance is $999 a day. In
many cases, if a person is turned in to authorities and owns the
house, they have to sell the house, often at a losss, Donohue said.
   Donohue said families and one real estate agent are the main
opponents of change.
   Among those affected by the ordinance are three nuns, who are
being forced to move out of a four-bedroom home.
   ``They wanted all but one of us to move out,'' said one of the
nuns, who asked that her name not be used. ``To me, it's wasteful
to have just one person living in a dwelling with four bedrooms.
It's very sinful.''
   The ban dates back to the 1960s when home owners in some of
Denver's most exclusive neighborhoods feared invasion by hippie
communes.
   So far, hundreds of people have violated the ordinance,
including the Mexican consul, students sharing expenses, and
unmarried couples.
   The law is being challenged in court.
</TEXT>
