<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-Soviet     03-28 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Soviet,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Ponders New Plan for Soviet Bloc</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is cautiously
considering a proposal to seek discussions with the Soviet Union on
a new political arrangement for Eastern Europe, according to The
New York Times.
   Under the proposal, Moscow would loosen its hold on the region
in exchange for a pledge by the United States and its NATO allies
not to exploit the new environment in a way threatening to the
Soviet Union, Secretary of State James A. Baker III said in an
interview published Tuesday.
   The idea, first broached by former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger, was being addressed as part of Baker's overall strategic
policy review, which is to be completed by the beginning of May,
the Times said.
   ``I think it is worthy of consideration because it is a novel
approach,'' Baker said during the interview at his State Department
office in Washington.
   ``I think it is important that any such idea, to the extent that
it is going to be pursued, be pursued carefully, so that you do not
send a signal that somehow we are getting together with the Soviet
Union and carving up Eastern Europe,'' he added.
</TEXT>
