<FIRST>r a AM-Evangelists-Prostitution 1stLd-WritethruL   03-28 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Evangelists-Prostitution, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0699,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leyva Sentenced To Maximum 20 Years For Running Boy Sex Ring</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Turk sentenced ...,' to CORRECT defendant's
name to Rias, sted Ries.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY O'DELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge sentenced an evangelist who
admitted guilt in a child sex ring to 20 years, calling the man and
his two partners in the case ``bad to the core.''
   ``Everyone who ever heard you out there (on the revival circuit)
ought to kick you good,'' U.S. District Judge James Turk told
evangelist Mario ``Tony'' Leyva, 42.
   The remark prompted cheers from the courtroom audience, which
included some of the victims and their families.
   Turk sentenced Rias Edward Morris, 47, an organist for the Tony
Leyva Evangelistic Association of Columbus, Ga., to 15 years in
prison, and Freddie H. Herring, 50, of the Lighthouse Assembly in
Douglasville, Ga., to 12 years in prison. All three men were fined
$5,000.
   The three pleaded guilty last year to interstate transportation
of boys for prostitution. Morris and Leyva also pleaded guilty to
conspiracy to transport the boys.
   Leyva and Morris each received the maximum sentence; Herring's
sentence was three years short of the maximum. Leyva already is
serving a 2{-year sentence on state charges of sexually abusing two
boys in Salem.
   Turk told the defendants at sentencing that he saw no redeeming
qualities in any of them. ``All three of you, in the court's
opinion, are just bad to the core,'' the judge said.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Jennie Montgomery said the men procured
the boys during their travels along the revival circuit, using
their influence over the boys' families.
   Since pleading guilty, the three have been at a federal prison
hospital for child sexual abusers in Butner, N.C., for evaluations.
Three psychologist from the hospital told the court that the
evangelists had been diagnosed as pedophiles and suffered from
other personality disorders.
   One of youths, who was 15 at the time of the molestations,
testified at the sentencing that he had been sexually abused by all
three men. The Roanoke County man, who is now 21, said he remains
haunted by the experience. He said he has nightmares, wakes up in a
cold sweat and has suffered family problems and from drug addiction.
   ``I try to forget, but I just can't,'' he said.
   William H. Gray, a Roanoke psychiatrist who has treated four of
the victims, testified that all showed signs of depression and some
had attempted suicide. He said the victims find it difficult to be
intimate and honest with others.
   Ms. Montgomery said Leyva had sexual relations with at least 30
boys, some as young as 8, over the last 20 years. The boys either
attended Leyva's services or were brought there by their mothers,
Ms. Montgomery said.
   Ms. Montgomery said 11 juveniles were victimized by Morris and
nine by Herring.
   All three defendants apologized for their actions. When asked by
Turk why he had committed the crimes, Herring was unable to answer.
</TEXT>
