<SECOND>AM-Dead Marines,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>19 Victims Of Korean Crash Returned To U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SC1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRAVIS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of 18 Marines
and a Navy corpsman killed in a helicopter crash in South Korea
were returned to the United States on Monday as a band played ``The
Marine Hymn.''
   A chaplain prayed and an honor guard made up of Navy and Marine
personnel and about 150 Air Force members watched as black-gloved
Marine pallbearers removed caskets from a C-141 cargo jet and
placed them in hearses.
   ``It was a very moving ceremony,'' said Maj. Gen. John P.
Monahan. ``It's been a tough week at Camp Pendleton.''
   Most of the Marines killed were from Camp Pendleton in Southern
California, according to a Marine spokesman, Gunnery Sgt. Stan
Pederson.
   The bodies were taken to a military mortuary in nearby Oakland,
where they were to be turned over to relatives.
   The 19 were killed March 20 when a CH-53D helicopter carrying 34
military personnel crashed in a rugged mountain area about 250
miles southeast of Seoul. It was the second fatal crash of a Marine
helicopter in South Korea in four days.
   Four Marines were killed earlier when a CH-46 helicopter crashed
in a rice paddy.
   Both helicopters were participating in ``Team Spirit,'' the
annual joint U.S.-South Korean military maneuvers.
