<HEAD>Twenty Stowaways Found On Barges Returning From Jamaica</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty Jamaicans who apparently stowed away
on grain barges were discovered after a week, and the Immigration
and Naturalization Service said it wasn't sure if the refugees had
consumed any food or water.
   The tug American Eagle radioed the Coast Guard Sunday night to
report stowaways on two barges, which had delivered corn to Jamaica.
   ``It appears they had been there about seven days,'' said INS
spokesman Russ Bergeron.
   The 18 men and two teen-agers were taken to the New Orleans INS
office Monday for processing.
   INS District Director John B.Z. Caplinger said the men would be
arraigned on stowing away charges. The boys, who appeared to be
about 16 or 17 years old, will not be prosecuted, he said.
   Bergeron and Caplinger said they did not know if the stowaways
had eaten or had water since leaving Jamaica.
   ``I would imagine there must be some grain aboard the barges,''
said Caplinger.
   The refugees appeared weak when they were turned over to the
INS, officials said.
