<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Spokeswoman Admits Limited Policy Expertise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new State Department spokeswoman admits
she's not an expert in foreign policy and is asking reporters'
``patience and understanding.''
   ``As you all know, I am not, and do not claim to be, an expert
in foreign policy,'' Margaret Tutwiler said, reading a statement at
the start of Monday's daily State Department briefing.
   ``But I do claim to have a fair amount of experience in working
with the press, and I do know this president and this secretary of
state very well,'' she added.
   Ms. Tutwiler, 38, served as Secretary of State James A. Baker's
spokeswoman when he was treasury secretary in the Reagan
administration and worked for George Bush when he made his
unsuccessful bid for the Republican presidential nomination in 1980.
   Ms. Tutwiler, who is considered one of Baker's closest advisers,
was confirmed by the Senate earlier this month. She has a tough act
to follow in her job as assistant secretary of state for public
affairs.
   Her predecessor, Charles Redman, is a career foreign service
officer with experience in U.S. diplomatic posts overseas. Redman,
who has been nominated ambassador to Sweden, enjoyed close ties
with former Secretary of State George P. Shultz and was adept at
handling the department's press corps.
