<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A little critter that's been dead for
300 million years is being given new life in the Illinois General
Assembly.
   Lawmakers this session are pondering a measure to designate the
prehistoric animal called the Tullimonstrom gregarium _ known
unofficially as the Tully monster _ as the state's official fossil.
   ``The thing that's significant about the Tully monster is that
it's indigenous to Illinois,'' said Rep. Larry Wennlund.
   ``If you look at the other state symbols _ the cardinal,
violets, even the monarch butterfly _ they can be found all over
the country,'' he said.
   The Tully monster is named for Lockport pipefitter Francis
Tully, who discovered its fossilized remains in 1958 among slag
heaps south of Braidwood, about 55 miles southwest of Chicago.
   Tully died two years ago, but his son, Dan, said it would be a
``tremendous honor'' to have his father's discovery recognized by
the state.
   The Tully monster grew to about 1long, had a tube-like body with
a spade-shaped tail and sported two tentacle-like sensors or eyes
and a snout that of an elephant.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's a bird! It's a plane! It's a ...
blimp?
   At first glance, the senior desi Tennessee at Chattanooga's
School of Engineering doesn't look revolutionary.
   The students' 28-foot blimp looks like a mini-version of the
Goodyear model that's been honas since before the first Super Bowl.
   But they say their project could save money for utilities like
Chattanooga's Electric Power Board as a way to monitor power lines
for heat loss and other problemde of garbage-bag plastic hung on a
balsa and plywood frame, the blimp is powered by two radio-ntrolled
motors. An infrared camera near the front base, also red, surveys
power lines for about a third of the cost of helicopters, said Jan
ns, assistant engineering profe project coordinator.
   The blimp gets its first test Thursday when the students will
check its flying, turnpeed capabilities.
   ``If it n't work, we've got to make it wsaid Greg Phillips, a
civil engineering major. ``They have told us we won't grduate if it
doesn't work.
   `on't know if they were joking or they were serious. ... So,
yes, it will fly.''
