<FIRST>r w PM-BarryLoan     03-28 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barry Loan,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethics Official Reportedly Concludes Mayor Violated Disclosure Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia's chief ethics
official has concluded that Mayor Marion Barry violated a financial
disclosure law by failing to report a real estate partnership, a
newspaper reported today.
   The Washington Post quoted sources as saying that Marianne
Coleman Niles, who directs the city's campaign finance office, has
determined that Barry should be fined for failing to report the
deal with developer Jeffrey Cohen.
   The paper said Ms. Niles has concluded that a promissory note
the mayor signed in 1985 when he purchased an interest in a
Nantucket, Mass., building amounts to an interest-free loan.
   Barry has recently been dogged by reports concerning the city's
skyrocketing murder rate and controversy in December after he
visited the district hotel room of a man, Charles Lewis, later
charged with selling cocaine in the Virgin Islands. Barry has
repeatedly denied using drugs or having any knowledge about any
possible involvement with drugs by Lewis.
   The Post said the mayor's legal counsel, Herbert O. Reid Sr.,
did not say whether Barry would agree to the sanctions and
emphasized that the mayor did not knowingly violate any law.
   District law requires top city officials to annually disclose
any liability of more than $1,000 that they owe to anyone other
than a family member or financial or credit institution.
   Barry could face a maximum penalty of $1,500 because he did not
report the deal on his 1986, 1987 or 1988 disclosure forms. Each
violation is punishable by a $500 fine.
   Barry's share in the building is held under the name of investor
Israel Kogan, a local obstetrician. Kogan and Barry hold an
unregistered partnership called KB Associates.
   Under the terms of the note, the mayor is required to pay
$49,000 over 10 years for a 10-percent interest in the building.
The building, valued at $1 million, is owned by Barry, Cohen and
seven others.
   When asked why his interest in the real estate deal was hidden,
Barry said, ``I was advised by my lawyers and (accountants) to
handle it that way.''
</TEXT>
