<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua     03-28 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Urges U.S. Congress To Reconsider Contra Aid Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega denounced the
U.S. government for deciding to give the Contra rebels more
non-lethal aid, saying it should instead support regional leaders'
plan to dismantle rebel forces.
   Later Monday, the Defense Ministry said rebels attacked a
military truck in the country's north. It reported two guerrillas
and one soldier killed in the Sunday attack in El Jicote Valley,
near the Honduran border.
   Ortega, speaking to 60 Harvard scholars from 37 countries,
accused the United States of ignoring a Central American peace plan
that commits regional leaders to draft a program by mid-May to
demobilize Contra forces.
   Speaking of the proposed U.S. aid package, the leftist
Sandinista leader said: ``What they're trying to do is maintain
intact a force in Honduran territory, which is like a cannon aimed
at Nicaragua.
   ``The president of Honduras himself has insisted he has not
agreed that the Contras remain for another 10 months or a year,''
he said.
   Ortega said the U.S. decision to continue funding the Contras
``reaffirms once again the policy that the strongest can act
without regard for the will of others.''
   The Nicaraguan rebels are based in Honduras, where the
government, though allied to Washington, has been increasingly
trying to remove them.
   The U.S. proposal, worked out between the Bush administration
and bipartisan congressional leaders and unveiled Friday in
Washington, would provide $4.5 million a month in non-military aid
to the Contras.
   The current $27.1 million in humanitarian aid runs out Friday.
   The new package proposes aid at least through November and could
continue through February, when Ortega has promised to hold general
elections.
   The U.S. government cut off military aid to the Contras early
last year.
   ``If the U.S. Congress were respectful of our (regional) accord,
it would approve aid for 90 days and gear it to the dismantling of
the Contras,'' Ortega told the gathering of Mason Fellowship
scholars, who were in Nicaragua on a one-day visit.
   Ortega moved up general elections in Nicaragua by 10 months as
part of the regional peace plan he and the presidents of El
Salvador, Honduras, Guatemala and Costa Rica reached in El Salvador
on Feb. 14.
   The plan calls for dismantling the Contras in return for greater
democracy in Nicaragua.
   The presidents agreed to come up with a plan by mid-May to
demobilize up to 11,000 Contras living in Honduran jungle camps
near Nicaragua with about 12,000 relatives.
   They have been battling the government for eight years but most
fled to Honduras after the Contras and Sandinistas signed a
preliminary cease-fire agreement one year ago.
   President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica told a news conference in
San Jose on Monday that the proposed U.S. aid package could help
bring peace to the region. Arias won the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize for
a peace plan that called for amnesties and an end to civil wars in
the region, a plan that eventually evolved into the accords signed
in February.
</TEXT>
