<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 0554EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Koreas     03-28 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Koreas,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: South Korean Dissident Meets With North's Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite strong protests from the Seoul
government, a South Korean dissident has met with North Korean
leader Kim Il Sung to discuss reuniting the two countries,
according to reports today.
   Rev. Moon Ik-hwan had lunch Monday with the communist leader in
Pyongyang and they discussed ways to end the division of the Korean
peninsula, according to South Korea's official Naewoe Press, which
reports on North Korea.
   Moon's visit has provoked a massive controversy in South Korea.
Government officials say he is serving North Korean interests and
attempting to subvert South Korean policy.
   His visit has fueled demands from government hardliners for a
crackdown on South Korea's dissident groups. Government prosecutors
in Seoul said Monday that Moon will be prosecuted for aiding the
communist north if he returns home.
   South Koreans cannot visit the north without government
permission.
   Kim Il Sung thanked Moon for supporting his call for ``political
negotiation talks'' on reuniting the two Koreas, Naewoe said.
   ``I express my all out support to the democratic figures from
all walks of life in South Korea fighting under difficult
circumstances for self-reliant and democratic reunification,'' Kim
was quoted as saying.
   The North Korean leader said he was determined to realize his
plan of reuniting the two nations in a confederation under which
they would retain control of their internal affairs
   Moon's secret visit came right after President Roh Tae-woo
ordered a major crackdown on dissidents and radical students he
charged were trying to stage a leftist revolution. Roh cited the
threat in justifying his decision March 20 to postpone indefinitely
a promised referendum on his performance.
   South Korean dissident groups are calling for Roh's overthrow,
but they have little support and are not seen as a major threat
despite a recent spate of violent anti-government protests.
   Police seized more than 3,000 copies of pro-North Korean books
and arrested 11 publishers in raids Monday night in Seoul as part
of Roh's order to suppress leftist groups, prosecutors said.
   Many ordinary South Koreans were critical of Moon's visit,
charging the dissident leader was playing into the hands of the
totalitarian north.
   Kim Il Sung ordered the North Korean invasion in 1950 that
started the bloody three-year Korean War. Kim rules what is widely
regarded as one of the world's most repressive police states.
   North Korea often claims the Seoul government is a U.S. backed
military dictatorship with no public support and attempts to have
independent contacts with dissidents to help ``liberate'' the south.
   Leading South Korean newspapers charged in editorials today that
the north was trying to undermine the Seoul government by
supporting dissidents to incite opposition and eventual revolution.
   ``It is once again proven that North Korea is sticking to its
long standing policy of conquering the south through revolution,''
said the conservative Kyunghyang Shinmun.
   The two Koreas have been holding talks on improving relations,
but have made little progress. The Seoul government says only it
can handle contacts with the north.
   The Korean peninsula was divided by U.S. and Soviet forces that
ended the Japanese occupation at the end of World War II. Separate
countries were formed in 1948 and they have clashed repeatedly over
the years.
</TEXT>
