<FIRST>r a PM-DoctorSlain     03-28 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Doctor Slain,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smith Says Doctor Might Still Be Alive If He Had Received Psychiatric
Help</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note Contents. Hearing resumes at 9:30 a.m. EST</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former mental patient charged with raping and
strangling a pregnant doctor told police the woman ``looked like a
real lady'' and it was ``just something I had to do.''
   Steven Smith described in a taped confession played at a
pretrial hearing Monday how he posed as a doctor and, along with a
man he calls ``John,'' strangled Dr. Kathryn Hinnant with an
electrical cord on Jan. 7. Police say John doesn't exist.
   Smith, 23, is charged with the crimes that took place in
Hinnant's office at Bellevue Hospital. Hinnant, 33, was five months
pregnant.
   In the videotape, Smith said that if he had received psychiatric
help earlier, ``the lady would be alive today.''
   ``I did it on purpose ... left evidence so I could get caught
and get help,'' Smith said.
   Smith, who authorities have said secretly slept in an unused
area on the hospital's 22nd floor, told police was able to approach
Hinnant by presenting himself as a doctor, Detective David Argenzio
testified.
   The detective said Smith recalled that when he knocked on the
doctor's office door and entered, she was wearing a red dress.
``Her hair was nice; she looked like a real lady. ... It's just
something I had to do,'' he quoted Smith as saying.
   Argenzio said Smith claimed ``John'' hit Hinnant in the face,
causing extensive bleeding.
   Smith said there was ``so much blood my hands slipped off the
electric cord twice.''
   ``While I'm doing my thing (robbing and stripping the body),
John all of a sudden wants to get sexy, and John makes love to the
lady.''
   Although Smith has admitted helping to kill Hinnant on the
videotape and in other statements, he has insisted that ``John''
raped her.
   Smith's lawyer, Marvyn Kornberg, told state Supreme Court
Justice James Leff that the confession was obtained illegally and
shouldn't be allowed as evidence.
   Kornberg said police knew Smith faced charges in an unrelated
case and he shouldn't have been questioned without a lawyer present.
   Smith is being held at a hospital under a suicide watch.
</TEXT>
