<FIRST>r a PM-Spy'sWife     03-28 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spy's Wife,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spy's Wife Asks Judge To Move Her From Prison Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of convicted spy Jonathan Pollard
says she is isolated and mistreated at a federal prison hospital
where she is the only female inmate and that she should be
transferred.
   ``I'm hated by administrative and medical personnel,'' Anne
Henderson Pollard told Judge Harry MacLaughlin.
   ``I feel I've been in segregation the two months I've been
there,'' said Pollard, who weighs less than 100 pounds and appeared
frail and in pain during Monday's hearing.
   Pollard is serving two concurrent five-year prison terms on
charges related to her husband's spying. Jonathan Pollard, 34, was
sentenced in 1987 to life in prison for supplying classified
documents to Israeli agents.
   Pollard, 28, and her lawyers argued that she should be
transferred to a federal prison camp in Danbury, Conn., which they
said would be less stressful. They said her medical condition,
which includes a gastro-intestinal disorder, is worsening at the
Federal Medical Center in Rochester.
   U.S. Magistrate Janice Symchych has recommended that MacLaughlin
deny Pollard's request.
   Assistant U.S. District Attorney Robert Small argued that
Rochester was the best place to treat Pollard's medical problems.
He said the woman has made herself sicker by limiting her intake of
food and water.
   The prison hospital placed Pollard under 24-hour surveillance to
monitor her food intake, but the surveillance has been lifted.
   Pollard told MacLaughlin that the surveillance was ``the most
stressful and humiliating event I have ever undergone.''
   ``I could not sleep. I could not even have the dignity of going
to the toilet without someone watching me,'' she said.
   Pollard said she wants to return to the women's prison in
Danbury to be closer to her family. She began serving her sentence
at that facility in March 1987.
   The judge said he expected to rule on the request, which was
made in a lawsuit, next week.
</TEXT>
