<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0476,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS dollar-yen closing figure in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in quiet early European trading
today following the Easter holiday weekend. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign currency dealers said that, barring any unexpected
events, they expect the dollar to trade in a narrow range all week.
   Currency movements will be dampened by anticipation of the
meeting of finance ministers and central bankers from the Group of
Seven industrialized nations, they said.
   That meeting is scheduled to be held during an International
Monetary Fund meeting starting Friday in Washington.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.60 yen to a closing 132.90. Later, in
London, it was quoted at the same rate.
   Other dollar rates in London at midmorning, compared with late
Friday's rates in Europe:
   _1.8843 West German marks, up from 1.8733
   _1.6450 Swiss francs, up from 1.6252
   _6.3715 French francs, up from 6.3350
   _2.1239 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1138
   _1,381.20 Italian lire, up from 1,376.10
   _1.1935 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1895
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7005, cheaper for buyers
than late Friday's European quote of $1.7190.
   Bullion markets were closed in Europe on Good Friday and Easter
Monday.
   London's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price
for gold at midmorning Tuesday of $391.25 a troy ounce, unchanged
from the opening bid but down from $394.75 bid late Thursday.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $391.25, down from $395.00 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $3.50 to close at a bid $392.64.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.97 a troy
ounce, down from Thursday's $6.08.
</TEXT>
