<FIRST>r a PM-Doctor-Fraud     03-28 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Doctor-Fraud,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Cancer Doctor To Remain in Country</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge told a physician who specializes
in cancer treatment that he can't go to Switzerland where he faces
fraud charges because a patient might die if the doctor leaves.
   U.S. District Judge Sol Blatt Jr. on Monday ordered Dr. Rajko D.
Medenica to surrender his U.S. passport.
   The doctor, who has clinics on Hilton Head Island and in
Switzerland, is scheduled to stand trial next month in Switzerland
on fraud charges, authorities said.
   During the hearing, Medenica, represented by attorney F. Lee
Bailey, said he wanted to return to Switzerland to clear his name.
He said he is innocent of the fraud charges, which stem from
changes that were made in records at his Swiss clinic.
   Medenica has developed an unusual cancer treatment that uses the
drug interferon to treat tumors.
   One of Medenica's cancer patients, Charles E. Stevinson of
Colorado, filed suit to keep Medenica in the United States,
contending that he would die if the doctor were imprisoned abroad.
   Several other of Medenica's cancer patients also testified,
including Richard Walker of Columbia, a former ambassador to South
Korea.
   Bailey said his father-in-law has been treated by Medenica as
well.
</TEXT>
