<FIRST>r a PM-Hatcher     03-28 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hatcher,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Charge Dropped; Extradition Fight Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indian activist charged with taking
hostages in a North Carolina newsroom last year can fight
extradition now that a federal charge against him has been dropped.
   A federal magistrate on Monday dismissed a charge of unlawful
flight against Eddie Hatcher and turned him over to authorities to
begin extradition proceedings.
   Hatcher's lawyers said they would seek his release on bail and
try to deny extradition to North Carolina. Hatcher has said his
life would be in danger if he is returned to North Carolina, where
he has accused law enforcement authorities of corruption.
   Hatcher also contends he should not be tried on state charges
since he has been acquitted of federal hostage charges for the same
incident.
   Monday's hearing was to determine whether Hatcher should be
returned to North Carolina on the federal charge or to drop the
charge and begin extradition proceedings on the state charges in
California.
   Hatcher, 31, and Timothy Jacobs, 20, both Tuscarora Indians,
have been accused of holding up to 20 people hostage for 10 hours
in February 1988, in the offices of The Robesonian newspaper in
Lumberton, N.C.
   A state task force said their claims of corrupt law enforcement
officials were unfounded.
   In December, the two were indicted on state kidnapping charges.
   Jacobs, arrested in New York state, was returned to North
Carolina last week. A judge in Lumberton has set his bail at
$100,000.
   Hatcher was arrested in San Francisco three weeks ago after
unsuccessfully seeking political asylum in the Soviet consulate. He
is being held without bail.
</TEXT>
