<DOCNO> AP890328-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 0813EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SchoolDesegregation     03-28 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Desegregation,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>NAACP Lawsuit Over Los Angeles Schools Ends</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NAACP has abandoned an 8-year-old
desegregation lawsuit against the nation's second-largest school
district.
   NAACP attorney Joseph Duff said Monday the group cannot afford
to pursue the case and does not have enough time to assemble
evidence to prove its allegations of racial inequities in the
595,000-student school system.
   ``I don't think there's any failure with the substance of the
case,'' Duff said.
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
remains convinced that local government, with the acquiescence of
the state, established segregated neighborhoods and schools, he
said.
   At the NAACP's request, U.S. District Judge A. Wallace Tashima
on Monday dropped the last defendants in the class-action lawsuit _
the state, its Education Department and school superintendent. The
district was dropped in January.
   Duff argued that local government fostered segregation by
concentrating public housing in black areas, requiring children to
attend schools in their neighborhoods and steering black teachers
toward primarily black schools.
   He said the state was at fault for failing to prevent such
decisions.
   Deputy Attorney General Samuel Overton said racial inequities
were the result of private housing patterns rather than government
activity.
   ``There are certainly racially isolated schools ... (but) it's
not because somebody has made a conscious decision to make them
that way, not someone in government,'' he said. ``There's certainly
private discrimination that takes place every day, certainly in the
housing market.''
   Of the district's students, 59 percent are Hispanic, 16.7
percent black, 15.8 percent white, 5.9 percent Asian, 1.9 percent
Filipino, and less than 1 percent are Pacific islanders or native
Americans.
   The NAACP sued in 1981, two years after a state ballot measure
overturned a court-imposed busing plan.
   The group had sought new education programs for minorities, more
aid to minority schools with the lowest achievement records and
smaller classes in minority schools.
   Since 1980, the state has given the district $1 billion toward
mandatory and voluntary desegregation programs, Overton said. The
district still buses thousands of students a day in voluntary
programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
