<FIRST>r a PM-PublishedApologies     03-28 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Published Apologies,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Drunk Drivers To Place Photos, Apologies in Local Papers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drunken drivers are being forced to
publicly acknowledge their sins by putting their photo and an
apology in the newspaper.
   Indian River County Court Judge Joe Wild has been ordering
first-time offenders to place the ads since February. The first
appeared on Friday, and 13 more are to follow.
   Wild still fines offenders, suspends their licenses and requires
them to take driving classes but goes one step further, making them
publish the message, ``I apologize to all the people of this
community for driving impaired over the streets of Indian River
County.''
   The judge said the message makes the community aware of what can
happen to those who drink and drive.
   But lawyer Bob Pegg, who often handles drunken driving cases,
said the ads could ``sentence a guy to financial ruin'' by
affecting businesses and reputations.
</TEXT>
