<FIRST>u a PM-PitBulls 1stLd-Writethru a0504 03-28 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pit Bulls, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0504,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board of Health Outlaws New Pit Bull Dogs in City</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RESTORES `be' to 3rd graf, `All such ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City has all but banned pit bulls.
   The Board of Health on Monday adopted regulations barring any
new pit bull terriers from being brought into the city after Oct. 1
and requiring current owners to obtain hard-to-get liability
insurance of at least $100,000.
   All such dogs must be registered; spayed or neutered; identified
by photographs and tattoos, and muzzled and kept on a leash in
public. In addition, owners of pit bulls must post warning signs at
home.
   Only Lloyd's of London offers such insurance policies, and it
charges $3,000, said ASPCA spokesman Jeffrey Hon.
   ``No insurance company will give (coverage) for any price,''
said Mordecai Siegel, president of the Society of New York Dog
Trainers. ``Anyone with a pit bull will be forced to give it up.''
   Unregistered pit bulls could be seized and their owners fined up
to $500 a day, said Health Department spokesman Barry Adkins.
   Pit bull terriers were bred long ago to battle bulls for sport.
They have been known to attack people without warning or
provocation.
   ``After October 1,'' Adkins said, ``there will be no pit bulls
allowed into New York City. This will lead to the grandfathering
out of all pit bulls. Eventually, there will come a time when there
will be no pit bulls in New York City.''
   Adkins said that, ``by rigorously controlling pit bulls, the law
seeks to prevent serious bites by these animals before they occur,
thereby protecting the public health.''
   He guessed pit bulls would be gone from the city in 12 to 16
years.
   City Health Commissioner Dr. Stephen Joseph said in January that
while pit bulls are estimated to account for only 2 percent of the
total city dog population, they are responsible for close to 14
percent of all reported bites.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
