<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-Liepa     03-28 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Liepa,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ballet Dancer Dies of Heart Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maris Liepa, the Bolshoi Ballet star known for his
glamour and charisma on stage and off, has died of a heart attack.
   The dancer died Saturday at age 52, the official Tass news
agency said.
   Liepa created the role of Crassus, the Roman tyrant in
``Spartacus,'' Yuri Grigorovich's ballet based on a 1968 score by
Khachaturian. He also danced leading roles in ``Swan Lake,''
``Sleeping Beauty,'' ``Raymonda,'' ``Les Sylphides,'' ``Don
Quixote,'' and ``Romeo and Juliet.''
   In his book, ``Yesterday and Today in Ballet,'' Liepa wrote:
``We give all our physical and spiritual powers so that our art,
transformed into ourselves, would influence people's hearts and
minds.''
   Liepa began dancing professionally in 1955 with the Latvian
Opera and Ballet Theater. He later moved to Moscow's Stanislavsky
and Nemirovich-Danchenko Musical Theater and finally joined the
city's Bolshoi Ballet.
   Twenty-six years ago, Liepa began teaching ballet, and this year
he worked on setting up his own ballet troupe. His daughter, Ilze,
and son, Andris, have distinguished themselves as ballet dancers.
</TEXT>
