<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0502 03-28 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0502,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Switch Gears After Attacks Stall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs ``Casualty reports...'' to give number of
insurgents reported killed.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem insurgents said today they set
up a military committee to revamp their strategy in the battle for
Afghanistan's eastern city of Jalalabad.
   The move came after an Afghan government official said Monday
the three-week guerrilla attack around Jalalabad was collapsing and
the rest of the country was quiet.
   ``There has been terrible coordination in Jalalabad,''
acknowledged a guerrilla source today, speaking on condition of
anonomity.
   He said the guerrillas' strength lies in harassment, not
launching a conventional attack on an urban center. To return the
Jalalabad fight to a hit-and-run battle, he said ``would be a
better strategy.''
   Western diplomats, who also spoke on condition of anonymity,
today reported a lull in battle for control of Jalalabad. A
guerrilla victory would give the insurgents control of their first
major city and provide a base for the interim government they
elected Feb. 23 in Pakistan.
   The diplomats said the fighting had dropped off because the
U.S.-backed insurgents are trying to coordinate their military
strategy.
   However, the insurgents are also moving more supplies toward the
battlefront and trying to negotiate the surrender of government
troops, diplomats said.
   Casualty reports in the fight for Jalalabad have varied widely.
Official government sources put the guerrilla death count at more
than 4,000. Guerrillas and Western sources said about 300
insurgents have died and another 900 have been injured.
   Mohammad Nabi Amani, the Foreign Ministry spokesman in the
Afghan capital of Kabul, said 190 guerrillas were killed between
Sunday night and Monday night. He said two government soldiers and
three civilians also died.
   Amani said guerrillas fired 250 rockets and shells at Jalalabad
during that time, compared with 12,000 in the previous 24 hours.
   ``We're of the opinion that they are drawing a conclusion that
they cannot achieve any success through military means,'' he said
of the guerrillas.
   In Islamabad, Pakistan, a guerrilla group claimed 53 soldiers
were killed and five aircraft shot down in weekend fighting around
Jalalabad.
   The guerrillas launched their offensive on Jalalabad March 6. At
its peak the fighting, was said to be the heaviest in the
decade-long war.
   The insurgents have been fighting the Afghan government since
1978. The Soviet Union, which sent troops into Afghanistan in
December 1979 to support the Moscow-allied government, withdrew the
last of its soldiers Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
