<FIRST>r w PM-DoubleTransplant 2ndLd-Writethru a0462 03-28 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Double Transplant, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0462,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hospital Scolded for Performing Unapproved Heart-Pancreas Transplant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs 6th graf, ``When he,'' with 5 grafs to update with
doctor's comments, give details on survival chances and edit reference
to Macoviak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   District health officials have asked the
Washington Hospital Center to sign an agreement that essentially
admits doctors violated the law by performing a heart-pancreas
transplant without city approval.
   The agreement requires the hospital to set up procedures to
prevent a violation from happening again.
   ``The important thing to do is reestablish the rules. If there
is another violation, I'm not sure we'll be so lenient,'' said
Carolyn Graham, acting director of the District of Columbia's State
Health Planning Agency. She said the city could have sought
financial penalties against the hospital.
   Surgeons at the hospital performed a combined heart-pancreas
transplant Saturday on Barry Katz, 45, of Silver Spring, Md., the
first time such a procedure has been successfully performed in the
United States.
   Katz's doctors argued that they had to go ahead with the
transplant to save the patient's life. Katz was reported in serious
condition following the operation.
   Katz, whose heart was deteriorating, also suffers from diabetes,
which is caused by a defective pancreas. The one-year survival rate
for recipients of pancreas transplants has been estimated at 50
percent.
   On the ``CBS This Morning'' program, one of Katz's physicians,
Dr. John A. Macoviak, said the Defense Department physicist was
feeling better today.
   ``He yelled at me, `I feel lousy, now get me out of bed,'''
Macoviak said.
   The physician added that Katz has not had any insulin for 48
hours. ``We're hoping that we will learn a lot about this disease
diabetes from patients like Dr. Barry Katz,'' he said.
   ``When he got here (March 17) he was deteriorating,'' Macoviak
said Monday. ``His condition did not give us the luxury of time to
consider this.'' Hospital officials were not immediately available
for comment.
   The city has yet to act on an emergency application the hospital
filed late Thursday for permission to perform pancreas transplants.
The hospital has approval to perform heart transplants.
</TEXT>
