<FIRST>r a PM-HighTemperatures     03-28 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High Temperatures,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mini Heat Wave Bring Spring Break North</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Convertible owners put their tops down to watch a sneak preview
of summer as Florida-style temperatures reached Michigan, Ohio and
West Virginia today.
   ``It's not normal,'' National Weather Service meterologist Jerry
Orchanian in Charleston, W.Va., said this morning of the 84
degree-reading there Monday and the record-tying 86 forecast for
today. ``Usually we're in the 60s at this time of year, for example
yesterday was about 24 degrees above normal.''
   He credited warm air from the Gulf of Mexico, and said a cold
front will cause temperatures to drop and rain to fall Wednesday.
   A stalled cold front that blocked cool air from entering
Michigan from the south produced temperatures as high as 62 at
Grand Rapids and 59 at Detroit at 5 a.m. today, forecaster Dick
Wagenmaker said.
   In Michigan, Lansing and Flint had record-tying 78-degree
readings Monday, while the same high in Detroit brought tops down
on convertibles and lured joggers outdoors.
   Akron, Ohio, and Norfolk, Va., had 79 and Washington reached 74,
the weather service reported. Forecasters predicted 81-degree highs
today for Norfolk and Washington.
   Columbus and Akron, Ohio, were expected to have 80-degree highs
today, matching the temperature the spring break crowd will be
enjoying in sunnier Daytona Beach, Fla.
   It's too early to pack up coats, of course. Cooling
thunderstorms were expected to bring Flint's high down to the 70s
today and 50s Wednesday, while showers should dunk temperatures
into the 50s in Ohio.
</TEXT>
