<FIRST>r a PM-TinyBaby     03-28 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tiny Baby,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fifteen-Ounce Baby Coming Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TABERNACLE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five-month-old Christy Andrews, one of
the tiniest infants ever to survive premature delivery, is ready to
come home from the hospital _ five times heavier than at birth but
still only 5 pounds.
   At birth, Christy weighed 15 ounces and measured 10 inches, so
small that neonatologists at Our Lady of Lourdes Medical Center in
Camden rated her chance of survival at less than 5 percent,
according to the Courier-Post of Cherry Hill.
   ``She finally fits into her preemie clothes. She's a nice size
now; she's a cuddly size,'' said Leslie Andrews, 28, who gave birth
to Christy 3 months prematurely in October.
   The baby, who was to come home today, has about an 80 percent
chance of growing up to be a normal child, said Dr. Margaret
Fernandes D'Souza, director of the hospital's neonatal intensive
care unit.
   ``She should catch up and, at the age of 3, should be like any
3-year-old. But a baby who starts off so small usually tends to be
a small child and adult,'' the doctor said.
   As Christy prepared to go home with her family _ her father,
Edward, 31, her sister, Michelle, 8, and her mother _ Mrs. Andrews
shouldered the 15-pound portable oxygen tank that she probably will
be carrying for the next year.
   ``She needs extra oxygen because of her lung damage,'' she said.
``We have two big tanks at home _ in the living room and in the
bedroom _ and the portable one for when we go out.''
   Once a week, Christy will be back at the hospital for a checkup,
and a therapist will visit her at home to monitor her speech,
hearing and motor development.
   ``Babies this size have up to a 25 percent chance of
developmental problems,'' Dr. Fernandes D'Souza said. ``If she
didn't have such a good home to go to, she would be sent to a
rehabilitation hospital for six months to a year.''
   Mrs. Andrews said Christy was ``just skin and bones when she was
born.''
   ``Her skin was transparent, because there was no fat on her,''
the mother said. ``I slipped my wedding band over her hand, and it
went up past her elbow.''
</TEXT>
