<FIRST>u a PM-PhoenixTransit     03-28 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phoenix Transit,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Votes Cast On $8.4 Billion Mass-Transit Plan For Phoenix</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fate of an $8.4 billion highway and
mass-transit program for the Phoenix area rested today with the
voters, who were asked to add a half-penny to their sales tax to
pay for the project.
   Turnout of 30 percent to 35 percent of Maricopa County's 860,000
eligible voters was predicted in the one-issue special election.
   Maricopa County includes Phoenix, Glendale, Scottsdale, Tempe,
Mesa and Chandler. The sales tax varies from city to city; the rate
in Phoenix is 6.7 percent.
   Recent polls indicated that the public was about evenly split on
the program, which calls for a 103-mile elevated railway; an
increase in the number of buses to 1,500 from 350; operation of a
commuter train linking suburban Chandler, Mesa and Tempe with
Phoenix, and accelerated freeway construction.
   The metropolitan area of 2 million people is the nation's
largest without an integrated freeway system, and county residents
have some of the highest auto insurance rates, partly because of
accidents.
   Most of the controversy has focused on whether trains and added
buses would attract enough riders to justify the expense and reduce
air pollution and traffic.
   Neighborhood preservationists and tax-dolllar watchers have
lined up against the increase; politicans and others predicting
huge population growth support it. Cost estimates range from $8.4
billion to $10.4 billion by the year 2019.
</TEXT>
