<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Crime     03-28 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Crime,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Convicted of Planting Bomb in Wife's Luggage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet court convicted a former army colonel of
planting a defective bomb in his wife's airplane luggage and
sentenced him to 13 years in a labor camp, Tass reported today.
   The former colonel, identified only as V. Grib, planned for the
crude explosive device to go off 35 minutes into the 870-mile
commercial flight from the Ukrainian capital of Kiev to the Volga
River city of Kuibyshev, but it failed to detonate, Tass said.
   His wife, who was traveling with their 15-year-old daughter,
found the bomb last summer while unpacking at her relatives' house
and reported it to authorities, the official Soviet news agency
said.
   A court in Kiev found Grib guilty of attempted murder and of
endangering the lives of the 168 passengers and eight crew members
on board the plane. He also was found guilty of trying to destroy
the airliner and of making an explosive device, Tass said. The
agency did not say when the conviction or sentencing occurred.
   Grib was working as an engineer at a Kiev factory at the time of
the incident, and Tass reported earlier that he disappeared after
learning the plane had landed safely. He later was located by
police.
</TEXT>
