<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Elections 2ndLd-Writethru a0478 03-28 0937</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Elections, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0478,0960</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voters Reject Top Party, Government Officials</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thoughout with additional results, comment from Foreign
Ministry spokesman. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet voters offered their first real choice in
70 years spurned many Communist Party and government leaders in a
stunning rejection of the status quo, election returns showed today.
   Moscow's mayor, its No. 2 Communist Party leader, five regional
party chairmen in the Ukraine, and Communist Party chiefs in
Leningrad and Kiev were all rejected Sunday in elections for the
new Congress of People's Deputies.
   Asked if the results indicated a loss of confidence in the
Communist Party, Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov
said today: ``Maybe they were wrong for their posts. Maybe they
failed to advertise their platforms.
   ``As far as party members are concerned, about 20 percent of
party members lost, 80 percent won,'' he said.
   The voters' rejection of top local officials for the national
parliament did not sweep them from their jobs in the party or
government apparatus. However, it could weaken their power base and
eventually lead to their replacement.
   Gerasimov said local party organizations would examine the cases
of officials who lost their races and decide their futures.
   Voters appeared to be expressing dissatisfaction with the
inefficiency and mismanagement associated with an entrenched party
elite that many see as resisting President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
efforts to reform Soviet society, to end chronic food shortages and
improve the quality of life.
   The 1,500 winners in Sunday's vote and in subsequent runoffs
will join those chosen earlier by the party and other officially
sanctioned organizations in the 2,250-seat congress, which is
certain to be dominated by the Communists.
   Still, many indepedent voices are expected to make a lively body
of the congress, which will meet once a year to choose a standing
legislature and the country's president.
   Final figures were not available on voter turnout, but figures
from individual cities indicated it was high. The Communist Party
paper Pravda said 89 percent of eligible voters cast ballots in the
southern city of Krasnodar and 90.3 percent voted in the Ukrainian
city of Kharkov.
   Officials at the Central Election Commission in Moscow said Yuri
Solovyev, a candidate member of the ruling Politburo and regional
party chief in Leningrad, was defeated in the election even though
he was unopposed. Enough voters crossed Solovyev's name off the
ballots to deny him the required majority and force a runoff.
   Election officials said two full Politburo members, Ukrainian
party leader Vladimir V. Shcherbitsky and Russian republic
President Vitaly I. Vorotnikov, won seats without opposition, as
did the premier of the Russian republic, Alexander V. Vlasov.
Vlasov is a candidate Politburo member.
   City officials in Voronezh, where Vorotnikov was a candidate,
said he received 84 percent of the more than 2 million votes cast
in his district. Totals were not available for Shcherbitsky's
district in Dnepropetrovsk and Vlasov's in Rostov, but the Moscow
officials said both won.
   As returns were reported, Boris N. Yeltsin left Moscow for a
vacation after the resounding success of his anti-establishment
candidacy for Moscow's sole at-large seat in the new congress.
   Yeltsin received 89.4 percent of the vote in Moscow, a city he
ran as Communist Party chief until he was sacked in November 1987
for criticizing the party's style of leadership and warning of a
Stalin-like cult developing around Gorbachev.
   Voters did not get a chance to voice their opinion of Yeltsin's
replacement as Moscow party boss, Politburo member Lev N. Zaikov.
Like Gorbachev and most other Politburo members, he took one of the
100 seats alloted to the Communist Party in the new congress.
   But two other top Moscow officials _ Mayor Valery Saikin and
Communist Party second secretary Yuri Prokofiev _ faced voters
Sunday and were denied seats in the congress.
   Saikin received 42.5 percent of the vote, while his opponent
received 24.8 percent, the newspaper Moskovskaya Pravda reported. A
new election will be held.
   Prokofiev received only 13.5 percent of the vote in his
district. The winner was Vladimir Markov, director of a radio
communications institute, the newspaper said.
   Tass reported Leningrad party leader Anatoly Gerasimov received
only 15 percent of the vote in a contest with a shipbuilder.
   The official news agency said the regional Communist Party
leaders in Kiev, Voroshilovograd, the Carpathian region, Lvov and
Chernigov all were defeated.
   Pravda reported that regional party leader in the Ural Mountains
city of Perm was defeated, but that regional party leaders in
Volgograd, Krasnodar, Kursk, Omsk, Stavropol, and Kharkov won
election.
   Another defeated candidate was the commander of Soviet forces in
East Germany, Gen. Boris Snetkov. Voters in a district east of
Moscow favored another military officer, Lt. Col. Viktor Podzeruk,
by 1.8 million votes to 871,000 for Snetkov, local journalists
reported.
   In the Baltic republics, candidates from grassroots movements
that have tapped popular dissatisfaction with Moscow's control over
their economies, cultures and politics generally fared well in the
election.
   In Estonia, Edgar Savisaar, a founder of the People's Front, won
more than 80 percent of the vote in defeating a local party chief.
Another Estonian People's Front leader, Marju Lauristen, also
received more than 80 percent to defeat the editor of a
Russian-language newspaper.
   Lithuania's president, Vitautas Astrauskas, and its premier,
Vitautas Sakalauskas, were defeated. Sajudis, the Lithuanian
grassroots movement, claimed all 39 of its candidates either won or
advanced to run-off elections, which are scheduled for April 9.
   Latvia's premier, Vilnis Bresis, lost to a television reporter,
and the republic's party chief, Janis Vagris, was elected by a
small margin, Tass said.
</TEXT>
