<FIRST>r a PM-Spill-Wildlife     03-28 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Wildlife,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Not Much Can Be Done For Contaminated Wildlife</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rugged wilderness that makes Prince
William Sound a rich marine habitat stands as a barrier to efforts
to rescue the thousands of animals expected to be fouled by
America's biggest oil spill, officials say.
   ``There's just a lot of problems out there,'' said Pam Bergman,
head of the regional response team for the U.S. Department of the
Interior.
   Problems cited by Bergman and others include:
   _A coastline so remote that rescuers are afraid to send out
volunteers for fear they might not be prepared for wilderness
survival;
   _Beaches so rugged that in many places it is impossible to land
a boat, let alone chase down and capture oil-coated birds or
wildlife;
   _Distances to aid facilities so great that animals captured on
the beach would probably die in captivity waiting to be taken to a
hospital;
   _Wild animals so large and powerful that rescuers could be
seriously injured.
   A body count of dead animals is about all anyone can hope to
accomplish, said Jon Lyman, Alaska Department of Fish and Game
spokesman. That count stood at fewer than 100 birds late Monday,
but thousands more are expected to die.
   Bergman said environmental groups have begun organizing to help,
but she has asked the volunteers not to come to Valdez. There is no
place to stay, no boats to take people out, no equipment and
nothing to do, she said.
   Officials in the state of Washington estimated that 10,000 birds
died there after a barge spilled 231,000 gallons of bunker oil off
the coast last year. Bunker oil is thicker than the North Slope
crude that spilled in Prince William Sound, but the Washington
spill was only about one-fiftieth the size of the spill near Valdez.
   In Washington, rescuers were able to mobilize thousands of
volunteers who could easily get to the scene.
   In Alaska, strong winds Monday and Tuesday pushed the oil
farther from the rescue coordination center at Valdez, beyond the
reach of would-be animal rescuers, and made it impossible to
retrieve oil-soaked wildlife, Bergman said.
   Bergman said there is no place to put a rescue facility any
closer to the advance of the oil slick, which covers more than 100
square miles. There are no communities in the southwest portion of
the sound, an area of rocky reefs and tree-studded islands.
   A lot of the beaches are too small, she said, and catching birds
from boats is out for safety reasons.
   ``It's real hard to sneak up on (birds),'' she said. ``You end
up racing the birds down the beach with a net trying to catch them.
Once you capture an oiled bird, you can't leave it in a box for 12
hours.''
   Contaminated birds must go almost immediately to a
rehabilitation center to be fed, de-oiled and dried.
   Sea otters present even bigger problems, she added. ``They look
sweet and cuddly and wonderful, but they got sharp teeth and
claws,'' Bergman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
