<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-GrandJury     03-28 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Grand Jury,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules on Alleged Prosecutor Misconduct Issue in New York Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal criminal defendants who fail to
persuade a judge to throw out their indictments because of alleged
misconduct by prosecutors cannot appeal before they are tried and
convicted, the Supreme Court said today.
   The unanimous ruling is a defeat for a Buffalo, N.Y.,
contracting firm and its president, both charged with rigging bids
in selling liquid bituminous coal to the state and some western
counties.
   The justices upheld the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals'
refusal to hear arguments by Midland Asphalt Corp. and Albert C.
Litteer that grand jury abuses by prosecutors tainted the
indictment.
   Writing for the court, Justice Antonin Scalia said federal court
rules bar criminal defendants, once a judge dismisses such
allegations in pretrial proceedings, from appealing immediately to
a federal appeals court.
   Scalia said Midland and Litteer, indicted in early 1987, must
wait until after a trial is conducted, and pursue their
prosecutorial-misconduct arguments if they are convicted.
   The decision resolves conflicting rulings between the New York
City-based 2nd Circuit court and the San Francisco-based 9th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
   The 9th Circuit court had ruled that dismissals of such
allegations are immediately appealable.
   Lawyers for Midland and Liteer contend that prosecutors violated
federal rules by disclosing details of a grand jury investigation
to the public.
   They said the information was released in connection with a
separate civil case.
   The case is Midland Asphalt vs. U.S., 87-1905.
</TEXT>
