<HEAD>Preachers' Sentences Total 47 of Possible 50 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY O'DELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three evangelists accused of molesting
scores of boys along the Southern revival circuit represent
``everything bad under the sun,'' a federal judge said in
sentencing them to a combined 47 years in prison.
   ``All of you have preyed on the uneducated and the poor, because
I think anyone else would have seen through you, and you've
blackened the eye of religion,'' U.S. District Judge James C. Turk
said Monday.
   Mario ``Tony'' Leyva, 42, of Columbus, Ga., and the two other
traveling preachers pleaded guilty to transporting boys across
state lines for sexual purposes. Leyva and Rias Edward Morris also
pleaded guilty to conspiracy.
   Leyva, who has admitted to having sexual relations with as many
as 100 boys over the past two decades, received the maximum of 20
years in prison. He already is serving 2{ years on state charges he
sexually abused two boys.
   Morris, 47, an organist for Leyva, received the maximum 15-year
sentence.
   Freddie H. Herring, 50, of Lighthouse Assembly of Dougasville,
Ga., also faced up to 15 years but received a 12-year term.
Testimony indicated he has diabetes and a heart condition.
   The maximum sentences were spelled out in plea agreements in
October. Each defendant also was fined $5,000.
   Authorities identified more than 30 boys molested by Leyva.
Morris was accused of having sexual relations with 11 youngsters,
Herring with nine.
   The judge, noting that Leyva committed acts he told his
followers were sinful, said, ``Everyone who ever heard you out
there ought to kick you good.''
   That brought a cheer from those assembled in court, including
some victims and their families.
   All three men expressed regret in court, but government
psychologists testified the preachers expressed little remorse and
blamed their victims by characterizing them as promiscuous.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Jennie Montgomery asked for the maximum
sentences ``solely for the protection of the public.''
   Psychiatrist William H. Gray, who said he counseled four of the
evangelists' victims, said the judge should consider castration as
part of the sentences. ``Massive doses of estrogen also is a
possibility,'' Gray said.
</TEXT>
