<HEAD>Police Chief Limits Police from Posing as Reporters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with police chief forbidding officers
from posing as journalists without his permission. Pickup 6th graf `On
Thursday...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Israel's police ordered policemen
not to put ``press'' signs on their cars while searching for
Palestinians suspects unless they have his permission, a day after
saying the practice was to continue.
   Journalists' plans to put ``police on duty'' signs in their own
cars were canceled after the agreement with Police
Inspector-General David Krauss.
   The decision came after an appeal from Jerusalem's Journalists
Association, which said the officers' use of press signs could
endanger reporters traveling in the occupied territories and Arab
east Jerusalem to cover the Palestinian uprising.
   Palestinian youths routinely stone cars with yellow Israeli
license plates but are more likely to let journalists pass
peacefully. Arab-owned cars in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip have blue or white license plates.
   Members of the Journalists Association met today with Krauss to
ask him to forbid the decoy method even though the police chief
said Monday the signs were not illegal and that police were to
continue using them.
   Krauss responded today with a statement saying he will instruct
police units to refrain from impersonating journalists unless they
have his permission.
   ``Any request by police figures to make use of such means will
be subject to the approval of the inspector general,'' the
statement said.
   ``I am satisfied,'' said Elisha Shpigelman, chairman of the
Journalists Association, after his meeting with Krauss. ``I
certainly see this as an acceptance, though not fully, of our
position.''
   On Thursday, several Western news agencies and an Israeli
photographer filmed Jerusalem police driving a rented car with a
handwritten sign saying ``TV'' and arresting a 15-year-old Arab
girl for throwing stones.
   Israeli journalists and the Foreign Press Association condemned
the ruse, but Krauss defended the practice as legal.
   ``The policemen did not disguise themselves as journalists,'' he
said in a television interview. ``They camouflaged their vehicle in
one of the possible camouflage ways.''
   ``The police have very difficult and very important duties in
the field including arresting stone-throwers and firebombers on the
spot without harming them and I think that's preferable,'' Krauss
said.
   Shaked said on Israeli radio that the practice endangers freedom
of the press. Another journalist leader, Gabi Brun, said the
Journalists' Union planned to distribute signs saying ``Police on
Duty'' for reporters' cars.
   Meanwhile, an organization of Jewish settlers in the West Bank
said it plans to distribute thousands of ``Press'' signs to
settlers in the area.
   If reporters are stoned as a result, ``maybe they'll understand
the distress of the settlers,'' the Committee for Secure Roads said
in a statement.
   About 70,000 settlers live among the 1.7 million Palestinians in
the occupied lands, which Israel seized in 1967.
   The settlers often have been involved in confrontations with
Arabs during the 15-month Palestinian uprising against Israeli
rule, and complain that the news media pays little attention to
their problems.
</TEXT>
