<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Nightingale     03-28 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Nightingale,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Commentator Dies at 68</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARADISE VALLEY, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Earl Nightingale, a radio
commentator and voice of the adventure character Sky King during
the 1950s, has died at age 68.
   The gravel-voiced broadcaster, who died Saturday at Scottsdale
Memorial Hospital of complications following heart surgery, was
also a pioneer in the production of motivational audiotapes.
   After serving in World War II, where he was one of only 12
Marines to survive the 1941 attack on the USS Arizona in Pearl
Harbor, he began a daily talk show, ``Our Changing World,'' on
radio station WGN in Chicago.
   It went into syndication in 1949 and still is carried across the
nation and in a number of countries overseas.
   From 1950 to 1954, Nightingale was the radio voice of ``Sky
King,'' an adventure about a rancher who used an airplane instead
of a horse to fight bad guys.
   In 1960, Nightingale and Lloyd Conant formed the
Nightingale-Conant Corp.
   Vic Conant, a son of Nightingale's late partner, said the
company produces tapes by Nightingale and other motivational
speakers, including Chrysler Corp. chairman Lee Iacocca.
   Nightingale is survived by his wife, Diana; two sons, and a
daughter.
   Funeral arrangements were incomplete.
</TEXT>
