<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Pensions 2ndLdWritethru a0534 03-28 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Pensions, 2nd Ld Writethru, a0534,420</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Eds: Inserts grafs 16-21, In other action, with other cases. ^By
RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   States may not tax federal pensions while
exempting the pensions of retired state and local government
workers, the Supreme Court ruled today.
   By an 8-1 vote, the justices struck down Michigan's differing
tax treatment of the pensions received by retired government
employees.
   The challenged Michigan law ``violates principles of
intergovernmental tax immunity by favoring retired state and local
government employees over retired federal employees,'' Justice
Anthony M. Kennedy wrote for the court.
   He said Paul S. Davis, an East Lansing lawyer, is entitled to a
refund of $4,299 on taxes he paid from 1979 through 1984.
   Davis worked for the federal government at various times in his
career, retiring in 1980.
   He challenged the Michigan law that allows federal retirees
living in the state to deduct only up to $7,500 of their annual
federal pensions when computing their state tax liability.
   The law permits retired employees of the state government and
local governments within Michigan to deduct all their state
pensions from their state taxes.
   The Michigan Court of Appeals had upheld the law, but that
ruling was reversed today.
   Kennedy said the law violates a federal law that authorizes
states to tax federal employees ``if the taxation does not
discriminate against the ... employee because of the source of the
pay or compensation.''
   The justices rejected arguments by Michigan authorities that the
law applies only to federal employees _ and not to federal
pensioners.
   Under the Michigan law, federal pensioners faced the same state
tax liabiity as private industry retirees while state and local
government pensioners do not.
   The court said the inequity among government workers may not
continue. But the justices left it up to Michigan courts to decide
whether the proper remedy would be exempting all federal pensions
from state taxes or exposing the pensions of state and local
government retirees to some state taxation.
   According to the National Association of Retired Federal
Employees, at least five other states give special preferences to
state or local government retirees not afforded to federal retirees.
   Those states are Arizona, Arkansas, Georgia, New York and
Virginia.
   Justice John Paul Stevens was the lone dissenter. ``I cannot
join the unjustified, court-imposed restriction on a state's power
to administer its own affairs,'' he wrote.
   In other action, the court:
   _ Made it easier for those who win partial victories in civil
rights lawsuits to recover their attorneys' fees.
   The court, in a case involving Texas school teachers, ruled
unanimously that those who prevail on a ``significant'' issue in
such suits are entitled to reimbursement for legal fees even if
they lose the ``central'' issue.
   _ Ruled that federal criminal defendants who fail to persuade a
judge to throw out their indictments because of alleged misconduct
by prosecutors cannot appeal before they are tried and convicted.
   The unanimous ruling is a defeat for a Buffalo, N.Y.,
contracting firm and its president, both charged with rigging bids
in selling liquid biruminous coal to the state and some western
counties.
   The pension case is Davis vs. Michigan Department of Treasury,
87-1020.
</TEXT>
