<FIRST>r i PM-Spain-Marks     03-28 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spain-Marks,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Agrees to Extradite Britons To U.S. To Face Drug Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Spanish high court has granted a U.S.
request for extradition of a Briton wanted for allegedly
masterminding a worldwide hashish and marijuana smuggling ring,
court sources said today.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
Audiencia Nacional court agreed to extradite Dennis Howard Marks to
face trial on federal drug smuggling charges in Miami.
   The sources also said the court agreed to a U.S. request for the
extradition of Marks' wife, Judith, on related charges.
   Last July 25, Spanish police working with agents of the U.S.
Drug Enforcement Administration arrested Marks, 43, his wife and a
third Briton, Geoffrey Kenion, at the Marks' house in Palma de
Majorca, a Spanish Mediterranean island.
   On that same day, an indictment unsealed in the federal court in
Miami named Marks as the alleged leader of a worldwide ring that
shipped tons of drugs from Asia to the United States, Britain and
several countries in Western Europe from 1970 to 1987.
   Mrs. Marks, Kenion and 19 other people were named in the
indictment as ring members.
   The court said the extradition carried a condition that U.S.
authorities limit any possible prison sentence for both Marks and
his wife to 30 years, the maximum permitted under Spanish law.
   Before the Marks can be sent to the United States, the Spanish
government must approve the extradition request.
   Thomas Cash, head of the DEA's Miami office, has described
Marks, an Oxford University graduate from London, as ``the Marco
Polo of drug trafficking.''
</TEXT>
