<SECOND>PM-AIDS Demonstration,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Activists Take On City Hall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAYNER PIKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 2,500 AIDS activists picketed City
Hall today, protesting what they said was inaction in dealing with
the disease, and nearly 100 were arrested, police said.
   Police carried, dragged and escorted away protesters who sat in
the street chanting, ``We will never be silent again.'' Most of the
arrests occurred after demonstrators blocked major roads such as
the Brooklyn Bridge off-ramp.
   Those arrested were charged with disorderly conduct. The 8 a.m.
demonstration was over in about two hours.
   The demonstrators, organized by the AIDS Coalition to Unleash
Power, shouted ``ACT-UP, fight back, fight AIDS,'' and ```Just say
no' is not enough, teach safe sex.''
   The group demanded improved and expanded health care; safe
housing for homeless people infected with the AIDS virus; free
treatment for all drug users, and AIDS education that ``teaches
protection, not morality.''
   ``We're here because we're angry, because we're dying and the
mayor won't do what he has to do,'' said Ann Northrop, an AIDS
educator who works with adolescents.
   Michael Nesline, a registered nurse at Bellevue Hospital, said
Mayor Edward I. Koch failed to prepare the hospital system for the
expected increase in AIDS cases, especially among the poor and
uninsured.
   ``Thousands of people will be dying in the street in a couple of
years. Ed Koch is making political decisions, making decisions for
a few rich people,'' Nesline said.
   Koch said in a statement that New York City ``does more than any
other city or state to serve the needs of those with AIDS and to
prevent its spread to others.'' He said the federal government is
not doing its part.
</TEXT>
