<FIRST>u i PM-Yugoslavia 4thLd-Writethru a0520 03-28 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0520,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Rioting In Kosovo Province, Death Toll Reaches 21</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with 21 dead, forces sent to Kosovo
from other regions. Pickup 9th graf `Authorities on...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired on hundreds of ethnic
Albanian protesters in Kosovo province today, killing at least one
person and wounding 14, in rioting against Serbia's bid to gain
more control over the region, authorities said.
   Serbia's parliament today formally adopted constitutional
changes to increase authority over government and schools in
Kosovo, the republic's autonomous southern province bordering
Albania.
   Six straight days of protests since Kosovo's parliament approved
the changes have left 21 people dead and scores injured,
authorities said. It is Kosovo's worst violence since 1981, when
nine people died in ethnic riots and the province was briefly
placed under martial law.
   The ethnic Albanians, who make up 85 percent of Kosovo's 1.9
million citizens, say the constitutional changes will curb the
broad autonomy they won under the 1974 Yugoslav Constitution.
   Serbia says the changes are needed to protect the province's
Slav minority, which alleges constant harassment from the ethnic
Albanians.
   The federal Interior Ministry, in a statement issued in the
capital Belgrade, said extra police forces from throughout the
country were being dispatched to Kosovo.
   The ministry, in the statement published by the official Tanjug
news agency, said two policemen were shot dead Monday and 25 police
were injured, five seriously, in the two days of unrest. Nineteen
demonstrators lost their lives, and 49 were injured, the ministry
said, adding that police were not responsible for all the deaths.
   Maria Gasi, a spokeswoman for Kosovo's information secretariat,
told a news conference told foreign correspondents at a news
conference that a dusk-to-dawn curfew in effect since Monday would
apply to them. She told foreign photographers they would no longer
be allowed to shoot pictures in Kosovo.
   Authorities on Monday also banned gatherings of more than three
people. Schools, the university, cinemas, theaters and sports
stadiums were closed indefinitely.
   Police in Djakovice used tear gas ``and other technical means''
today against a crowd of several hundred chanting, rock-throwing
youths, Tanjug said.
   Today's death and injuries came in a fierce clash in Zur, a
village neaer the Albanian border, and more violence was reported
from Orohovac, where about 250 stone-throwing ethnic Albanians were
said to have smashed windows.
   Tanjug said an 18-year-old youth died in Zur when police opened
fire after shots came from a rock-throwing crowd of about 500. The
crowd wrecked two police vehicles, the agency said.
   Ms. Gasi reported major incidents today in Zur, and the towns of
Prizren, Djakovice, Dusanovo and Orahovac.
   Tanjug said tear gas was fired to disperse crowds in Orahovac,
Djakovice and Dusanovo, where it reported an unspecified number of
injuries. Tear gas also was used in Decani, it said.
   Security was tight in Pristina, the provincial capital, 160
miles south of Belgrade, with dozens of military vehicles visible
and frequent patrols by riot police, some wearing bulletproof
jackets.
   Sonic booms were heard as military jets flew low overhead, a
tactic that was used in Pristina last September to try and
discourage unrest.
   Tanjug said Monday's riots appeared ``well prepared and
coordinated.''
   There have been allegations that ethnic Albanians in Kosovo are
part of an underground separatist movement that wants to join with
neighboring Communist Albania.
   The continuation of violence despite Monday's clampdown and
dozens of arrests after a partial state of emegency was declared in
Kosovo last month indicated the strength of ethnic Albanian anger
over the constitutional changes.
   Tanjug reported celebrations in factories and schools in several
Serbian towns today after the parliament formally approved the
changes.
   A rally was scheduled later in Belgrade to celebrate the passage
of the constitutional reforms, which give Serbia more control over
the judiciary, schools and police in its provinces of Kosovo and
Vojvodina.
   The Serbian drive for more control over Kosovo has produced
nationwide divisions in the Communist leadership of this
non-aligned and ethnically diverse country.
</TEXT>
