<FIRST>r i PM-Pakistan-Howe     03-28 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan-Howe,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Won't Recognize Afghan Guerrillas; Promises Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's foreign secretary, Sir
Geoffrey Howe, ended a 26-hour official visit to Pakistan today and
said Britain could not recognize neighboring Afghanistan's
guerrilla government-in-exile.
   Howe said he promised the equivalent of about $3 million to
non-government organizations helping refugees from the Afghan war.
He then left Pakistan for India.
   About 3 million Afghan refugees live in Pakistan and another 2
million in Iran.
   Unprecedented security arrangements were made for Howe's visit
after protests over ``The Satanic Verses,'' a novel written by
British author Salman Rushdie that Moslems say blasphemes their
faith.
   Protests forced Howe to cancel a trip to Pakistan's Northwest
Frontier province, where most Afghan war refugees live.
   ``The modern world must find a balance between mutual respect
for the great religions and the traditions of free speech and free
expression within the law,'' Howe said.
   After a meeting with Howe on Monday, Prime Minister Benazir
Bhutto said she emphasized the ``anguish Moslems felt'' over the
book but said she ``appreciated that Britain has its own laws.''
   Hours after Howe arrived Monday, a bomb exploded near a British
cultural center in the Pakistan capital. Although no group claimed
responsibility, the blast was apparently linked to protests over
Rushdie's novel.
   Seven people died Feb. 12 in an anti-Rushdie demonstration
outside an American cultural center in Islamabad and another person
died in two other bombings at British Council libraries outside the
capital.
   Howe met briefly with representatives of the Pakistan-based
Afghan guerrillas, who are fighting Afghanistan's Soviet-supported
communist leaders.
   But he said there was no question of diplomatic recognition. He
said Britain recognizes only states and never governments.
   ``The meeting was an encouragement and not a recognition,'' Howe
said.
   The provisional Afghan government _ formed about one month ago
after Soviet troops withdrew Feb. 15, ending a nine-year
intervention _ is lobbying for diplomatic recognition. The
Organization of Islamic Conference Nations has recognized the
rebels as the legitimate government of Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
