<FIRST>u p PM-IndianaCongress 1stLd-Writethru a0470 03-28 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indiana Congress, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0470,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Dan Quayle's Former House Seat up for Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to UPDATE with campaign resuming. PICKS
UP 3rd graf pvs, `The seat ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The congressional seat that launched the
political career of Vice President Dan Quayle was at stake today in
a special election that pitted a newcomer against a candidate who
has sought the seat before.
   Republican Dan Heath and Democrat Jill Long campaigned at
daybreak today, meeting voters in coffee shops in efforts that
could prove crucial given an expected turnout of as low as
one-third of the district's more than 200,000 voters.
   The seat was vacated by Dan Coats, a Republican who resigned to
take the Senate seat Quayle occupied before taking the oath as vice
president. District voters were the first to send Quayle to
Washington in 1976 as a 28-year-old congressman. Quayle won
re-election in 1978, then gave up the seat for a successful effort
to defeat three-term Democratic senator Birch Bayh.
   A poll released Sunday by the Fort Wayne Journal-Gazette showed
Heath with a 44 percent and Long with 36 percent, with 20 percent
undecided. The poll among 1,019 likely voters was conducted in the
week before the election and had a margin of error 3.1 percent.
   In the final evening of campaigning Monday, Long, a business
professor at Indiana University-Purdue University at Fort Wayne,
chose not to cancel a scheduled class in public finance that
followed a campaign rally with Gov. Evan Bayh, the son of Birch
Bayh.
   Heath made evening campaign stops at several bowling alleys
after a round of door-to-door campaigning.
   The district has voted Republican 2-to-1 in recent congressional
elections.
   The candidates, picked by party caucuses in January, attacked
each other's sources of campaign funding, with Long hammering on
Heath ads produced by the National Association of Realtors. ``This
congressional district should not be bought by an outside interest
group,'' she said.
   Heath countered with copies of finance reports showing 62
percent of Long's funds came from out-of-state political action
committees.
   Heath also turned to the White House for campaign help and was
visited by Quayle _ his first visit to the city as vice president _
Barbara Bush, and Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter.
   Long was boosted by a campaign visit from Sen. Albert Gore Jr.,
D-Tenn., a presidential hopeful in 1988.
   Long, 36, lost to Quayle in 1986, when Quayle ran for
re-election to the Senate. She lost to Coats last fall in her first
bid to win the 4th District seat.
   Heath, 36, making his first run for office, has been a
congressional aide to Coats.
</TEXT>
