<FIRST>r a PM-NursingHomeDeaths     03-28 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nursing Home Deaths,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Charged In 3 New Murders At Nursing Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former nurse's aide accused of
suffocating two nursing home patients for the ``emotional release''
it gave her has been charged with murdering three more elderly
women.
   Gwendolyn Graham, 25, of Tyler, Texas, was arraigned Monday in
the February 1987 deaths of the three women at Alpine Manor Nursing
Home in Walker, a suburb of Grand Rapids. She has been jailed since
December in the other deaths.
   She worked at Alpine Manor in 1986 and 1987 before leaving to
return to Texas. At the time, the five deaths were considered to
have resulted from natural causes.
   The first two bodies have since been exhumed for autopsies, but
the remains of the three other women were cremated.
   Kent County Prosecutor William Forsyth said Graham's
co-defendant, Catherine Wood, has agreed to testify against her
former co-worker and lover. Wood has said she served as a lookout
while Graham suffocated the women, court records show.
   Another nurse's aide, Russell Shawn Thatcher, testified earlier
that Wood told him Graham killed the patients ``to relieve Gwen's
stress if she was having a bad day.''
   Witnesses also testified Wood told them she and Graham took
souvenirs from their victims.
   Wood's ex-husband, who went to police in October, said Wood told
him she and Graham had tried to select victims whose initials
spelled out ``murder.''
   Police said they have been unable to confirm that.
</TEXT>
