<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BusInvestigation     03-28 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Investigation,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigator of Ky. Crash Urges Better School Buses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal safety investigator looking into the
deadliest accident in U.S. history attributed to drunken driving
said today that school buses should have to meet more stringent
emergency evacuation standards.
   Bernard S. Loeb, investigator for the National Transportation
Safety Board, testified as the board considered recommendations and
conclusions it will make in the head-on collision between a pickup
truck and a church-operated school bus that killed 24 children and
three adults near Carrollton, Ky., on May 14, 1988.
   Loeb told the five-member board that standards for evacuation
from public transit buses exceed the federal standards for
school-type buses. He said performance-related standards are needed
rather than those which only require certain widths between benches
and set dimensions for exits.
   ``I don't care how they do it, but they've got to be able to
evacuate that bus'' in a shorter period of time, Loeb said.
   NTSB staff members, based on interviews with many of the 40
children and adults who escaped the fiery crash, described children
crawling over each other to get out of the bus after it was hit by
a pickup truck driven by Larry Mahoney, 34, of Worthville, Ky.
   NTSB investigator John V. Moulden testified that Mahoney could
have had up to a 0.29 blood alcohol level, which is nearly three
times the legal level for presumption of intoxication and
two-thirds of the way to a lethal dose.
   Mahoney, who faces a Nov. 8 trial date on 27 murder charges, was
driving the wrong way on Interstate 71 when his truck collided with
the bus. The crash blocked the front door and sent flames and smoke
through the bus, which was returning from a church outing at an
amusement park.
   Moulden said Mahoney likely drank about a full case _ 24 cans _
of light beer on the day of the crash, which occurred at 10:55 p.m.
``He in no way could be judge competent to operate a vehicle,'' the
investigator said.
   Investigators said Mahoney, 35, had been arrested in 1984 on
drunken-driving charges. They said he had been twice divorced and
was planning to remarry his first wife.
   About an hour before the crash, friends took away his keys
because they thought he would lose his driver's license, but gave
them back when he told them he was only driving a short distance on
a dirt road to the trailer where he lived, said Jean Fassone, who
headed the on-site investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
