<DOCNO> AP890328-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-GandhiInquiry 1stLd-Writethru a0500 03-28 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gandhi Inquiry, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0500,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Withheld Portions Of Gandhi Assassination Report</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with government admitting keeping
portions of report secret. Pickup 7th graf `In the...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said today it withheld
parts of a report on the assassination of Prime Minister Indira
Gandhi because they contained top secret material.
   Home Minister Buta Singh told reporters the government did not
release certain passages of the report because they were classified
or considered sensitive, Press Trust of India reported.
   The agency quoted Singh as saying the speaker of Parliament will
be given the full report and will be able to seek the attorney
general's opinion on whether the secret portions should be made
public.
   The report, released Monday and based on the findings of a
special state commission, accuses an adviser to Prime Minister
Rajiv Gandhi of complicity in the 1984 shooting death of Mrs.
Gandhi. The adviser, Rajendra Kumar Dhawan, was personal secretary
to Mrs. Gandhi at the time.
   The government said Dhawan had been exonerated of involvement in
Mrs. Gandhi's death.
   Opposition members said today the government failed to release
two volumes of the report.
   ``Is the Parliament at the mercy of the government?'' asked
opposition leader Madhu Dandavate, a Janata Party member of the
lower house.
   Dandavate presented a motion for breach of privilege, a form of
parliamentary sanction, against Singh, who delivered the report to
Parliament.
   In the upper house, opposition members wrested an assurance from
Deputy Chairman Najma Heptulla that the issue would be taken up
with the government.
   The Statesman newspaper reported the report had four volumes and
was about 8,000 pages long. The government released 657 pages in
two volumes.
   The report links three people directly to the assassination: the
two gunmen and Dhawan, Mrs. Gandhi's personal secretary for more
than 20 years.
   Mrs. Gandhi was slain by two Sikh bodyguards on Oct. 31, 1984,
as she walked through the garden of her New Delhi residence to a
television interview.
   One of the two Sikh assassins was killed by other bodyguards
just after the assassination. The other was sentenced to death and
hanged along with a third Sikh, Kehar Singh, who was convicted for
instigating the assassins to commit the crime.
   The report accuses Dhawan of facilitating the crime by reversing
an order to remove all Sikhs from Mrs. Gandhi's inner security
circle as well as changing the shift of one of the assassins and
the time of the television interview.
   It says Dhawan lied or gave inadequate reponses to questions
about entries in his diary about one assassin, foreign money, the
CIA and his association with a Sikh suspected of having ties to the
U.S. intelligence agency.
   It said Mrs. Gandhi had looked into replacing Dhawan and had
reprimanded him a month before she was killed. It did not say why
he was reprimanded.
   In releasing the report to Parliament, the home minister said a
special investigating team had ``unraveled a conspiracy, a larger
conspiracy to eliminate Mrs. Gandhi.'' He said more charges are to
be filed but gave no details.
   According to the report, the commission accepted that Mrs.
Gandhi was killed by her bodyguards. However, it did not rule out
involvement of a foreign power.
   The government says Mrs. Gandhi was killed in revenge for an
army raid she ordered in June 1984 on the Golden Temple to clear
the Sikhs' holiest shrine of militants. At least 1,200 people died,
most of them Sikhs.
   India has long accused Pakistan of training and arming Sikh
militants. Pakistan has denied the charge.
   Dhawan, 52, left his post after Mrs. Gandhi's death, but
returned to the government last month as an adviser to her son.
Dhawan could not be reached at his home or office for comment on
the report.
</TEXT>
