<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--OilRig     03-28 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Oil Rig,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Sea Oil Rig Wreck Sunk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wrecked North Sea oil and gas platform where
167 men died in an explosion last year was sunk Tuesday because it
was a hazard to shipping.
   The Occidental Petroleum Corp. of Los Angeles, which owned the
Piper Alpha platform, said three tugs and a barge pulled the
remains of the structure over after the legs were weakened by
controlled explosions under water.
   John Brading, the company's chairman in Britain, said there is
now 250 feet of clear water above the wreck on the seabed, 110
miles east of Aberdeen on Scotland's east coast.
   The worst disaster to a platform at sea occurred July 6, 1988,
and was attributed to a leaking gas valve. There were 62 survivors,
and 31 of the victims were never found.
   Occidental said the 12,500-ton pile of wreckage will be
inspected and mapped, and ``every effort'' will be made to retrieve
any human remains.
   Brading said salvage of the undersea wreckage was not attempted
because it would have cost up to $1.7 billion.
   Lawyers said each victim's family would get about $1 million in
compensation.
</TEXT>
