<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Sports     03-28 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Sports,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Progress Reported in Joint Korean Sports Team</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sports officials from South Korea and
North Korea made progress Tuesday on forming a joint team for the
1990 Asian Games and expressed optimism on reaching an overall
agreement.
   Delegates agreed after about three hours of talks to meet again
April 18 at the Panmunjom truce site to clear the way for forming a
joint national team. Such a development could be a big step in
easing tension on the divided Korean peninsula.
   ``The north seemed to be sincere about the talks ... I can say
we made some progress today,'' said chief South Korean delegate
Chang Chung-shik.
   Chief North Korean delegate Kim Huong Jin said the talks must
help the two sides improve relations and end their rivalry.
   ``What is most important ... is for both to get rid of the
concept of confrontation and think, first of all, that they are
members of one nation sharing the same destiny,'' Kim said in an
opening statement.
   The talks must still overcome major obstacles before they can
form a joint team to send to the games in Beijing. Past efforts
failed on such issues as the name of the team and what flag it
should use.
   Both sides agreed a team would be selected after joint training
of candidates. South Korea had wanted selection before training.
   North Korea offered a concession on the name of the team and
both sides offered suggestions on a team flag _ both critical
issues. They agreed March 9 that a traditional Korean folk song
would serve as the team anthem.
   The nations have been holding intermittent talks at various
levels to try to improve relations. Both sides say they want to end
their long, bitter rivalry.
   Separate talks between parliamentary delegations and senior
government officials were stalemated by North Korean demands last
month that Seoul call off annual ``Team Spirit'' military exercises
with U.S. forces.
   South Korea refused, and the exercises, involving 200,000 South
Korean and U.S. troops, concluded last week.
   Pyongyang proposed the sports talks in December, saying the two
sides should stop fielding separate teams at international sports
events.
   North Korea boycotted the Summer Olympics in Seoul last year
after South Korea and the International Olympic Committee refused
to let Pyongyang be a co-host. North Kora also boycotted the 1986
Asian Games in Seoul.
   The two nations have been enemies since the division of the
Korean peninsula by U.S. and Soviet forces in 1945 at the end of
World War II. North Korea invaded South Korea in 1950 to start the
three-year Korean War.
   The Korean border is sealed and the two sides have hundreds of
thousands of troops facing each other along their 150-mile border.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
