<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-NATO     03-28 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-NATO,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greece Again Says it Won't Take Part in Annual NATO Exercise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greece said Tuesday it again won't take
part in NATO's annual ``Dragon Hammer'' military exercise April
20-May 2 because of a continuing dispute over an island in the
Aegean Sea.
   Government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos said Greece was not
participating because the exercise would violate a treaty
concerning the military status of the northern Aegean island of
Lemnos.
   Greece claims that international treaties allow it to garrison
the island, while neighboring Turkey, a member of the North
Atlantic Treaty Alliance, says Greece has no such right.
   Greece, which keeps a large military presence on the island,
refuses to take part in NATO exercises unless Lemnos is included in
the war games. Turkey strongly objects to the fortification of
Lemnos, located near its Aegean coast.
   Although Greek-Turkish relations have improved recently, the two
still are at odds over control of Aegean airspace, its seabed and
mineral rights.
   Greece has not taken part in any NATO exercises held in the
Aegean since Premier Andreas Papandreou's Socialist government came
to power in 1981. Parts of ``Dragon Hammer,'' are to take part in
the Aegean.
</TEXT>
