<FIRST>u i AM-VisaLottery Bjt   03-28 0873</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Visa Lottery, Bjt,0897</SECOND>
<HEAD>Worldwide Lottery For U.S. Visas _ Taking a Chance on a New Life</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The aspirations of the young Pole in the
crowd outside the U.S. Embassy weren't grandiose: ``I would like to
work and live a normal life.''
   But they speak volumes in a country where little is ``normal''
other than spirit-sapping shortages of everything from housing to
hope.
   So he and hundreds of thousands of others worldwide have taken a
chance on finding a place in what they see as a land of plenty.
They have entered a U.S. State Department lottery to win one of
20,000 immigration visas to the United States to be issued over two
years starting in October.
   A computer will select the winners, rather than the immigration
officers, who normally must strictly limit visas to those who have
specialized skills or a close relative in the United States.
   ``This lottery may be their only chance of immigrating,'' said
Phyllis Villegoureix-Ritoud, consul-general of the U.S. Embassy in
Warsaw.
   Many Poles learned about the program from Voice of America
broadcasts ``as my ringing phones can testify,'' said embassy
Second Secretary Sylvie Martinez. ``We haven't had a moment's peace
since.''
   Rules for the lottery are quite specific. The applications are
mailed directly to Washington, a difficult prospect to start with
in many parts of the world. The deadline is Friday.
   Each person can send only one application. It must by
typewritten, contain specific information and photographs, and be
mailed in an envelope no larger than 9{ by 4{ inches and no smaller
than 6 by 3{ inches.
   ``The people who would really benefit from a visa won't be able
to make the application,'' complained a Rome spokesman for the
private Intergovernmental Committee for Migration, which is
supported by countries including the United States. ``What
assurance do they have that it will arrive on time?''
   In impoverished Bangladesh, a business started overnight to sell
applications and envelopes following the prescribed form. An
envelope sold for about 31 cents, five times normal, and the same
price was charged to get the address typed.
   In Peru, a mail strike that started Feb. 2 has complicated
matters, with many people much too poor to afford a private courier.
   Nonetheless, the applications have been streaming toward
Washington. State Department spokeswoman Frances Jones said
hundreds of thousands are expected, although they won't be counted
until the deadline. A more restrictive lottery program for 10,000
visas in 1986 generated 1.4 million applications.
   Bangladesh authorities report 500,000 immigration applications
were sent during the first 15 days of March. With the number
expected to swell to a million, the postal service has opened
special counters and added hours.
   On line at one post office was Jalaluddin Sikder, a prayer
leader at a mosque at Savar near Dhaka, who said: ``It's a lottery,
there is no harm to try my luck. Allah will help me.''
   Golam Mostafa, a 30-year-old elementary school teacher, applied
``because I have no future here. I heard that the States is a rich
country and I will be able to lead a good life there.''
   Many applicants seemed philosophical about the daunting odds.
   Polish-born Bozena Trela, who learned of the lottery from a
translated embassy bulletin posted in a Rome hotel housing Polish
refugees, sees it as another small chance of getting to America.
   ``I'm not very hopeful I will win, but maybe if I'm lucky,''
said Trela, 30. If she gets to America, she hopes to ``earn enough
not just to exist, but to live.''
   The random selection by computer worries her, though, because
``it is a risk to let people into America without knowing their
background.''
   ``I am university educated with work experience, but how will
they know that?'' she said.
   Some who might qualify through customary immigration channels
also are applying for the lottery, hoping to reduce waits that can
add up to a decade or more for siblings of U.S. citizens. In
Poland, 3,500 immigrant visas and 70,000 temporary visas were
issued last year from more than 110,000 applications.
   Lottery applications also are coming from among the estimated
17,000 Soviet Jews in Italy waiting to enter the United States.
   ``They must also apply for this program because they no longer
are having much luck with refugee status because those quotas have
been filled,'' said Jim Wagner of the Tolstoy Foundation for Soviet
refugees in Rome.
   A Romanian mechanical engineer who defected and now must wait
for a U.S. visa at the Traiskirchen refugee camp south of Vienna,
said he learned about the lottery in a friend's letter from the
United States.
   ``If I am lucky (in the lottery) I may leave early next year. If
not, I'll have to waste more time here, which I hate because I am
not allowed to find a job and I am bored stiff doing nothing,'' he
said.
   In Thailand, where 40,000 information sheets on the program have
been passed out, Saranpat Anumutrachakit, a 24-year-old who wants
to study in the United States, sees the lottery as taking a chance.
   ``You know, it is like the Thai lottery _ you may win or you may
lose,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
