<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--SovietInspectors     03-28 0106</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Soviet Inspectors,0107</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Inspectors Arrive to Monitor Treaty Compliance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet inspectors arrived in West
Germany on Tuesday to monitor compliance with a superpower treaty
that eliminates medium- and shorter-range nuclear weapons.
   The nine Soviets would be conducting one of a series of
``short-notice'' inspections, said Lt. Col. Pat Maloney, a
spokesman for the Rhine-Main U.S. Air Force base near Frankfurt.
The sites will be announced Wednesday.
   Under the Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces treaty, 220 missiles
are being scrapped in West Germany alone. The treaty was signed in
December 1987 by then- President Ronald Reagan and Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
