<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1326EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Brazil-Strikes     03-28 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Brazil-Strikes,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transportation Strikes Slow Rio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikes by bus and train workers
Tuesday over wages slowed millions of commuters in Rio de Janeiro.
   Nearly all of the 25,000 workers in the category were on strike,
said Luis Martins, president of the Bus Workers Union. A spokesman
for employers said almost half the 6,200 buses were operating.
   The union wants a six-hour day and a 30 percent pay increase,
Martins said. Drivers make around $150 per month, and employers
have offered an 18 percent increase, he said.
   Rio's buses carry around 4 million passengers per day.
   Only 2,000 of the 11,000 train workers showed up to work,
paralyzing the government-run commuter lines in the city, said Luis
Carlos de Souza, a spokesman for the Brazilian Company of Urban
Trains.
   Train workers demanded a six-hour day and bonus pay, which
employers said was unwarranted. The trains normally carry 1 million
workers daily.
   Train and bus workers called meetings to decide whether to
continue the strikes.
</TEXT>
