<HEAD>First Albanian Delegation in Decade Visits China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albania sent its first official delegation to
China since the two former communist allies parted company more
than a decade ago, the official Xinhua News Agency said Tuesday.
   The delegation, led by Deputy Foreign Minister Muhamet Kapllani
and Foreign Trade First Deputy Minister Kostandin Hoxha, arrived in
Beijing on Tuesday for a five-day visit, Xinhua said.
   Albania was one of China's last loyal friends in the communist
camp after Mao Tse-tung split with the Soviets in 1960 and veered
sharply to the left during the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution.
   However, relations cooled with the rise to power in the late
1970s of Deng Xiaoping, a pragmatist who has transformed China with
his experiments in market-oriented economic reforms.
   The report said the Albanians will hold talks with officials
from the Foreign Ministry and from the Ministry of Foreign Economic
Relations and Trade.
   Albania, one of the world's most closed nations, has showed
signs recently of opening to both the West and its former communist
allies.
