<FIRST>r a PM-LivingInSin     03-28 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Living In Sin,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Council Tackles `Living-in-Sin' Zoning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council has tentatively voted to give
ground to both opponents and backers of Denver's ``living-in-sin''
zoning ordinance.
   The Council voted 8-5 Monday night to give tentative approval to
amendments in zoning measures that were adopted in the 1960s to
discourage hippie communes by barring unrelated people from living
together in some parts of town.
   Council members then postponed any further vote April 24.
   The exact number of residents affected by the zoning rules was
not immediately known. Denver has a population of 505,000.
   As many as 53 percent of the residences in Denver are in an R-1
zone, where a homeowner must obtain a $20 boarder's permit to cover
a non-relative. The amendments would drop the permit requirement
but would bar nieces, nephews, aunts, uncles and in-laws from
moving in, said City Councilwoman Cathy Donohue.
   Donohue, who voted for the amendments, counted that as a setback
to opponents of ``living-in-sin'' restrictions. ``Since 1956, you
have been allowed to have all these relatives in your home,'' she
said.
   A more restrictive code, called R-0 and applying to 7 percent of
Denver residences, bans boarders or unrelated people from living in
the same house. The amendments would allow two unrelated adults to
live together, but no more.
   The penalty for violating the city's ordinance is $999 a day. In
practice, Donohue said, people just move.
   The city zoning office keeps no count of boarder permits issued,
and the city attorney's office said it has no figures on people who
have challenged the law or paid the fine.
   Among those affected are three nuns who are being forced to move
out of a four-bedroom home.
   ``They wanted all but one of us to move out,'' said one of the
nuns, who asked that her name not be used. ``To me, it's wasteful
to have just one person living in a dwelling with four bedrooms.
It's very sinful.''
   Five years ago, five people challenged R-0 zoning in state
Supreme Court and lost, said Jennifer Macy, administrative
assistant to the City Council.
</TEXT>
