<FIRST>u w PM-US-JapanFighter 1stLd-Writethru a0551 03-28 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Japan Fighter, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0551,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Still Seeking Clarification On Fighter Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs graf 4, Japanese ambassador, with grafs 4-5, ambassador
asking tosee Baker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today he is still seeking
clarifications on an arrangement with Japan for joint production of
the FSX fighter plane.
   ``What I want to know is that the agreement is clear. There's no
point in having an unclear agreement. We have a lot at stake
here,'' Bush told reporters.
   The president also said the two sides were continuing to talk
and he does not know whether a Friday deadline set by Japan in
accordance with requirements of its fiscal calendar would be met.
   Japanese Ambassador Nobuo Matsunaga met with Deputy Secretary of
State Lawrence Eagleburger, the first official meeting between the
sides since a negotiating session last Thursday.
   But State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the FSX
fighter was discussed only briefly because the meeting was a
courtesy call planned before the controversy arose.
   Bush said last week that he endorsed the pact for joint
manufacture of the FSX fighter, which was concluded by the Reagan
administration, but wanted some changes to protect U.S. technology.
   Administration sources said the holdup now is over nailing down
who owns the technology that derives from the FSX project and what
percentage of the fighter should be built in the United States.
   Under the agreement signed late last year, St. Louis-based
General Dynamics would join with Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries to co-develop and co-produce the FSX as an advanced
version of the U.S. F-16 fighter.
   Proponents argue the agreement represents the best deal the
United States could negotiate in the face of Japanese opposition to
buying F-16s directly from this country. They say the deal will
promote exchanges of technology while helping U.S. industry.
   Critics contend the arrangement amounts to a giveaway of
advanced technology that Japan may use to help propel its civilian
aircraft industry into competition with the United States in the
world market. They say Tokyo should purchase American-made planes
to help offset the $50 billion U.S. trade deficit with Japan.
</TEXT>
