<FIRST>u a PM-Bush-School     03-28 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-School,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Visits High School, Hits Movies for Glamorizing Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush dropped in unannounced at a
suburban high school today, eating lunch in the school's cafeteria,
visiting a computer center and telling students ``you learn
something from every step outside the White House you take.''
   The president visited James Madison High School in Vienna, a
suburb of Washington, D.C., in advance of his upcoming release of a
package of legislative proposals dealing with education.
   Bush, who during the campaign vowed to be the ``education
president,'' first chatted with students in the school's computer
center. Then he sat on a stool in the school's library and answered
questions for nearly 30 minutes.
   Bush talked about ``this stupid abuse of drugs,'' and said
``we've got to mobilize the entertainment media'' to combat drugs,
suggesting that movies have tended to glamorize drug use over the
years.
   ``We've got to change the way this problem has been looked at,''
he said.
   He said movies often treat cocaine use ``in a humorous vein, or
made the user look like a silly idiot ....''
   ``We've got to say, look, don't put out great emotion in favor
of cocaine or other drugs. A lot of it is education. This is not
going to be solved from the White House. It's going to be solved by
the American people, young and old, saying `enough is enough.'''
   Answering a question about international terrorism, Bush said:
``It's like dealing with fog _ you can't get hold of it very well.''
   One student asked Bush how a president ``has time to visit a
high school?''
   ``A very good question,'' he replied. ``We're perfecting now an
education package. Tell you how it works: in a campaign, you get
certain themes of what you think is right for education ... It is
important that people be computer literate. I think math and
science are important. I favor magnet schools. I favor trying to
set up a system to reward the better teachers ... I think you learn
something from every step outside the White House that you take.''
   Now, Bush said, he was trying to put his campaign vows on
education into a legislative package. On his two-hour trip to the
school, Bush said: ``It's symbolic, in some sense. But you also
pick up information as you go along.''
   ``You have go balance that with your overall responsibilities,''
he added.
   On a foreign policy question, Bush said the long-sought peace in
the Middle East ``has escaped us all, escaped the world ... You
still see a lot of killing. And so, we have a particularly
important role there. We are the only country that can be a
substantial catalyst for peace there.''
   He mentioned his meetings next week with leaders from Israel,
Egypt and Jordan.
   Bush joined the students in the school cafeteria, downing a
lunch of pizza, french fries and milk.
</TEXT>
