<DOCNO> AP890328-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1400EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ScotusRdp     03-28 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus Rdp,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Strikes Down Differing Tax Treatment of Government Pensions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Tuesday barred states
from taxing federal pensions if they exempt the pensions of retired
state and local government workers.
   By an 8-1 vote, the court struck down Michigan's differing tax
treatment of the pensions received by retired government employees.
   The court's lone dissenter said the decision will affect similar
tax laws in at least 14 other states: Arizona, Colorado, Georgia,
Louisiana, Maryland, Missouri, Montana, New York, North Carolina,
Oregon, South Carolina, Virginia, West Virginia and Wisconsin.
   The challenged Michigan law ``violates principles of
intergovernmental tax immunity by favoring retired state and local
government employees over retired federal employees,'' Justice
Anthony M. Kennedy wrote for the court.
   He said Paul S. Davis, a lawyer living in East Lansing, is
entitled to a refund of $4,299 on taxes he paid from 1979 through
1984.
   Davis worked for the federal government at various times in his
career, retiring in 1980.
   He challenged the Michigan law that allows federal retirees
living in the state to deduct only up to $7,500 of their annual
federal pensions when computing their state tax liability. The law
permits retired employees of the state government and local
governments within Michigan to deduct all their state pensions from
their state taxes.
   Michigan courts had upheld the law.
   Kennedy said the law impermissibly clashes with a federal law
authorizing states to tax federal employees ``if the taxation does
not discriminate against the ... employee because of the source of
the pay or compensation.''
   The justices rejected arguments by Michigan authorities that the
law applies only to federal employees, not federal pensioners.
   The court said the inequity among government workers may not
continue. But the justices left it up to Michigan courts to decide
whether the proper remedy would be exempting all federal pensions
from state taxes or exposing the pensions of state and local
government retirees to some state taxation.
   Justice John Paul Stevens, in a spirited dissenting opinion,
said, ``I cannot join the unjustified, court-imposed restriction on
a state's power to administer its own affairs.''
   In a separate ruling, the court said federal criminal defendants
who fail to persuade a judge to dismiss their indictments because
of alleged misconduct by prosecutors cannot appeal before they are
tried and convicted.
   The unanimous ruling in a case from Buffalo, N.Y., likely means
the court will turn down two appeals that have been pending before
the justices for some time.
   In one, ex-White House aide Oliver North, former national
security adviser John M. Poindexter and arms dealer Albert Hakim
are attempting to challenge a judge's refusal to dismiss their
indictments stemming from the Iran-Contra affair.
   A federal appeals court ruled that the three could not make
their prosecutorial-misconduct appeal before they stand trial.
   North currently is on trial, and the other two are awaiting
trial.
   In a second pending case, hotel owners Harry and Leona Helmsley
are challenging their 1988 tax-evasion indictment in New York City.
   In a third decision Tuesday, the court made it easier for people
who win partial victories in civil rights lawsuits to get their
lawyer fees paid by the losing side.
   The court ruled unanimously in a Texas case that those who
prevail on a ``significant'' issue in such suits are entitled to
reimbursement even if they lose on the case's ``central'' issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890328-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1409EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Laws     03-28 0775</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Laws,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Can Sue Government, Under New Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese will be allowed to sue their government
under a new law submitted Tuesday, but a noted legal scholar said
the legislation comes down heavily on the side of protecting the
state.
   Another law, also submitted Tuesday, delineates the powers of
the National People's Congress, China's legislature. It, too,
favors a centralization of power.
   Both laws are expected to pass as submitted during the current
session of the legislature.
   The legislation allowing the lawsuits, officially known as the
Administrative Procedure Law, completes a series of legislation
promulgated since 1979 which aim at instituting a rule of law in
China.
   In 1979, China passed its criminal code law, allowing the state
to take the people to court. In 1985, it passed a law on civil
suits, allowing people to sue each other.
   Under a draft of the new law, Chinese may sue their government
and its agencies if their ``lawful rights and interests have been
infringed upon by a specific administrative act of an
administrative organ or its personnel.''
   Infringement can include fines, the restriction of ``freedom,''
refusal by an administrative bureau to carry out a task, and the
compulsory seizure of property.
   The main problem is that the law allows Chinese people to
challenge the legality of an act but not the law itself. Thus, if
the government can prove its action was based on a law, no suit can
be brought, according to the draft.
   Zhang Shuyi, a researcher at the Political Science and Law
College of China, said this problem shows the law ``doesn't
adequately protect the interests of the people.''
   Writing in the World Economic Herald, Zhang said the law ``ends
up protecting the government more than anything else.''
   ``The strange thing is that for the longest time we've turned a
blind eye to the violation of the people's rights,'' he said, ``but
at soon as someone says the people should be allowed to sue,
somebody says we have to protect the interests of the government.
   ``Since when do we have to protect the power of the
government?'' he said. ``The goverment by its nature is power.''
   The key to understanding this problem is that lawmakers and
executors in China want to ensure the courts don't become too
powerful, he said.
   ``This is not like the United States where they have a
separation of powers and the various departments battle on an equal
footing,'' he said. ``The goal is to keep the courts weak.''
   Since the communist revolution in 1949, law was regarded as
``bourgeois,'' and a ``tool of capitalist society.''
   But in reality, political campaigns and purges since 1957,
culminating in the ultra-leftist Cultural Revolution, resulted in a
massive infringement of basic rights. Red Guards closed the
schools, religion was repressed, and people were jailed, beaten and
killed because they were born into a family that once belonged to
the upper classes.
   Beginning in 1978, a reform movement to open China to the West
and introduce elements of a market economy into the state-run
system pushed change in the legal system.
   Reformers, led by Deng Xiaoping, were concerned they did not
repeat the abuses of the past. They also were sensitive to the
demands for legal protection for foreign clients who want to do
business in China.
   Major problems remain, however.
   Although China's constitution guarantees freedom of opinion,
thousands of prisoners remain jailed for political beliefs. In
addition, the courts remain powerless when compared to the
Communist Party and the administrative wing of the government.
   An example appeared on the front page of Sunday's People's
Daily, which reported that three lawyers were arrested and jailed
for several months because they chose to enter an innocent plea for
a rape suspect. The prosecutor's office disagreed with the plea and
ordered them jailed on charges of ``protecting a criminal,'' the
paper said.
   Their case eventually was taken up by the National People's
Congress and they were released.
   Another problem with the legal system concerns the function of
the congress, ostensibly responsible for making laws in China.
   Under the second piece of legislation submitted Tuesday, the
congress can only propose laws after 30 of the approximately 3,000
delegates submit a bill and it passes the inspection of the
congress' Presidium.
   Since the Presidium is nominated by the State Council, China's
Cabinet, the effect of the law is to further centralize government
power in the council's hands. The law, known as the Rules of
Procedure for the National People's Congress, gives the State
Council power to submit legislation directly. The Communist Party
controls the State Council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
