<FIRST>r a AM-AbuDhabi     03-28 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abu Dhabi,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court: Arab Ruler Can't Claim Immunity From Questioning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the United Arab Emirates
can't avoid questioning in a lawsuit involving his personal
investments by claiming ``head of state immunity,'' New York
state's top court ruled Tuesday.
   His Highness Sheik Zayed bin Sultan al-Nahyan, who rules Abu
Dhabi, the capital of the United Arab Emirates, must submit himself
to a deposition before litigation involving $96 million can be
resolved, the New York Court of Appeals said in a unanimous
decision.
   Sheik Zayed's testimony is needed to resolve a flurry of
lawsuits involving Lasidi, S.A., a Swiss investment firm, and
Financiera Avenida, a Panamanian firm, both of which funneled the
Arab leader's money into overseas investments.
   The Panamanian company sued Lasidi, S.A., claiming it used the
Sheik's funds in an unauthorized manner, the court said. The Swiss
company launched a defamation suit and asked for the Sheik's
testimony.
   Lower courts dismissed Avenida's lawsuits because the Sheik
refused to give a deposition, claiming he didn't have to under the
international common-law doctrine of ``head of state immunity.''
The Court of Appeals upheld the lower court rulings.
   ``The Sheik cannot seek to recover some $96 million in personal
funds by counterclaims brought in an American court through his
corporate alter ego while at the same time invoking head of state
immunity as a means of insulating himself from discovery on the
matters directly related to the substance of those counterclaims,''
the court wrote.
   Since Avenida is a corporate shell, with no functioning officers
or directors, there's no one else for the lawyers to talk to, the
court said.
</TEXT>
