<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-TankerSpill 2ndLd-Writethru a0541 03-28 1081</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0541,1114</SECOND>
<HEAD>Port Reopens; Authorities Investigate Pilot's Drinking</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 18 grafs to UPDATE with port reopening; PICKS UP
16th graf pvs, `The goo ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing; LaserGraphic NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The harbor reopened and a fleet of tankers
anchored offshore churned in to pick up oil today for the first
time since the biggest spill in U.S. history closed the port at the
southern end of the Alaskan pipeline.
   Authorities, meanwhile, investigated reports that the captain of
the tanker responsible for the 100-square-mile spill in Prince
William Sound had drinking problems, and winds that had the oil
moving ``like it's on a superhighway'' died down.
   At the White House, President Bush said that the federal
government would consider taking over the cleanup after top
officials travel to Alaska today ``to take a hard look at where
this disaster stands.''
   Coast Guard Lt. Ed Wieliczkiewicz said an Arco tanker would be
the first to arrive at the Valdez marine terminal, and nine other
tankers would follow. He said the oil slick spreading across the
sound was clear of shipping lanes.
   The port had been closed since the accident Friday, cutting the
flow through the Alaska pipeline, which supplies nearly 20 percent
of the nation's domestic oil. Some industry experts had predicted
sharp price increases from an extended shutdown.
   The accident reduced the oil flow through the pipeline to
800,000 barrels a day from 2.1 million.
   ``We look at all areas in an investigation and that's an area of
concern,'' National Transportation Safety Board spokesman Bill
Woody said of reports that Exxon Valdez Capt. Joseph Hazelwood had
a drunken driving conviction as recently as September.
   Hazelwood probably will be required to testify at NTSB hearings
that begin April 4, Woody said.
   Hazelwood, 42, was not on the bridge when the vessel left
shipping lanes on Friday to avoid ice and ran aground, said Exxon
officials. The third mate, who did not have proper certification,
was in charge, company President Frank Iarossi said.
   Investigators said the results of drug and alcohol tests on crew
members will be made public perhaps in two or three days.
   Hazelwood pleaded guilty in 1984 to driving while intoxicated
after an accident near his home in Huntington, N.Y., The New York
Times reported today. He was convicted of drunken driving in
September in New Hampshire and his license was revoked, the paper
said. His driver's license had been suspended on two other
occasions during the past five years, the Time said.
   The cleanup Monday was set back by 70 mph gusts that swept the
slick more than 30 miles toward the southwest. But gusts died down
to 13 mph today, officials said.
   Beaches on four uninhabited islands have been fouled, and the
slick fast approached sensitive salmon-spawning areas.
   The cleanup ``is not proceeding well _ believe me, that is an
understatement,'' Iarossi said Monday. ``We've got a mess on our
hands.''
   ``It's unbelievable. That slick is moving like it's on a
superhighway,'' said Iarossi.
   Fewer than 135,000 gallons of oil have been recovered from the
10.1 million-gallon spill.
   Asked whether he was satisfied with Exxon's efforts, Bush said,
``They're certainly making a good beginning here, but there are
some conflicting reports on that. I don't want to prejudge that.''
   Bush said Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner, Environmental
Protection Agency Administrator Bill Reilly and Coast Guard
Commandant Paul Yost would evaluate the operation first hand and
that a federal takeover is ``an option.''
   The goo also threatened the region's abundant herring, marine
mammals and seabirds, biologists said.
   ``There are bird populations all over the place,'' said Pamela
Bergman, an Interior Department spokeswoman. Nearly 100 oiled birds
and two oiled sea otters have been spotted, and many more stricken
animals likely have gone undetected, she said.
   The cleanup was getting more difficult as the leading edge of
the slick moves into more remote areas of the sparsely inhabited
sound.
   Bergman and others said efforts to rescue thousands of animals
were hampered by fears that volunteers would be endangered in the
remote area, with its rugged shores, harsh weather and powerful
wild animals. Also, any animals rescued could die in the time it
would take to transport them to a hospital.
   The 987-foot tanker was carrying 1.2 million barrels of North
Slope crude oil when it ran aground.
   About 240,000 barrels spilled through the hull, creating the
slick that has spread to more than 100 square miles.
   The Port of Valdez has been closed since the accident, stranding
tankers and cutting production on the North Slope, which supplies
nearly 20 percent of the nation's domestic oil.
   Coast Guard Cmdr. Steven McCall, however, said he planned to
reopen the port today.
   The vessel remained stuck on Bligh Reef, about 25 miles from
Valdez. Iarossi said the wind pivoted the ship 12 degrees to the
north, and that the crew said the new position felt much more
stable.
   Iarossi and Exxon spokesman Don Cornett said efforts to unload
the 1 million barrels that remained on board the vessel were
progressing well. Iarossi said Exxon hoped to have about 95 percent
of the remaining oil off the vessel in three or four days.
   Cornett said it appeared increasingly likely salvage crews will
be able to unload the Exxon Valdez, refloat it and get it to
drydock without spilling more oil.
   The wind did damage some of the containment booms used to corral
the oil, Iarossi said.
   Fishermen held a news conference Monday to complain that Exxon
was not taking adequate steps to warn cleanup workers and nearby
villagers about the health threat from the oil and from burning it
with jelled gasoline.
   Smoke from test burns conducted on the spill last week prompted
complaints of nausea and severe headaches among residents of
Tatitlek, a village of 100.
   ``You're talking about fish. We're talking about human lives,''
said Norman Vlasoff. ``The whole village is getting sick.''
   Gov. Steve Cowper has declared Prince William Sound a disaster
area and said he would seek federal money to help with the spill.
   ``I think sorting out the money is something that will occupy
lawyers for years to come,'' Cowper said. ``We will do everything
possible to make sure the industry pays for this.''
   Cornett said the company has no cost estimate for the cleanup,
which could take months.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   David Foster is the AP's Northwest regional
reporter, based in Seattle.
</TEXT>
