<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     03-28 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korean Dissident Meets with Communist Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South Korean dissident defied his
government and met with North Korean President Kim Il Sung to
discuss reunification of the two nations, it was reported Tuesday.
   The Rev. Moon Ik-hwan and Kim held talks Monday that were
``overflowing with compatriotic sentiments'' about ways to end the
division of the Korean peninsula, according to North Korea's news
agency.
   Kim told Moon that since ``national reunification is a
nationwide cause, anyone may come even individually, if he wants to
discuss the question of reunification, and we will welcome him,''
the Korean Central News Agency said.
   On Tuesday, Moon visited Kim's birthplace, a favorite North
Korean tourist spot, and watched a revolutionary opera, the news
agency said.
   Moon's visit has provoked controversy in South Korea, where
government officials say he is serving North Korean interests.
Public opinion appears to be against his trip.
   The visit also has fueled demands from Seoul hardliners for a
crackdown on South Korea's dissident groups. Prosecutors in Seoul
said Monday that Moon will be prosecuted for aiding North Korea
when he returns.
   South Koreans cannot visit North Korea without government
permission.
   Moon's secret visit came shortly after President Roh Tae-woo
ordered a crackdown on dissidents and radical students he allleged
were trying to stage a leftist revolution. Roh cited the threat in
justifying his decision March 20 to indefinitely postpone a
promised referendum on his leadership.
   Police seized more than 3,000 copies of allegedly pro-North
Korean books and arrested 11 publishers in raids Monday night in
Seoul as part of Roh's suppression of leftist groups, prosecutors
said.
   North Korea appealed for Koreans on both sides of the border to
take a more active part in efforts to reunify the peninsula. It
said South Korean authorities, along with the United States, sought
to keep the division.
   The news agency said North Korean political parties and
organizations met Monday and declared that reunification is not a
task ``confined to specified classes and strata or to the
authorities.''
   ``To our regret,'' the agency said, ``the South Korean
authorities are openly suppressing the efforts of South Korean
personages and organizations or various circles to have dialogues
with the North.''
   It said, ``If people meet and hold a dialogue, they can easily
come to understanding and pool their will and ... turn the
atmosphere of confrontation into that of unity and resolve the
tangled problems between the authorities without much difficulty.''
   Also on Tuesday, sports officials from both countries reported
progress on forming a joint team for the 1990 Asian Games in
Beijing.
   Aside from the sports talks, begun March 9, the two Koreas have
been holding intermittent talks since August on improving
relations. Little progress has been made as each side has tended to
push its own proposals.
   The peninsula has been divided since the end of World War II in
1945. North Korea's invasion in 1950 triggered a three-year war,
and the two sides continue to station thousands of troops along
their border.
</TEXT>
