<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1527EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Nielsens     03-28 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nielsens,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Roseanne,' and `Brewster Place' Women Almost Spoil NBC Streak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC tied CBS' 26-year-old record of 40 weeks
atop the Nielsens last week by barely edging ABC, whose
``Roseanne'' and ``The Women of Brewster Place'' came in first and
second.
   ``We were lucky,'' said Gerald Jaffe, NBC's vice president for
research projects. He said NBC would be lucky to win again next
week to become the all-time record-holder, because ABC has the
Academy Awards on Wednesday.
   But for the week ending March 26, according to the A.C. Nielsen
Co., NBC had an average, prime-time rating of 14.9, half a rating
point in front of ABC, which had a 14.4. CBS trailed with 11.6. NBC
has won all 27 weeks in the season to date, plus 13 in a row before
that. The last time a network won 40 weeks in a row was when CBS
did it during the 1962-63 television season.
   It appears unlikely that CBS will catch ABC for second place
this season. With only three weeks to go _ the 1987-88 television
season has an asterisk beside it because of delays caused by last
summer's writers' strike _ NBC has an average 16.1 to ABC's 12.9
and CBS' 12.6.
   ABC's ``Roseanne'' was the top-rated show of the week for the
third week in a row, with a rating of 25.7 and a 38 share. The
second half of ``The Women of Brewster Place,'' starring Oprah
Winfrey who was also co-executive producer, had a 24.5 and a 38
share. It became the highest-rated, two-part movie this season.
   Each rating point represents 904,000 households with
televisions. The share is a percentage of sets in use.
   The rest of the top 10 were: ``The Cosby Show'' NBC, ``Who's the
Boss?'' ABC, ``The Wonder Years'' ABC, ``The Golden Girls'' NBC,
``Day by Day Special'' NBC, ``Cheers'' NBC, ``Empty Nest'' NBC and
``L.A. Law'' NBC.
   CBS was shut out of the top 10. Its highest-rated show, ``60
Minutes,'' was 13th.
   Some venerable old-timers made a showing. The 29-year-old tape
of Mary Ma as ``Peter Pan'' ranked 21st with a
16.1 rating and a 27 share. NBC broadcast it Friday night for the
first time since 1973.
   ABC also goecent showing out of the 1956 epic ``The Ten
Commandments.'' It was 31st with a 14.7 rating and26 share.
   Among the spring tryouts, NBC's `antum Leap'' premiered at a
respectable 30th. Co new Monday comedies, ``Live In'' and
``Heartld mediocre performances, landing in 41st and 44th
place, respectively. ABC's new ``Men'' was a lowly 71st in the
rankings.
   The lowest-rated network shows of the week were: ``Hard Time on
Planet Earth,'' ``NCAA Basketball Championship Thursday Prega
``A Man Called Hawk,'' ``Mission Impossible,'' ``Purple Hearts,''
``The Shaggy Dog, Part One,'' ``HeartBeat,'' ``West 57th,'' ``Men''
and ``TV 101.''
   ``ABC World News Tonight'' won the news race, edging the ``CBS
Evening News,'' which was affected by NCAA basketball pre-emptions.
ABC had a 10.8 and 20 share, CBS a 10.5 and 20 share, ``NBC Nightly
News'' a 9.6 and 19 share.
</TEXT>
