<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1942EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     03-28 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Operation Behind Because of U.N. Budget Delay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations is two to three
weeks behind schedule in preparing an observer force for the
Namibian independence process, which begins Saturday, a top-ranking
official said Tuesday.
   Also Tuesday, officials reported the first gunfire against U.N.
soldiers in Namibia, but there were no injuries.
   The wrangle in the U.N. General Assembly over how much to spend
on the one-year operation and how many observers to send cut
drastically into time available for logistical arrangements, said
Cedric Thornberry of Ireland, the main assistant to U.N. Special
Representative Martti Ahtisaari.
   ``We had told them we needed a minimum of six to eight weeks. We
got a month,'' Thornberry said. ``But it looks like we will start
on April 1.''
   Ahtisaari, a Finn, is scheduled to arrive Saturday to oversee
U.N. efforts to ensure that South Africa conducts free elections in
the territory it has controlled for 74 years.
   The voting, planned for the first week in November, will be to
choose a constituent assembly that will write a constitution and
organize Namibia's first independent black majority-ruled
government.
   ``We are not going to delay the elections,'' Thornberry said,
``except in the case of something being done or not done that would
interfere with the fairness of the election. Then we would stop the
clock.''
   He said most of the U.N. military units are in position, but the
arrival of civilian workers and police monitors may be delayed
because of the lack of accommodation and vehicles.
   The U.N. group will consist of 4,650 U.N. peacekeepers, 500
police monitors, about 620 election monitors from various nations,
more than 760 U.N. civilian administrators and about 820 locally
hired staff.
   Ahtisaari said 803 military staff and 129 civilians are already
in Namibia. Thornberry said he expects the South African
administrator-general of the territory, Louis Pienaar, soon will
begin repealing discriminatory laws that might interfere with a
fair election and start the process of freeing political prisoners.
   But in the meantime, he said, the South Africans remain in
charge of border controls and law enforcement. He said there is no
plan to force repeal of laws which restrict hospitals and schools
by race.
   He said there would be discussions about Pienaar's plan to set
the voting age in Namibia at 21, rather than 18 as in South Africa.
Government opponents say Pienaar wants to restrict the numbers of
younger voters who may be more likely to favor the South-West
African People's Organization, or SWAPO, which fought South African
rule since 1966.
   The mission is budgeted at $416 million, of which over $52
million has already been collected from U.N. member states.
Ahtisaari said the total will go over $100 million by late next
week when some major pledges are paid.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia for 74 years, since it captured
the colony from Germany during World War I.
   In 1920, the League of Nations granted Pretoria a mandate to
govern Namibia. In 1966 the U.N. General Assembly revoked that
mandate, but the world body was unable to wrest control of the
mineral-rich territory from South Africa.
   In December, South Africa signed accords with Angola and Cuba
agreeing to free Namibia if 50,000 Cuban troops stationed in Angola
are sent home by mid-1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
