<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia Bjt   03-28 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia, Bjt,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Least 21 Killed, Scores Injured in Kosovo Riots</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New battles broke out Tuesday
between police and ethinic Albanians who oppose new laws giving
Serbia more control over Kosovo province, and officials said 21
people had been killed in two days of fighting.
   The federal Interior Ministry said scores were injured. It said
extra police were being sent to Kosovo to try to quell violence
that began Monday and resumed Tuesday in at least 10 cities and
towns.
   An Associated Press reporter saw tanks and other military
vehicles on the roads outside Pristina, the provincial capital.
Army units were bivouacked in fields along the main roads into
Kosovo and police at roadblocks checked the identities of travelers.
   In Belgrade, capital of both Yugoslavia and of Serbia, its
largest republic, thousands of Serbs gathered in the streets to
celebrate of the constitutional changes.
   Kosovo's own legislature passed the constitutional changes last
Wednesday and the Serbian parliament approved them Tuesday.
   Protests in Kosovo, which was the heart of ancient Serbia but
now is 85 percent ethnic Albanian, began after the provincial
lawmakers acted and turned violent Monday.
   In one confrontation Tuesday, police killed an 18-year-old and
wounded 14 protesters when they opened fire after shots came from a
stone-throwing crowd of about 500 in Zur, near the Albanian border,
the official news agency Tanjug reported.
   The official death toll was the highest reported in Kosovo's
ethnic unrest.
   At least nine paople are known to have died during riots in
1981, when martial law was improsed briefly. Saturday is the
anniversary of those riots.
   Authorities imposed a dusk-to-dawn curfew Tuesday in Kosovo and
banned public gatherings of more than three people. Schools,
theaters, movie houses and sports stadiums were closed indefinitely.
   Tanjug reported trouble in at least 10 towns before the curfew
hour. It said police repeatedly faced groups of between 50 and 400
stone-throwing youths that formed quickly and were dispersed with
clubs and tear gas.
   Shots occasionally were fired from the crowds, as in Zur, the
agency said.
   Some of Monday's worst violence occurred in Pristina, but the
town was comparatively calm Tuesday and was quiet after the curfew
hour.
   Dozens of military vehicles were visible during the day and riot
police patrolled in bulletproof vests. Sonic booms cracked as
military jets flew low overhead, a tactic used in Pristina
previously to discourage unrest.
   The federal Interior Ministry said two policemen were shot and
killed Monday and 25 had been injured, five seriously, in the two
days of violence. Nineteen protesters were killed and 49 injured,
and police were not responsible for all the deaths, the ministry
said.
   It said 146 of the ``most aggressive'' demonstrators were
detained. Hundreds of ethnic Albanians have been jailed in Kosovo
since a partial state of emergency was imposed last month.
   According to Tanjug, the ministry said the violence displayed
elements of ``an armed uprising,'' with snipers firing on police
from high floors of buildings. It blamed the trouble on ethnic
Albanian separatists and nationalists working with ``hostile
emigres'' and ``foreign factors.''
   In Serbia, nationalist demonstrations and rallies were reported
in towns, factories and schools.
   Flags waved in the center of Belgrade, which was closed for the
occasion. Thousands of people milled around podiums and stages to
hear speeches and folk musicians.
   Slobodan Milosevic, the Serbian Communist Party chief and
architect of the changes, received a standing ovation in the
republic's parliament.
   Hundreds of thousands of Serbs have rallied in central
Yugoslavia in recent months to press Milosevic's demands for
greater control over Kosovo's schools, judiciary and police force.
   Serbs say the changes are necessary to protect the Slavic
minority in Kosovo. They and others claim there is an underground
movement in Kosovo that seeks to unite it with Albania.
</TEXT>
