<FIRST>r w AM-MIARemains     03-28 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MIA Remains,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Team May Have Found More Americans' Remains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of U.S. military officials is returning
to Hawaii on Wednesday after excavating in Laos remains thought to
be American servicemen missing from the Vietnam War, the Pentagon
said Tuesday.
   Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief spokesman, said it was
impossible at this point to say how many sets of remains had been
found. Attempts will now be made to identify the remains at the
Army's Central Identification Laboratory in Honolulu, he said.
   The excavation lasted eight days and was conducted at the site
where an Army CH-34 helicopter crashed in November 1968, Howard
continued. Seven crewmen were lost when the helicopter disappeared,
he said.
   ``The Joint U.S.-Lao excavation in Savannakhet Province
concluded March 26,'' Howard said.
   ``Human remains found at the site, which may be associated with
Americans missing in Laos, will be analyzed'' at the Army
laboratory, he added.
   ``The team also surveyed four other potential aircraft crash
sites in southern Laos to aid in determining possible future
excavation sites.''
   According to the Pentagon, 545 of the 2,371 Americans still
missing from the Vietnam War are listed as missing in Laos.
</TEXT>
