<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 2021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Panama     03-28 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Accuses Noriega of Fostering Harassment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Tuesday accused
Panamanian leader Manuel Antonio Noriega of fostering harassment
against U.S. military personnel and workers at the Panama Canal.
   ``There's clearly a deliberate effort by the Noriega regime to
harrass U.S. and Panamanian citizen employees of the U.S.
government,'' said department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler.
   The statement comes as William R. Gianelli, chairman of the
Panama Canal Commission, has expressed fears the campaign of
harassment could jeopardize continued use of the waterway.
   His office has issued a statement urging countries that send
ships through the canal to pressure Noriega to end the harassment.
   Over the past several months, members of Noriega's Panamanian
Defense Forces have accosted canal workers and U.S. military
personnel stationed in Panama. The incidents have increased as
U.S.-Panamanian relations have worsened.
   Noriega is under indictment in Florida on drug trafficking
charges and the United States has refused to recognize the
authority of Noriega's ally, President Manuel Solis Palma.
   As the United States continued pressing its campaign to force
Noriega to step down, the Panamanian government began to take steps
against the canal workers, such as denying them license plates for
their cars.
   In one incident earlier this month, several buses containing
children attending the U.S. military-run schools were detained for
nine hours because they allegedly did not have the proper license
plates.
   The Panamanian government now states that in order to obtain
license plates, the driver must prove he or she has paid local
taxes. But Washington has barred tax payments to Panama as part of
its program of economic sanctions against the Noriega regime.
   Asked about reports of continued acts of intimidation directed
against the U.S. military protecting the canal and the Americans
and Panamanians who work there, Ms. Tutwiler said the United States
intends to fulfill its role under the 1977 Panama Canal treaties.
   Under the pacts, the United States has the primary
responsibility for the canal's operation and its defense until Dec.
31, 1999, after which Panama assumes responsibility and sovereignty
over the waterway.
   ``We respect our treaty commitments and intend to meet our
obligations to ensure the canal's safe, efficient, uninterrupted
operation,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   Asked whether the United States intends to increase its security
in the area if harassment continues, Ms. Tutwiler replied only that
``we will continue to meet our treaty responsibilities.''
   The United States has about 10,000 military personnel in Panama
to defend the Panama Canal. Most of the about 8,000 employees
working at the canal are Panamanian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890328-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 2004EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearSafety     03-28 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Safety,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>10 Years After TMI, Nuclear Plants Still Unsafe, Group Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nuclear power plants are ``a danger to the
public's health and safety,'' an advocacy group charged Tuesday,
releasing a report that showed more than 33,000 nuclear plant
incidents have occurred in the 10 years since the Three Mile Island
accident.
   The study, ``Nuclear Power Safety: 1979-1989,'' charts an
increase at the beginning of the decade followed by a leveling off
in the number of reported events at nuclear plants.
   The incidents include failures or breakdowns of plant systems
and procedures which may pose a threat to public safety. The
operating utility must report these incidents to the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission by filing a ``Licensee Event Report,'' or LER.
   The report was released a decade after the March 28, 1978
accident at Three Mile Island, the nuclear power plant in
Pennsylvania where the nation's worst commercial atomic plant
accident occurred.
   Since the Three Mile Island accident, no utilities have begin
construction of nuclear plants. There are now 108 operating nuclear
plants in the nation.
   ``Although some of these mishaps may seem relatively innocuous,
it should be remembered that when combined in sequence, these
seemingly small incidents can result in a major nuclear accident _
as was the case at TMI,'' said the report, prepared by Public
Citizen, an organization founded by consumer activist Ralph Nader.
   The NRC has a system for grading the severity of LERs, but
Public Citizen did not take this into account, presenting only
total numbers of LERs.
   ``A decade after the accident at Three Mile Island, the NRC and
the nuclear industry have forgotten the lesson of TMI,'' said Joan
Claybrook, Public Citizen's president. ``The plants pose a
continuing danger to the public's health and safety.''
   But NRC spokesman Joseph Fouchard said the plants are safer than
a decade ago, and noted that ``Public Citizen gets its numbers from
us and, of course, analyzes them in its own way.''
   ``There have been fewer challenges to the system, fewer
automatic shutdowns, the amount of waste generated at these plants
has gone down, they're cleaner, and the amount of cumulative
radiation exposure to employees has gone down,'' Fouchard said.
``All of the safety indicators are going in a positive direction.''
   In 1979, there were 2,310 reported mishaps at the nation's 67
nuclear reactors, including the partial meltdown of TMI 2 in
Middletown, Pa. The number increased to 3,804 in 1980, to 4,060 in
1981, and to 4,500 in 1982. By 1983, the number of reported
incidents exceeded 5,000 at 82 operating plants, the group found.
   In 1984, however, the NRC changed its system for reporting such
events, and the total number of LERs dropped to 2,460 that year,
according to Public Citizen.
   The following year, 1985, there were 3,050 LERs and the NRC said
the period was one of the worst years in the history of the nuclear
power industry, marked by 645 emergency plant shutdowns and 38
fines totaling nearly $4 million levied against utilities.
   Since then, the number of nuclear plant mishaps has apparently
leveled off, although ``even the NRC's data is incomplete and thus
these figures probably do not reflect the entire sum of reportable
mishaps each year,'' the report said.
   For example, in 1984, the first year that the new reporting
requirements were in effect, the NRC estimated that between 12
percent and 35 percent of reportable mishaps were not reported, the
study said.
   ``If the NRC's assessment is correct, the LER count per reactor
simply reflects the mishaps which the industry chooses to report,
while the actual number of potentially significant safety events
may be much higher,'' Public Citizen said.
   The number of LERs has remained relatively constant since 1985:
2,960 in 1986 and 2,955 in 1987. Incomplete data for 1988 reveled
2,296 mishaps at the nation's 108 licensed-to-operate reactors.
   Total mishaps for the 10 years: 33,475.
   The report is a compilation of findings from Public Citizen's
annual nuclear power safety reports and preliminary data being
gathered for the group's forthcoming 1988 report. The data were
obtained under Freedom of Information act requests and from other
NRC sources.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890328-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Bush Bjt   03-28 0798</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, Bjt,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Fields Questions on Surprise Trip to High School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush paid a surprise visit to a
suburban high school Tuesday and fielded questions on subjects
ranging from drugs to the Middle East, telling students: ``You
learn something from every step outside the White House you take.''
   Bush also ate lunch in the school cafeteria where, surrounded by
several hundred chattering teenagers, he munched on pizza and
french fries and sipped milk through a straw.
   In the excurison, which was unannounced and for which the
school's principal had only 90 minutes' warning, the president
travelled by motorcade to James Madison High School in this
Virginia suburb, about 15 miles from the White House.
   The president, who during the campaign vowed to be ``the
education president,'' first chatted with students in the school's
computer center, then perched on a stool in the library and
answered questions for 30 minutes.
   ``Anybody got any questions about my line of work?'' Bush asked.
   One student asked about the new White House puppies. ``They're
doing fine,'' Bush said. Another student asked Bush how a president
``has time to visit a high school.''
   ``A very good question,'' Bush said. ``I think you learn
something from every step outside the White House that you take.
... It's symbolic, in some sense. But you also pick up information
as you go along. You have to balance that with your overall
responsibilities.''
   The trip comes in advance of Bush's submission to Congress of an
education package, expected to include a variety of proposals
highlighted in Bush's budget speech to Congress last month,
including the first installment in a $500 million national merit
schools initiative, an effort to reward the nation's best teachers,
a $100 million expansion of a magnet schools program and an
expansion of Head Start.
   Bush aide Stephen Hart said that the legislation would be
submitted to Congress sometime ``within the next few weeks,'' but
that now specific date had yet been spent.
   Bush talked with the students about ``this stupid abuse of
drugs,'' and said ``we've got to mobilize the entertainment media''
to combat drugs, suggesting that movies have tended to trivilize
drug use in recent years.
   He said movies of late have tended portrayed cocaine use ``in a
humerous vein, or made the user look like a silly idiot. ...''
   ``W've got to change the way this problem has been looked at,''
Bush said.
   Answering a question about international terrorism, Bush said,
``It's like dealing with fog _ you can't get hold of it very well.''
   On a foreign policy question, Bush said that the long-sought
peace in the Middle East ``has escaped us all, escaped the world.
... You still see a lot of killing. And so, we have a particularly
important role there; we are the only country that can be a
substantial catalyst for peace there.''
   He said he hoped some progress toward the peace process could
come from his meetings next week with the leaders of Israel, Egypt
and Jordan.
   Asked a question on drugs and guns, the president cited the
review going on in his administration on semiautomatic assault
weapons. ``There's a lot of laws on the books that need to be
enforced and maybe there's a need for more laws.
   ``You have to balance out all those interests.''
   Sami Van Vliet, a 16-year-old junior, told Bush her church group
had inflated balloons for the annual White House Easter Egg Roll
the day before but were prevented from taking extra balloons home
with them because they were ``government property.''
   She complained that the group had wanted ``to take some of the
balloons to Ghana for our mission trip that we're going on.''
   ``I was just wondering what you do with 10,000 balloons that
say, `A Family Easter at the White House, 1989?'' she asked.
   ``If only I had known about it, you'd have been able to carry
more than that one with you,'' Bush said.
   Another student invited Bush to speak at the school's graduation
on June 15, asking him, ``How busy is your schedule?''
   ``I don't know how busy it is. I don't even dare look till
tomorrow. But thanks for the invite,'' he said.
   A spokesman for Fairfax County schools, Dolores Bowen, said the
Education Department had asked for information on seven or eight
schools Monday afternoon.
   At 7:30 a.m. today, a White House advance team showed up to meet
with principal Edward Ryan, who thought the officials were there to
set up a visit, possibly by first lady Barbara Bush, sometime in
the future.
   About 9:30 a.m., roughly 90 minutes before Bush arrived, Ryan
learned his visitor would be the president and he would be there
before the morning was out.
</TEXT>
