<SECOND>AM-US-Vincennes,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Still No Approach for Compensating Families of 290 Aboard Iranian
Airliner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iraq-Compensation, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has been unable to come up
with an approach for compensating families of the 290 people who
died when the USS Vincennes shot down an Iranian airliner over the
Persian Gulf last year, a U.S. official said Tuesday.
   ``Nothing much has happened,'' said the official who has
knowledge about the situation and spoke on condition of not being
identified.
   Then-President Reagan had said families of the victims of last
July's tragedy would be compensated but that no other reparations
would be made. The administration said compenation must go to the
families and not to the government of Iran.
   The official said the government viewed the compensation as
``simply an expression of grief for the loss of life,'' and that no
liability has been assumed for the incident.
   The official said the United States has received a passenger
list from the Iranians, but specifics such as age and other
information about the individuals have not been obtained.
   Such information is needed to help determine the compensation,
he said.
   ``We've tried a number of channels to obtain information,'' but
nothing has been accomplished over the past several months, the
official said.
   The United States broke formal diplomatic relations with Iran
after the 1979 takeover of the U.S. Embassy in Tehran.
</TEXT>
