<FIRST>r w AM-Justice-Reorganization     03-28 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Justice-Reorganization,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Office Created</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As part of a Justice Department
reorganization, Attorney General Dick Thornburgh is creating a new
Office of Policy Development and abolishing the Office of Legal
Policy, and on Tuesday he appointed the current legislative affairs
chief to lead the new office.
   Thomas M. Boyd, 42, who has been assistant attorney general in
charge of the Office of Legislative Affairs for the past year, said
Monday in an interview that as the new office's director, he will
be ``working with the attorney general in his capacity as chairman
of the Domestic Policy Council'' and ``developing policy for the
department to implement.''
   The office will replace the current Office of Legal Policy, said
Thornburgh aide David Runkel, who said he did not know if the 29
people in that office, including a dozen attorneys, will be laid
off or transferred to the new office.
   Boyd is a rare Justice Department holdover from the Reagan
administration.
   Runkel said Edward S.G. Dennis, the assistant attorney general
in charge of the Criminal Division, is expected to remain in that
post, saying, ``There are no current plans for any changes in the
Criminal Division.''
   Elsewhere in the department, Runkel said New York lawyer Robert
B. Fiske, a former U.S. attorney in Manhattan, is a ``leading
candidate'' to become deputy attorney general, the Justice
Department's second-ranking position.
   Thornburgh earlier had taken away the Legal Policy Office's
mandate to conduct screening of judicial candidates, and the new
Policy Development Office will not be involved in that effort
either, Runkel said.
</TEXT>
