<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 2044EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MusicFestival     03-28 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Music Festival,0240</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 10th anniversary of New Music America, a
69-event contemporary music festival, will be hosted this year by
the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
   Harvey Lichtenstein, president of the Brooklyn Academy, made the
announcement Tuesday at the Kitchen in Manhattan. The festival,
which has been held in a different city each year, started at the
Kitchen and featured Laurie Anderson, Steve Reich and Philip Glass.
   Lichtenstein said that New Music America will be held Nov. 10-18
and will be a major component of the Brooklyn Academy's seventh
annual Next Wave Festival. He said the festival ``reflects BAM's
interest in exploring new directions in the performing arts.''
   New Music America will present 104 ensembles and composers
working in extended forms of rock, jazz, classical and electronic
music. Performances are scheduled in 23 locations. For the first
time, a Recording Industry Council will help support the festival.
   A group of radio stations will record the festival and make the
concerts available the next day, via satellite, to more than 300
U.S. radio stations. On the final night, radio stations in four
cities will record different concerts in each of the Brooklyn
Academy's four theaters.
   Lichtenstein said that Philip Morris Companies Inc. has renewed
its grant of $350,000 as sponsor of the Next Wave Festival for the
fourth year. Benson and Hedges will support New Music America.
</TEXT>
