<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     03-28 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVERSIDE, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents gathered at the VFW hall to
celebrate the birthday of an unborn, fictional astronaut _ a
birthday party that only serious Trekkies could have dreamed up.
   About 200 people attended Monday night's ``minus 239th birthday
party'' of James T. Kirk, the captain of the Starship Enterprise
played by William Shatner in the movies and popular television
series Star Trek.
   Gene Roddenberry, creator and executive producer of the series,
wrote in ``The Making of Star Trek'' that Kirk was ``born in a
small town in the state of Iowa.'' The Riverside City Council
picked up on the idea in March 1985, declaring a site behind what
used to be the town's barbershop the ``future birthplace'' of Kirk.
   Roddenberry sent along a certificate of commendation.
   ``Whereas Capt. Kirk's future birthday is March 26, 2228, the
Mayor of the City of Riverside has proclaimed that March 26 will be
set aside to honor and celebrate the future Capt. James T. Kirk's
birthplace in the city of Riverside,'' the city's proclamation said.
   At Kirk's ``minus 239th birthday party'' Monday night _
postponed by one day because the March 26 fell on Easter Sunday _
look-alikes of First Officer Spock and Dr. ``Bones'' McCoy mingled
with other Star Trek fans.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   And now, for the pet owner with everything _
cosmetic surgery for dogs.
   ``There are medical reasons and reasons like they just don't
look pretty. People don't want to be apologetic for their pets'
looks,'' said Dr. Bill Sanders, who performs pet makeovers in his
Aardvark Etc. Veterinary Hospital.
   ``It's amazing what you can do with animal skin that you can't
do with a person's,'' he said.
   Sanders says he most often removes unsightly scars from dogs,
cats and other domestic animals. But he also repairs broken jaws
and crooked legs, and removes unwanted patches of white hair.
   Although it sounds like a luxury reserved for the rich and
famous, Sanders said he discusses pet owners' requests at length to
ensure they are best for the animal.
   ``Sometimes, the animal doesn't need cosmetic surgery,'' Sanders
told a newspaper columnist recently. ``It's wonderful that so much
can be done with just good grooming.''
   Sanders disputes that cosmetic surgery is frivolous or cruel.
   ``One of the big things on my side is to stop pet abuse,''
Sanders said. With the surgery, people often, ``take an attitude
that the pet is more than just something you kick around.''
</TEXT>
