<SECOND>AM-BRF--Czech-Rights,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Human Rights Committee Sends Letter To Premier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official human rights committee
wrote a letter to the prime minister criticizing new legislation on
human rights and proposing changes, the state news agency reported
Tuesday.
   In the letter, the government-appointed committee suggested
legislators distinguish more clearly between civic rights and
responsibilities in March legislation that stiffens penalties for
protestors, the CTK agency said.
   The official Human Rights Committee was established on Dec. 9 in
an apparent move to offset rising protest.
   So far, the committee has focused on helping citizens obtain
exit permits and other cases of minor human rights abuse.
   Some Czechoslovaks have accused the committee of failing to
speak against police brutality during a week of anti-government
protests in January that spurred the new legislation.
   The protests focused on the anniversary of the Jan. 15, 1969,
suicide of Jan Palach, who burned himself alive to protest the
August 1968 Soviet-led invasion that crushed the ``Prague Spring''
liberal reforms.
</TEXT>
