<DOCNO> AP890328-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 2053EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HomelessHealth     03-28 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Health,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Volunteer Doctors Help Homeless Fight Street Ills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The health hazards of living on the street: dirt,
skin disease and swollen feet, are treated three nights a week by
doctors who volunteer their services at a temporary shelter for the
homeless.
   The free service is among fewer than 100 around the country that
tap the good will of the medical profession. Advocates say they
wish there were more.
   Trying to help the homeless hang on to their health involves
coping with some ailments, such as lice and tuberculosis, that are
virtually unknown in affluent America, doctors say.
   ``They come with sore feet. They come with skin infections. They
come with skin breakdown,'' said Dr. Joseph Dorsey, one of the
volunteers from the Harvard Community Health Plan. ``Alcohol is a
very major factor in leading people to be here,'' he said. ``It's a
real leveler.''
   The state- and city-funded shelter at a vacant National Guard
armory is run by the non-profit private corporation Positive
Lifestyles. It takes in about 200 men a night, shift supervisor Sam
Larsen said Monday.
   ``We have everything from chronic alcoholics to working poor to
heavily drug-addicted guys,'' he said. ``I think the common theme
is that they were once able to afford housing and they can't any
longer.''
   About 50 medical personnel volunteer at the shelter, with
another 50 involved in other ways, Dorsey said. He said an intern
at Harvard Community Health Plan came up with the idea to volunteer
at the shelter and participants were sought through a sign-up list.
   Similar volunteered services are available elsewhere in such
diverse cities as Washington, D.C.; Columbia, S.C.; Duluth, Minn.;
Cleveland; San Francisco; and Seattle.
   Estelle Nichols runs the 14-year-old Free Clinic of Roanoke,
Va., and is treasurer of the National Association of Free and
Community Clinics. She estimated there are fewer than 100 such
clinics nationwide relying on free help from doctors.
   ``There are a good number out there, but there really are not
enough,'' Ms. Nichols said Tuesday in a telephone interview.
``There are not more now because cities have not organized them.
   ``If there is one thing I have found out, it's that (doctors)
are waiting out there for you to call them,'' Ms. Nichols said.
``They want an opportunity to do good work. That's the reason they
went into medicine. To do good work.''
   The Boston shelter, which opened Dec. 2 and is scheduled to
close this April, operates the clinic seven days a week, with the
volunteer doctors working three evenings, said Eileen McGee, head
nurse.
   By 7 p.m. Monday, a steady stream of patients filed into the
clinic to get their blood pressure tested, foot sores washed and
dressed and, mainly, to talk to the doctors about their aches and
pains.
   Clinic patients say the free medical services make it easier to
stay healthy.
   ``If you have to go to a doctor outside, you have to pay,'' said
Dominic, 52, who asked that his last name not be used.
   Dominic, who has had surgery for throat cancer, said he has
received medical care from Veterans Administration hospitals and
from a clinic run by nurses at the Pine Street Inn, a downtown
homeless shelter.
   But he said the services offered at the armory shelter are more
convenient for him and he's more likely to make follow-up visits.
   Ivan Forman, 72, said he worked as a contractor for much as his
life, serving in the Navy during World War II and working most
recently at odd jobs in a hospital and synagogue.
   Forman, who says alcoholism took him from studying psychology at
a university to life on the streets, complained of a headache
during his visit with the volunteer doctors and was given a mild
pain reliever.
   ``I think it's nice and I think the doctors get something out of
it,'' he said.
   Like Forman, many of the patients seen at the clinic have
relatively minor complaints, said McGee, who noted that any serious
cases are referred to a hospital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
