<FIRST>r w AM-US-EasternEurope 360   03-28 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Eastern Europe, 360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Calls For Review Of US Relations Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III is
considering a new U.S. approach to Eastern Europe with the overall
goal of promoting self-determination and freedom among the Soviet
allies.
   U.S. relations with the countries, whose fortunes have been tied
to Moscow for more than 40 years, are undergoing review along with
other aspects of American foreign policy, Margaret Tutwiler, the
State Department spokeswoman, said Tuesday.
   Former Secretary of State Henry A. Kissinger has proposed the
new arrangement in which Moscow would loosen its hold on the region
in exchange for a pledge by the United States and its NATO allies
not to threaten Soviet interests there.
   Without going into detail, Ms. Tutwiler said ``part of this on
the merits deserves to be taken a look at.''
   The overall review is due to be completed April 21 or, at the
latest, in early May.
   Baker intends to use the results in talks he will hold in Moscow
with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze in May.
   ``Our principal objective in Eastern Europe is to promote
demoncratic self- determiantiona and individual freedoms,'' Ms.
Tutwiler said.
   The spokeswoman said Baker had noted ``welcome signs of
movement'' in some of the East European countries. Referring to
Kissinger's proposal, she said ``part of this on the merits deserve
to be taken a look at.''
   Baker, on a visit to Vienna earlier this month, met with the
foreign ministers of Hungary and Poland and called in a speech for
the Soviets to cancel what is known as the Brezhnev Doctrine.
   Baker's aides said he was impressed with developments in the two
countries.
   The late Soviet President Leonid I. Brezhnev sent troops into
Czechoslovakia in 1968 to put down a revolt by Communist party
leaders who sought to liberalize the system in Prague.
   The Soviets explained the intervention as coming to the support
of socialism. This became known as the Brezhnev Doctrine.
   Baker first disclosed his interest in the Kissinger proposal in
an interview in The New York Times.
</TEXT>
