<FIRST>r w AM-OwlAppointee     03-28 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Owl Appointee,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Appointee To Oversee Forest Service Opposed Protection For Owl</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man President Bush has nominated to
oversee the Forest Service adamently opposed making the spotted owl
an endangered species, the fired director of the Fish and Wildlife
Service's West Coast office said Tuesday.
   James Cason was nominated last week as assistant secretary of
agriculture for natural resources and environment, a job that would
give him control over the Forest Service and the Soil Conservation
Service.
   Cason is now deputy assistant secretary for land and minerals
management at the Department of Interior. As such, he oversees the
operations of the Bureau of Land Management and the Office of
Minerals Management Service.
   Both the Forest Service and the Bureau of Land Management are
embroiled in lawsuits over efforts to protect the spotted owl,
which is thought to nest only in the ancient forests of the
Northwest.
   Cason ``was adamantly opposed to listing the spotted owl as an
endangered species,'' Rolf Wallenstrom, the fired Fish and Wildlife
Service official said of Cason. ``He was part of the group at
Interior putting pressure on the director'' of the Fish and
Wildlife Service.
   Cason, through spokeswoman Kelly Shipp, ``categorically'' denied
that he exerted pressure on the Fish and Wildlife Service not to
list the spotted owl as endangered.
   ``He said he contributed to the policy process and was asked for
his opinion,'' said Ms. Shipp.
   Ms. Shipp said Cason, who was in Denver on Tuesday, will
probably not grant interviews until after his confirmation hearing
before the Senate Agriculture Committee and presumed Senate
confirmation.
   Wallenstrom was fired as director of the Fish and Wildlife
Service's Region 1 Office earlier this year after refusing to take
a job as a special assistant to the director.
   At the time he was fired, Wallenstrom said that he and other
employees were being punished by Frank Dunkle, the agency's
director, for their views on various natural resource issues that
were opposite those of the Reagan administration.
   The Fish and Wildlife Service is responsible for deciding which
species should be protected under the federal Endangered Species
Act, with the decisions to be based strictly on ``biological
factors.''
   A recent General Accounting Office report concluded that
officials of the Interior Department had put political pressures on
the agency not to list the owl as an endangered species.
   The report said that regional biologists has been ordered to
``sanitize'' an initial report warning that the bird faced
extinction if logging of the old-growth forests in the Northwest
weren't slowed.
   The Fish and Wildlife Service eventually concluded there was not
sufficient evidence to list the owl as endangered. A federal court
subsequently found that decision was ``arbitrary and capricious''
and gave the agency until May 1 to review it.
   Wallenstrom said that Cason at one point didn't even want the
Fish and Wildlife Service to consider a petition asking that the
owl be listed.
   Wallenstrom said in a telephone interview that Cason essentialy
said ``the bird will be listed over my dead body. Cason seemed to
think he had a bigger role in the decision than he did.
   ``He had no official veto power, but I'm sure he did try to
influence (then-Secretary Donald) Hodel and others.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
