<HEAD>Key Races in the Soviet Parliamentary Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Results of key races in the Soviet parliamentary
election compiled Tuesday from official and unofficial sources:
   _Boris N. Yeltsin, former Moscow party chief and former
non-voting member of the ruling Politburo, defeated Yevgeny Brakov,
director of the giant factory that makes the ZIL limousine, for a
seat representing all of Moscow. Yeltsin won 89.4 percent of the
vote to Brakov's 6.9 percent.
   _Reform_minded economist Oleg T. Bogomolov, director of the
Institute of the Economy of the World Socialist System, defeated
Alexei M. Bryachikhin, a regional party official, and Alexander V.
Seredenin, a factory worker.
   _Roy A. Medvedev, a historian critical of the Soviet system and
the bloody terror of dictator Josef V. Stalin, faces a runoff
against Kseniya A. Razumova, who runs an atomic energy laboratory.
Neither won a majority in balloting.
   _Ilya I. Zaslavsky, 29, who campaigned for rights for the
handicapped, defeated Alexander N. Krutov, a TV commentator who had
declined to disavow an endorsement from the extreme Russian
nationalist group Pamyat, for a seat representing the Oktyabrsky
region.
   _Moscow Mayor Valery Saikin and his opponent, Nina Ageeva, were
both defeated in the city's Lyublin region. Saikin received 42.5
percent of the vote and Ageeva 24.8 percent.
   _Yuri Prokofiev, the city's Communist Party second secretary,
received only 13.5 percent of the vote in the city's Kuibyshev
district. He lost to Vladimir Markov, the director of a radio
communications institute.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LENINGRAD=
   _Anatoly Gerasimov, first secretary of the Leningrad city
Communist Party, lost to Yuri Boldyrev, a ship-building engineer.
Gerasimov won just 15 percent of the vote to Boldyrev's 74 percent.
   _Yuri Solovyev, a candidate member of the ruling party Politburo
and the regional party chief in Leningrad, lost even though he had
no competition in Leningrad's Nevsky district.
   _Anatoly Fateyev, a secretary at the Leningrad Region party
committee, lost to Viktor Kabakov, rector of the Leningrad
Engineering Economics Institute.
   _Deputy Mayor Alexei Bolshakov ran without opposition and still
lost because more than 50 percent of the electorate voted against
him.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   UKRAINE=
   _In Kiev, the Soviet Union's third-largest city, city Communist
Party chief Konstantin Masik and Mayor V. Zgurski were both
defeated though they had no opposition. More than half the voters
crossed out their names on the ballots.
   _Ivan Drach, head of the political reform movement Narodni Rukh,
came in second in a six_way race, losing to a surgeon who came out
in favor of Drach's grass-roots group during the race.
   _Writer Yuri Shcherbak, who became famous for his exposes on the
Chernobyl nuclear power plant explosion, was elected.
   _Full Politburo member Vladimir V. Shcherbitsky, the Ukrainian
Communist party leader, won in Dnepopetrovsk. He was alone on the
ballot but Kiev activists had been waging a campaign to urge votes
against him.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ESTONIA=
   _Edgar Savisaar, a leader of the grass-roots political movement
People's Front, defeated Allik Jaak, a Communist Party chief in
Viljandi, winning more than 80 percent of the vote.
   _Marju Lauristen, another People's Front leader, defeated Walter
Toots, the editor of a Russian-language newspaper in the university
town of Tartu, also winning more than 80 percent of the vote.
   _Gustav Tonspoeg, Estonia's top agricultural official, defeated
Ants Paju, editor of a nature magazine, by less than three percent.
   _Rein Vederman, the No. 2 official in the Estonian Communist
Party, faces a runoff against Yevgeny Kogan, the leader of
Intermovement, a political group that promotes the interests of the
non_Estonian population in the republic.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LITHUANIA=
   _Algirdas Brazauskas, the republic's reform_minded Communist
Party chief, and his deputy, Valeri Beriozovas, were the only party
officials in the republic to win. They were the only top party
officials unopposed by the Lithuanian political reform group
Sajudis, which won seats or spots in the runoff for all 39 of its
candidates.
   _Premier Vytautas Sakalauskas was defeated by Jonus Kubilus,
rector of Vilnius University and a member of Sajudis.
   _President Vytautas Astrauskas lost to Juozas Olekas, a surgeon
and Sajudis member.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LATVIA=
   _Premier Vilnis Bresis was defeated by a popular TV reporter.
The republic's party chief, Janis Vagris, was elected a deputy by a
small margin.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   FAR EAST=
   _Lt. Gen. Viktor Novozhilov, commander of the Far Eastern
military district, was defeated by Yevdokiya Gayer, a researcher
from the Institute of History, Archaelogy and Ethnography.
   _Viktor Pasternak, first secretary of the Kharabovsk regional
party committee, was defeated by collective farm director Yuri
Chichik.
   _Boris Korsunsky, first secretary of Birobidzhan region's party
committee, lost to Alexander Milyutin, chief engineer at a cement
factory.
   _In the Maritime territory, party first secretary Alexei
Volyntsev; Adm. Gennady Khvatov, commander of the Pacific fleet,
and Viktor Miskov, chief of the Far Eastern Shipping Co. all failed
to win enough votes. It was not clear if they had opposition.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ARMENIA=
   _Armenian Church chief Vazgen I was elected. It was not known
whether he had opposition.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MOLDAVIA=
   _Marshal Sergei Akromeyev, former army chief of staff now
serving as an aide to President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, was elected.
It was not clear if he had opposition.
   _The Communist Party first secretary of Kishinev, Nikolai Tsyu,
failed to win 50 percent, although only two candidates were in his
race.
</TEXT>
