<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 2137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Canada-Trade     03-28 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Trade,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Threaten Canada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States threatened to impose higher
tariffs on various fish products from Canada on Tuesday in a
dispute involving Canadian restrictions on the sale of raw salmon
and herring to American companies.
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills said she had determined
that the Canadian ban on sales of unprocessed herring and pink and
sockeye salmon taken by Canadian fishermen off the coast of British
Columbia violated U.S. trade law.
   Hills' decision represented the latest round in a long-standing
trade dispute between the two countries.
   Canada, in an effort to protect the jobs of workers at
processing plants in British Columbia, prohibits the sale of
unprocessed salmon and herring directly to American processors. The
fish must first be processed in Canadian plants before sale to U.S.
companies.
   The United States has been urging Canada to remove this
prohibition since 1986. America took the issue before the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the Geneva-based organization which
governs world trade, in 1987 and later that year received a ruling
upholding the U.S. position.
   ``It has been more than a year since Canada's export
prohibitions were found illegal under the GATT. I see no choice at
this point but to take action,'' Hills said in a statement.
   Hills said an inter-agency group of U.S. officials would hold
hearings next month to determine what Canadian products would be
subjected to the higher tariffs.
   In the announcement of the action, the U.S. trade office said it
would consider higher tariffs on various varieties of fresh,
chilled and frozen fish now imported from Canada.
   The dispute over herring and salmon was brought up at a meeting
earlier this month between Hills and Canadian Trade Ministter John
Crosbie but the two officials were unable to narrow the differences
between them.
   At the time, Hills said that the landing requirement was
unacceptable to American companies because ``it bruises the fish
and we feel that we end up with a less valuable product.''
   Canada has contended that the landing requirement was needed as
a conservation measure to assure that Canadian waters were not
depleted. American officials contend that the fish could be counted
and inspected on the boats, allowing the fish to be sold directly
to U.S. buyers.
</TEXT>
