<FIRST>r a AM-TankerCaptain     03-28 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Captain,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>His Mother Says Tanker Captain Had Alcohol Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of Joseph Hazelwood, captain of
the oil tanker involved in the nation's worst oil spill, confirmed
Tuesday her son had a history of alcohol abuse and that Exxon was
aware of it.
   ``I do know that he had a problem with alcohol in the past,''
Margaret Hazelwood said in a telephone interview with The
Associated Press. ``I know he was rehabilitated. Exxon knows it.''
   ``But I had thought things were on an even keel,'' she added.
She declined to elaborate on that comment, and refused to say
anything further about her son's drinking.
   Hazelwood, 42, also of Huntington, N.Y., was captain of the
Exxon Valdez when the tanker went aground last Friday in Prince
William Sound near Valdez, Alaska.
   Hazelwood is banned from driving in New York and New Hampshire
because of a drunken driving conviction in North Conway, N.H., six
months ago.
   On July 21, 1981, Hazelwood was charged with driving while
intoxicated and leaving the scene of an accident stemming from a
collision.
   His license was suspended for 18 months when he refused to
submit to a chemical test. Later he pleaded guilty to the driving
while intoxicated charge, and was fined $510.
   In 1984, his license was revoked after he refused a Breathalyzer
test following a minor automobile accident near his home.
   His license was restored in May 1986 after he completed the
program, but it was withdrawn after last year's conviction in New
Hampshire.
   He grew up in Huntington, where he lives with his wife Susan and
teenage daughter.
   Mrs. Hazelwood said her son has been in close touch with his
wife since the incident.
   ``He calls her whenever he can get to a phone but it's difficult
because the hearings are going on,'' said Mrs. Hazelwood.
   Les Rogers, an Exxon spokesman in Houston declined to comment on
Hazelwood's drinking problem. He referred all question to Exxon
officials in Alaska.
</TEXT>
