<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Afghanistan     03-28 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Call for U.N. Border Posts On Afghan-Pakistan Frontier</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union said Tuesday it wants
U.N. military observers posted between Afghanistan and Pakistan to
stop cross-border raids by the Islamic guerrillas seeking to topple
the communist government in Kabul.
   ``It is very important now to look into the situation on the
border between Afghanistan and Pakistan,'' Soviet U.N. Ambassador
Aleksandr M. Belonogov said after meeting with Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   ``The government of Afghanistan is suggesting that United
Nations (military) observers should be posted in the border area,
and we think this is the right idea.''
   The 50 military observers of the U.N. Good Offices Mission in
Afghanistan and Pakistan monitored the Soviet troop withdrawal from
Afghanistan that ended Feb. 15.
   Belonogov said the observers now should focus on what he said
was Pakistan's policy of allowing the guerrillas to operate from
bases in Pakistan.
   He said he believes ``the situation now demands much more
attention by ... (the Good Offices Mission) to the border area
between Afghanistan and Pakistan.''
   U.S. officials were unavailable for comment.
   Earlier in the day, the State Department declined comment when
two lower-ranking Soviet diplomats suggested in Washington that the
United Nations consider posting U.N. border monitors.
   Belonogov said that he ``also drew the attention of the
secretary-general to the inadequate situation with regard to the
implementation of the Geneva Accords,'' under which the Soviet army
left Afghanistan.
   Those accords, signed last April 14, require Afghanistan and
Pakistan not to interfere in each others' internal affairs.
   ``We are proud that we honored our obligations under the
agreements and that at the moment there are no Soviet soldiers on
Afghan soil, but at the same time we are concerned that these are
not honored, they are disregarded by Pakistan,'' said Belonogov.
   ``We are now witnessing deeper involvement by Pakistan into the
internal affairs of Afghanistan.''
   The Soviets and Afghanistan accuse Pakistan of letting the
rebels maintain bases on its territory and launch cross-border
raids. They also say the United States violates the accords by
supplying the guerrillas with weapons.
   The rebels also received support from China and Saudi Arabia.
Other rebels operating in western Pakistan receive aid from Iran.
   Afghan officers have accused Pakistani officers of directing the
current rebel seige of the Afghan city of Jalalabad, 75 miles east
of Kabul.
</TEXT>
