<FIRST>u a AM-Oscars 1stLd-Writethru a0622 03-28 0821</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oscars, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0622,0841</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oscar Demonstrators Line Up on Eve of Awards Show</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, ``I thought ...,'' to UPDATE with new Carr comment;
INSERTS 2 grafs after 15th graf, ``We didn't ...,'' to ADD comment from
John Cleese; picks up 16th graf, ``Carr, the ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the Academy Awards are best known for
garish gowns and overlong acceptance speeches, then Oscar-oriented
pickets run a close third, and Wednesday night's awards ceremony
will be no exception.
   As the producers of the 61st Academy Awards hurried on Tuesday
to prepare the show, protesters picketed the studios of MGM-United
Artists, demanding an apology for the comic depiction of stuttering
in the triple-nominated film ``A Fish Called Wanda.''
   ``If young children across the country are watching this film,
they really won't understand how the person who stutters is abused
verbally and shamed by everyone around him,'' said Mark Power, a
member of the advisory board of the National Stuttering Project.
   ``I don't think (a film maker) would have a blind person walking
into walls and have people kid him about that or make fun of him,''
Power said. ``But it's the same thing with stuttering. People are
born with the problem, and there's nothing you can really do about
it.''
   Ironically, another United Artists release has been praised for
its sensitive depiction of a disability. ``Rain Man,'' in which
Dustin Hoffman portrays an autistic savant, is this year's most
nominated film, and is favored to win several major awards,
including best picture.
   Other protesters were expected to congregate at the Shrine
Auditorium to take full advantage of the tremendous news media
attention (700 members of the press will be on hand).
   The Rev. R. L. Hymers said he plans to demonstrate against ``The
Last Temptation of Christ,'' which a variety of conservative
Christian leaders denounced last year for its depiction of a
doubting Jesus. The film received only one nomination, for director
Martin Scorsese.
   ``If they give him the Academy Award it will be approval of the
spiritual pornography,'' Hymers said.
   Yet the show's production team was largely unconcerned with any
controversies surrounding this year's Oscars as it headed toward
curtain time.
   ``Every moment is a crisis, but we're sitting here perfectly
relaxed and happy,'' said show producer Allan Carr between the last
Oscar rehearsals Tuesday. ``This is as good as it's going to be.''
   ``A Fish Called Wanda'' is nominated for best original
screenplay, best supporting actor (Kevin Kline) and best director
(Charles Crichton). In the bank-robbery farce, Kline taunts a
character played by Michael Palin for his severe speech impediment.
   The character loses his stutter at the end of the film when he
runs over Kline with a steam roller. The movie was a box-office
hit, grossing more than $62 million, according to Exhibitor
Relations Co.
   The 4,000-member National Stuttering Project, which says that
more than 2 million Americans stutter, is asking MGM to add a
disclaimer to ``A Fish Called Wanda'' stating that the film did not
intend to perpetuate ``negative inferences about people who
stutter.''
   Tracy Lorie, a spokeswoman for MGM-UA, said the studio felt it
had nothing to apologize for.
   ``We didn't make a movie that is derogatory toward stutterers,''
she said. ``Michael Palin's character is the most likable in the
film.''
   John Cleese, who both co-wrote and stars in ``A Fish Called
Wanda,'' joked last week that the movie's use of stuttering was why
it received as many nominations as it did.
   ``The best way to get nominated for something is to have someone
in the film who is suffering from some kind of psychological or
physical handicap,'' Cleese said.
   Carr, the Oscar show producer, has added some new twists this
year. There will be no emcee. Instead, presenters will be duets of
stars, some married or romantically linked to each other. These
include Ryan O'Neal and Farrah Fawcett, Melanie Griffith and Don
Johnson and Goldie Hawn and Kurt Russell.
   Carr, who took Broadway by storm with ``La Cage Aux Folles,''
predicted a show that will combine ``the best of movies, the best
of Broadway and the best of television all rolled into one.''
   ``I think it's a triple,'' Carr said, ``but it just might be a
home run.''
   Last-minute odds put ``Rain Man'' in the lead for best picture
over ``The Accidental Tourist,'' ``Dangerous Liaisons,''
``Mississippi Burning'' and ``Working Girl.''
   ``Rain Man'' director Barry Levinson was thought by many to be a
shoo-in for best director, as was Hoffman for best actor for his
starring role in the film.
   The best actress category, though, was thought to be much
closer. Meryl Streep was nominated for ``A Cry in the Dark,'' Glenn
Close was selected for ``Dangerous Liaisons,'' Jodie Foster was
named for ``The Accused,'' Sigourney Weaver was nominated for
``Gorillas in the Mist'' and Miss Griffith was chosen for ``Working
Girl.''
</TEXT>
