<FIRST>r a AM-OralRoberts     03-28 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oral Roberts,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Lay Money At Feet Of Evangelist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of students laid money at the feet
of evangelist Oral Roberts Tuesday after he said he must raise $11
million by May 6 or creditors will start dismantling his university
and ministry.
   The 71-year-old evangelist said scandals in other ministries
have caused contributions to his ministry to decline from $5
million a month to $2.7 million during the past two years.
   Speaking to a sometimes hushed and often raucous gathering of
4,300 Oral Roberts University students at a campus chapel service,
Roberts described himself as a ``tough old bird'' intent on keeping
the university going ``until Jesus comes.''
   Roberts' son, Richard, executive vice president of the school,
told students it was the greatest financial crisis in his father's
41-year ministry.
   After the elder Roberts made an impassioned speech to students,
Richard Roberts laid a $100 bill on the stage at the feet of his
father and mother, Evelyn. Mrs. Roberts suggested students might
want to contribute, too, and hundreds filed down to the stage to
leave checks, change and bills in a pile.
   The collection raised $8,500, Richard Roberts said.
   University officials declared Wednesday a day of prayer and
fasting on campus.
   Roberts first made his plea during a taping session Monday for
his weekly ``Expect A Miracle'' television program, scheduled to
air in part on Sunday on 147 statons.
   ``If we can't make our payroll, I don't know what will happen to
this man or this ministry,'' Roberts said during the taping.
``People, this is serious. This is a life-and-death matter.''
   He lambasted the news media for the way they cover his ministry,
but school officials contacted reporters about his comments and
made the unedited tape available for viewing.
   The evangelist's plea comes two years after he raised a furor by
saying his life depended on raising $8 million to provide
scholarships for his university's medical students.
   Roberts announced on April 1, 1987, that the money had been
raised.
   ``Two years have passed, and I have been silent,'' he said.
   During that time, he said, contributions to his ministry have
declined by nearly half. He said the ministry needs 10,000 to
15,000 additional ``partners'' to boost monthly income to $3.3
million.
   With that amount coming in, ``we can pay all bills and keep them
paid,'' Roberts said.
   He said he was ``laughed at, mocked, scoffed'' two years ago,
but said he was only repeating what God had told him about
redirecting efforts in medical school missions work at the
university.
   Roberts said he has fallen behind in paying for time on the
television stations that air his program, as well as for food
services at the university, supplies and other bills owed to
hundreds of vendors.
   ``Now our vendors and suppliers have to have their money,'' he
said. ``If we cannot pay the $11 million by the first week in May
... they will have to go to the extent of the law to collect their
money.''
   ``If we don't pay it, then they start coming in, start
dismantling,'' he said.
   Richard Roberts said the university has no plans to sell its
commercial property, including a hotel and three office buildings
in Tulsa.
</TEXT>
