<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     03-28 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Tours Jewish Settlements Days Before Washington Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir toured Jewish
settlements in the occupied West Bank on Tuesday and said he is
still working on peace proposals he will take to Washington next
week.
   Israeli news reports interpreted Shamir's visit to the West Bank
as a message to the U.S. administration, which has said Jewish
settlements in the occupied territories are an obstacle to peace.
   In other developments, two Palestinians were reported wounded by
Israeli troops, an Israeli passenger bus was set ablaze, and
militant Palestinians and Israeli forces prepared for Land Day
violence on Thursday.
   Arab hospital officials said two Palestinians were shot and
wounded by Israeli soldiers in the occupied lands. At least 412
Arabs and 18 Israelis have been killed since a Palestinian uprising
began in the West Bank and Gaza strip in December 1988.
   In Arab east Jerusalem a firebomb burned an Israeli bus, but no
injuries were reported.
   Leaflets distributed in the West Bank and Gaza and signed by
various Palestine Liberation Organization factions called for a
general strike and attacks on Land Day.
   Palestinians mark Land Day from fighting in 1976 when six Arabs
were killed by army and police gunfire in riots over the
government's seizure of Arab land.
   ``Let us rain the occupiers and the settlers with thousands of
stones and firebombs because this is the only language our enemy
can understand,'' said a leaflet distributed in Gaza City.
   The army moved reinforcements into the occupied territories in
anticipation of Land Day violence. In the 1988 Land Day riots four
Palestinians were killed and dozens were wounded.
   Shamir, who wants more Jewish settlement in the occupied
territories, was given bread, salt and wine by dozens of cheering
settlers in the Har Adar settlement near Jerusalem. In nearby Givat
Zeev he was made an honorary citizen.
   At a meeting in Washington earlier this month, Secretary of
State James Baker III reportedly urged Israeli Foreign Minister
Moshe Arens to halt plans to expand Jewish settlements as a move to
improve the climate for peace talks.
   But a coalition agreement between Shamir's hardline Likud bloc
and the Labor party stipulates building eight new settlements over
the next four years. The two parties recently agreed to allocate
$19.4 million for that purpose.
   Some 70,000 Jewish settlers and 1.7 million Palestinians live in
the occupied territories.
   Shamir, who is to meet with President Bush April 6, was asked
about peace proposals he might make.
   ``We are still in the process of discussion,'' he said. ``There
is no point in publishing unfinished things. It's not clear these
would be accepted.''
</TEXT>
