<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 2106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Counterfeit     03-28 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Counterfeit,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secret Service Crushes Counterfeit Ring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents seized $36.5 million and arrested
85 people over a two-year period to crush the biggest counterfeit
currency ring in Secret Service history, law enforcement officials
said Tuesday.
   They estimated that $2 million in bogus bills is still in
circulation.
   ``As strange as it may sound, they planned to take the currency
to Colombia'' and palm it off on drug cartels in exchange for
cocaine, Assistant U.S. Attorney Daniel De Vita said at a news
conference.
   Instead, the ringleaders ``got a little greedy'' and started
selling the funny money, said De Vita, who prosecuted the case.
They got caught when the money surfaced in U.S. casinos, banks and
shopping malls, and even as far away as Paris.
   Thirty of the suspects, mostly ``mules (couriers) and go-fers,''
were arrested in New York and the rest in Los Angeles, Chicago and
Miami during the two-year investigation, said Richard Ward, the
chief agent in the Secret Service's New York office.
   Asked why authorities had waited so long to announce the case,
Ann Driscoll, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Attorney's Office in
Brooklyn, said they had been waiting for the last of the
ringleaders to enter his plea.
   That occurred March 13, she said. Since then, the announcement
had been a question of scheduling.
   The spokeswoman said she didn't have figures on how many of the
85 arrested were prosecuted, or on the disposition of the cases
because a number of jurisdictions were involved.
   The five New York ringleaders, including former used car
salesman Francisco Scocozza, 55, a Uruguayan living in Queens, were
arrested between October and January. They pleaded guilty to a
charge of creating counterfeit currency and are awaiting sentences
of up to 15 years in prison.
   In all, it's believed that $80 million to $100 million in $10,
$20, $50 and $100 bills was cranked out at six locations in
Manhattan and Queens _ the bulk of it in the basement of ringleader
Juan Moran-Munoz, an Argentine living in Queens, said De Vita.
   The balance of the money was dumped or burned when the suspects
``realized the Secret Service was onto them,'' said U.S. Attorney
Andrew Maloney. Sanitation workers found $18 million in chopped-up
bills in a Bronx trash bin last July, said Ward.
   Of the estimated $2 million still in circulation, Maloney said:
``We think most of these bills are of first quality. To the
unsophisticated person, it could pass as real bills.''
   Ward said the portrait on a suspected counterfeit should be
compared to the one on a genuine bill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
