<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-28 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Over Texas; Heat in East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy thunderstorms gave Texans a drenching on Tuesday while
Eastern Seaboard residents got a record-breaking preview of summer.
Snow and freezing rain fell in parts of Minnesota and far northern
Michigan.
   An upper-air disturbance moving across southern Texas produced
the strong thunderstorms that prompted flash flood watches for
northeast Texas, extreme southeast Oklahoma and all of Arkansas.
   Rainfall overnight averaged around 3 inches in the Dallas-Fort
Worth area, with 5 inches falling in northern sections of Fort
Worth. Rivers and streams rose rapidly.
   Up to 4 inches of rain soaked portions of south-central Texas,
and over an inch of rain fell in 50 minutes in the town of Hondo.
Flooding was reported along Cowhouse Creek at Fort Hood.
   Winds from an intense thunderstorm gusted to 58 mph at Austin,
Texas, and blew a tree onto a house just west of the capital.
   A tornado watch was posted for much of southern and eastern
Texas.
   One to 2 inches of rain drenched western Arkansas, flooding
highways in Sebastian County.
   Welcome rains fell over eastern Kansas and western Missouri,
with 2 inches falling at Westwood, Kan., and over 1.75 inches at
Liberty, Mo.
   Northern Minnesota and western upper Michigan had wintry
weather, with rain mixed with freezing rain and light snow.
   Rain showers fell over central California, western Montana and
the upper Great Lakes. Portions of the Great Lakes were shrouded in
fog.
   A cold front moving through the central Pacific Coast produced
high winds, including gusts over 70 mph west of Reno, Nev. A high
wind warning was in effect for extreme western Nevada.
   Record spring warmth continued from the lower Mississippi Valley
to the Atlantic Coast, with temperatures in the 80s as far north as
southern New England.
   It was 90 degrees at Baltimore-Washington International Airport,
shattering a 44-year-old record. Elsewhere, records were set or
tied at Beckley, W.V. (81), Boston, (81), Cape Hatteras, N.C. (76),
Huntington, W.V. (86), Mansfield, Ohio (75), Montgomery, Ala. (85),
Portland, Maine (67), Providence, R.I. (79), Roanoake, Va. (82) and
Youngstown, Ohio (77).
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 26
degrees at Warroad, Minn., to 88 degrees at McAllen, Texas, and
Fort Myers, Fla.
   The nation's low Tuesday was 17 degrees at Gunnison and Alamosa,
Colo.
   The forecast for Wednesday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from eastern portions of the southern plains to much
of the middle and lower Mississippi Valley, the Ohio and Tennessee
valleys, the lower Great Lakes and the middle and northern Atlantic
Coast, with thunderstorms most prevalent from eastern Texas to the
lower Mississippi Valley and southern portions of the lower Ohio
Valley; rain showers from the Pacific Northwest to the northern and
central Rockies and the northern plains, with snow over northern
Maine and snow mixed with rain at higher elevations of the central
Rockies.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 30s from eastern
North Dakota to northern Minnesota, upper Michigan and northern
Maine; the 40s and 50s from the northern and central Pacific Coast
to the northern and central Intermountain West, the northern
Rockies, much of the northern Plains, the Great Lakes and northern
New England; the 80s from south central Texas to the Gulf Coast,
Florida, and the southern Atlantic Coast, and across southwest
Texas and the desert Southwest; and in the 60s and 70s in the rest
of the nation.
</TEXT>
