<HEAD>Soviet Defense Minister Visits Syria's Mediterranean Coast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Defense Minister Gen. Dmitri Yazov
on Tuesday toured Syria's Mediterranean coast, where Moscow
reportedly plans to expand a military facility it has operated for
20 years.
   Sources in the Soviet delegation said Yazov was accompanied by
senior Syrian officers on the trip from Damascus to the port city
of Latakia.
   Yazov arrived Monday for the first official visit to Syria by a
Soviet defense chief in more than a decade. Syria is Moscow's chief
Arab ally.
   It could not be determined if Yazov also visited Tartus, the
site where the Soviets have maintained military facilities since
1969.
   Tartus is about 40 miles south of Latakia and 25 miles north of
the border with Lebanon.
   Last year Western intelligence reports mentioned contruction at
the Tartus installation. The reports said the Soviets want to
expand the facilities so that naval units in the region would not
have to make the journey north to Soviet ports in the Black Sea for
repairs and maintenance.
