<FIRST>u a AM-Spill-Wildlife     03-28 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill-Wildlife,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Oiled Birds May Never Be Rescued</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The very wilderness that made Prince
William Sound a rich habitat for birds, marine mammals and fish is
hindering efforts to retrieve animals contaminated by the nation's
biggest oil spill.
   ``I don't want to encourage people by saying we're going out to
save all those birds,'' Pamela Bergmann, head of the U.S. Interior
Department's Regional Response Team, said Tuesday. ``It's just not
going to happen. It's even going to be tough to count the bodies.''
   A bird recovery center, set up shortly after Friday's
10.1-million gallon oil spill, had not seen a single bird by
Tuesday afternoon, Bergmann said.
   Bergmann said beaches in many places are too rough for rescuers
to land a boat, let alone chase down and capture oil-coated birds.
The oil is spreading southwestward away from Valdez, where cleanup
crews are based. In the hours it takes for a bird to be captured
and returned to Valdez, its chances of survival are greatly reduced.
   Even under favorable conditions, rescue officials figure they
are lucky if half the captured birds survive an oil spill. Alaska's
chilly waters are likely to drive down the survival rate as
oil-coated birds deprived of their insulating layer succumb to
hypothermia.
   ``Some will sink. They'll bash up against a cliff. Or eagles
will pray on them,'' Bergmann said. Toxins in the oil pose a threat
to the eagles and other predators, she said.
   A body count of dead birds is about all anyone can hope to
accomplish, said Jon Lyman, Alaska Department of Fish and Game
spokesman. That count stood at fewer than 100 Tuesday.
   Marine mammals such as sea otters also are at risk. At least two
dead otters have been spotted. A dozen killer whales were seen
surfacing in the slick during the weekend, but officials said the
oil does not pose as a great a danger to them.
   Rescue officials are discouraging volunteers, who usually are an
integral part of bird rescues in oil spills along more populated
coastlines. Not only is the terrain more rugged, but officials fear
volunteers might not be prepared for encounters with the bears that
prowl the sound's forested, uninhabited islands.
   Bergmann said she has had to tell would-be volunteers that there
is no place to stay in Valdez, no boats to take them out and little
they can do.
   Environmental groups are growing impatient with the situation.
   ``We have got to make the attempt _ not just sit here ...
twiddling thumbs,'' said Cindy Lowry, Alaska representative of
Greenpeace.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   David Foster is the AP's Northwest regional
reporter, based in Seattle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
