<SECOND>AM-Right To Die,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Upholds Stabbing Victim's Right To Die</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN O'QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman prepared to cut her son's
life-support system after a judge ruled Tuesday that an assailant
who may face murder charges if the youth dies did not have the
right to stop her.
   Sylvia Lane, mother of victim Mark Weaver, said her son had no
wish to be kept alive artificially, and she would remove his
feeding tube on Thursday.
   Noel Pagan, who served three years in prison for stabbing Weaver
in 1985, had gone to court to keep Weaver alive because Pagan could
be charged with murder if the victim dies.
   ``I don't know how any judge could not have ruled in our
favor,'' Ms. Lane said. ``I don't see how he could have any right
to decide what happens to the victim of his crime.''
   Pagan currently is on probation while serving a suspended
sentence for the attack.
   The state attorney general's office said it will not decide
whether to file charges until after the death.
   ``Until there's a death, there's no cause of death,'' spokesman
David Cheever said Tuesday.
   Robert Mullen, Pagan's attorney, said his client had agreed
``that it was not in anybody's interest, certainly not in the
family's interest and not in Mark Weaver's interest'' to appeal the
ruling.
   Probate Judge Dana Childs said Pagan's interest in preventing
Weaver's death ``has nothing to do with the purposes of this
proceeding.''
   Mullen said he met Monday with prosecutors to try to talk them
out of filing additional charges.
   Pagan, 29, stabbed Weaver, 26, on a Lewiston street in 1985, and
the victim lapsed into a coma when his neck wounds prevented oxygen
from reaching his brain.
   Weaver, who doctors say is in a ``permanent vegetative state,''
has been under his mother's care at her Portland home.
   Childs said Feb. 27 that Ms. Lane was within her rights in
removing her son from life support. Ms. Childs said at the time
that she would do so on Thursday.
</TEXT>
