<FIRST>u a AM-Haiti 2ndLd-Writethru a0710 03-28 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0710,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Port-Au-Prince</HEAD>
<HEAD>Church Workers: `We Were Lucky To Get Out Alive'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with church workers arriving in Miami, driver's
account of attack, details. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a U.S. church group said Tuesday they
were lucky to escape alive from a machete-wielding, rock-throwing
Haitian mob that rushed their pickup truck on a crowded street near
Port-au-Prince.
   ``It's a miracle we got out,'' said Roger Mercer, a member of
the Free Methodist Church in Alpena, Mich., who drove the truck.
``It was obvious to me it was a planned attack because of the way
they were prepared for us.''
   The 12 members of the church group involved in the Sunday night
incident, all from northern Michigan except for one Floridian,
arrived at Miami International Airport on Tuesday night.
   Mercer, whose left eye was swollen shut and whose head and left
foot were bandaged, rolled off the plane in a wheelchair. He said
his brother-in-law, John Freel, who was in the passenger side of
the pickup, was shot in the arm; Louis Haber, of Zephyrhills, Fla.,
was knocked unconscious by a rock, and others were hit by rocks but
not seriously injured. Their vehicle was demolished, he said.
   The Americans were treated at the St. Croix Hospital in Leogane,
a small town 18 miles southwest of Port-au-Prince.
   The Rev. Abner Rabouin, a Haitian minister of the Free Methodist
Church, said earlier in Haiti that the the truck struck two
Haitians as it tried to maneuver through a crowd of about 1,000
revelers at a Lenten celebration.
   The minister said a rumor passed through the crowd that the
truck was running down Haitians, provoking the mob attack. Rabouin
said two Haitians hit by the truck suffered broken legs.
   Mercer gave a harrowing account of the attack, which came
shortly after the group left a celebration at another town and were
headed to Gurim, where the members were helping build a church.
   The truck was inching through a huge crowd of revelers in the
road when some men broke the truck's mirrors, pounded on the hood
and started throwing rocks at them, Mercer said. ``At that point, I
knew I was in trouble,'' he said.
   Mercer said another man was ready to heave a huge rock at the
truck when he started to drive at him.
   ``My objective was to get him off balance and it did just that.
... I had no intention of hitting him,' he said, adding that he
wasn't sure if he struck the man.
   When he tried to accelerate and escape, Mercer said, another
truck came from behind and cut off the church group's vehicle.
   ``I rammed the truck from the rear, spun him around and kept on
going,'' he recalled.
   But another crowd of revelers ahead slowed the truck and the
attack continued. ``These machetes nearly carved the door off,''
Mercer said of the hour-long attack. ``They were saying we were
killers.''
   ``There were many angels there to protect them,'' Rabouin said.
``Otherwise, they would have been killed.''
   Elmore L. Clyde, director of the Free Methodist Church's world
missions headquartered at Winona Lake, Ind., said the group was on
a two-week trip to build a church in Leogane.
   According to Clyde, the Americans had gone to an Easter service
at another town and were returning to Leogane when the attack
occurred.
   Rabouin said Haitians in a car that preceded the Americans'
truck spread the rumor that the truck was deliberately running down
people.
   He called the rumor baseless and said the Americans ``did
everything they could to avoid hitting anyone.''
   He dismissed as ``abolutely untrue'' a report that occupants of
the truck had pulled out revolvers and fired in the air.
   Rabouin said it took about two hours for the truck to arrive at
a military outpost, where the mob dispersed when a soldier fired
into the air.
   The Free Methodist Church has operated a mission in Haiti since
1964 and has built 30 churches in the impoverished Caribbean nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
