<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-ItalianMovies Adv05 1stLd-Writethru 03-28 1175</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italian Movies, Adv 05, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0237,1209</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs April 5 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Signs of Hope Seen in Italy's Cinema Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, CORRECTS spellings to Wertmuller and Bellocchio in 8th graf
``1989 began ... and Bellochio'' and ``spettacolo'' in 16th graf ``This
love ... United States.'' An accompanying box is PM-Italian Oscars, b0238</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Once Italian filmmakers dominated the world's
screens. Stars like Sophia Loren and Anna Magnani set hearts
throbbing or tears flowing. Then came a rapid decline and the
Italian movie industry hit bottom. There are signs of a
renaissance, however. Here is a report.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the dusty square, a crowd of villagers stares
wistfully at the movie palace that once brought them love and
death. Its sign is chipped, its facade blackened, its windows
smashed like broken teeth.
   Suddenly, a demolition expert presses a switch and the theater
explodes in a cloud of dust, to make room for a parking lot.
   The scene, from the recent film ``New Paradise Cinema'' by
Giuseppe Tornatore, is intended to symbolize the death of Italy's
once highly acclaimed cinema.
   The image reflects the grim reality Italian cinema has faced for
more than a decade: shrinking audiences, shuttered theaters, a drop
in quality. But although Italian filmmaking remains troubled,
recent signs indicate that reports of its death may be exaggerated.
   ``The Italian cinema in the past two years has had a small
recovery,'' says Carmine Cianfarani, president of the Italian
Motion Picture Association. ``We have huge possibilities, at least
on paper.''
   For years, Italians set the pace for moviemakers around the
world. Roberto Rossellini and Vittorio De Sica captured the
brutality of life in neo-realist films like ``Open City'' and
``Bicycle Thief.'' The 1960s brought the fantasy and metaphor of
Federico Fellini, Michelangelo Antonioni and Pier Paolo Pasolini.
   No one is predicting a quick return to those glory days. But
movie production is up for the third straight year after hitting an
all-time low in 1985. And well-known directors who had to scramble
for financing are now being courted at home.
   ``1989 began in a positive way,'' Cianfarani said. ``All the
major directors are at work, from Fellini to (Ettore) Scola, from
Sergio Leone to the Taviani brothers, from Lina Wertmuller to
(Marco) Bellocchio.''
   In addition to the masters, a younger generation of filmmakers
is beginning to emerge after a long period in which Italy's
directors were turning steadily grayer.
   The reason for the flurry of activity is money, coming from a
host of television stations competing fiercely for the Italian
audience and hungry for films.
   ``The possibilities have opened up incredibly with television,''
said Cristina Comencini, 35, a slender, ginger-haired director. The
daughter of well-known director Luigi Comencini, she recently made
her own debut with an acclaimed film, ``The Zoo.''
   ``There's a bigger circulation of money,'' she said. ``This has
allowed many young people to make their first film.''
   But television is also seen as a mixed blessing. Many people
fear its influence is lowering film quality. And television is
considered the main culprit in the collapse in movie attendance.
   ``Television in Italy is destroying the cinema,'' declares Lino
Micciche, a prominent film critic. ``In the mid-70s, we sold 500
million tickets. Now we're under 100 million. ... That's not a
decrease, it's a disaster.''
   For most of this century the cinema was a focal point of life in
Italian cities and villages. Italians grew up laughing with the
comedian Toto, crying with Anna Magnani, lusting after Sophia
Loren, and being outraged by films like ``La Dolce Vita'' that
portrayed the emptiness of their society.
   This love of ``spettacolo'' (spectacle) gave Italy the highest
per-capita movie attendance in the West and the biggest production
of films after the United States.
   But all that changed after Italy's Constitutional Court
deregulated television in 1976. Almost overnight, new stations
popped up all over the country. Television went from showing two
movies a week in 1976 to a bewildering total of 2,000.
   ``Our theaters have been emptied, because the public could see
too many films free at home, above all Italian ones,'' complains
Silvio Clementelli, head of the national producers' association.
   The television explosion crippled an industry already hurting
from the withdrawal of U.S. producers, who had flocked to Italy in
the 1960s to take advantage of special financial laws and produced
blockbusters like ``Ben Hur'' and ``Cleopatra.''
   With the financial squeeze, production began to center on easy
comedies, pseudo-American adventures and a handful of proven stars
like Marcello Mastroianni or Ornella Muti. Many films were pushed
out of theaters by technically superior American movies with big
promotion budgets.
   ``In Italy, you see very little Italian film,'' said Luigi
Filippi, a spokesman for the Italian General Association of
Entertainment.
   The economic situation was so grim that Bernardo Bertolucci had
to find a foreign producer and capital to make his Oscar-winning
``The Last Emperor,'' which was filmed in English in China.
   But if television has caused a crisis, it is providing some
compensation. Competing stations _ particularly the state-run RAI
and magnate Silvio Berlusconi's three commercial networks _ are now
paying top dollar for the rights to films, and often adding another
chunk for a share of box-office profits.
   One of the trickle-down effects of their investment is growing
attention to new filmmakers.
   ``In the past year, we have begun to talk about the so-called
young Italian cinema,'' said Micciche. ``We are discovering that
young people's films do exist.''
   Indeed, in recent months three major films by new directors have
come out _ ``It's Happening Tomorrow,'' by Daniele Luchetti;
Massimo Guglielmi's ``Rebus,'' featuring Charlotte Rampling; and
``Mignon Has Come to Stay,'' by 28-year-old Francesca Archibugi,
who gave birth to her first baby on the set.
   Other beginners like Comencini and Tornatore (``New Paradise
Cinema'') are also winning acclaim, even though their films are
less widely distributed.
   The road is still long for relatively unknown directors. Many
have trouble getting their films into one of the dwindling number
of theaters. And with filmmaking depressed in recent years, few
bankable young stars have developed.
   ``There aren't any more Sophia Lorens,'' said Comencini. ``All
the great actors are of the older generation.''
   Some observers say young directors also lack the inspiration
provided by the idealistic postwar period or the 1960s.
   ``This moment in Italy is one of passage,'' says Micciche. ``The
young generation is unable to find new truths, new ideals, because
the society doesn't know what they are. We are so cynical.''
   While it has provided new opportunity, the flood of television
money may have drawbacks. Some directors are abandoning sweeping
panoramas, complicated plots and other things that don't adapt
easily to television.
   Despite the problems, producers and directors are hopeful that
the small upturn will continue.
   ``Cinema may never be popular mass entertainment again. That's
what television is,'' said Comencini.
   ``But it's still an area where you can create new things,
different things.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs April 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890328-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-VideoReleases ADV29   03-28 0861</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Video Releases, ADV 29,0880</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs, March 29, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Promotional Clips Flood TV Newsrooms, Raising Ethical Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FELIX GUTIERREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Royal Viking's new luxury liner sailed
under the Golden Gate Bridge at the beginning of a recent
television news report, it was the end of a successful promotional
journey for the cruise lines' publicist.
   The segment _ shown on stations from San Diego to Boston in
January _ was shot, edited and transmitted not by news crews, but
by a video public relations agency.
   ``If we do it right it looks like their own tape,'' said Gail
Cottman, whose Pro Video News Service produced the clip. Her
$10,000 fee included contacting more than 100 television news
outlets, distributing the piece via satellite and making follow-up
calls to see where it was broadcast.
   Parts of the story, including the ship's christening and an
on-board interview with actor Jimmy Stewart, screened on
Entertainment Tonight and CNN. It was retransmitted to more than
500 local stations that take newsfeeds from ABC, CNN or Group W,
Pro Video reported.
   As television news expands, more public relations agencies are
moving past typewritten press releases and still photos. They
target TV newsrooms with videocassette news releases and
promotional tape available via satellite.
   ``The most interesting things I see companies doing is putting
up satellite feeds on the day of an event. They put it up there for
people to grab,'' said CBS news West Coast bureau manager Jennifer
Siebens.
   When Honda offered visuals of its first U.S.-manufactured cars
being shipped to Japan from Portland, Ore., Ms. Siebens passed up
the reverse-import story. ``If we took their feed we would be
conceding total control of the story to the subject of the story,''
she said.
   Such ethical concerns divide news directors. Some argue against
ever using promotional clips within newscasts. Others use them, but
identify who supplied them. And still others broadcast the clips on
newscasts without any hint to viewers as to who supplied them.
   ``There is absolutely no consensus among our members,'' said
Ernie Schultz, president of the Radio-Television News Directors
Association in Washington, D.C. ``We've got 1,200 news directors
and 1,200 positions. Everybody is different.''
   ``We believe that if we do a story the viewer should be
confident that whatever he's seeing is 100 percent CBS news, that
we have been there as an independent set of eyes on the story,''
said Ms. Siebens.
   Sometimes news directors have little choice. A few months ago
CBS and other networks showed Drexel Burnham Lambert chief
executive Frederick H. Joseph reacting to the firm's settlement of
alleged federal securities-law violation.
   But Joseph wasn't interviewed or taped by news staffers.
Instead, his comments were issued as a video press release in the
late afternoon by Drexel. CBS noted the source when it broadcast
the edited tape.
   Ms. Siebens said CBS identifies publicity videos for viewers,
such as file footage of a factory assembly line. CBS newsfeeds
likewise identify sources for the local stations receiving them,
but Ms. Siebens doesn't know if stations pass the identifications
along to viewers.
   Radio-Television News Directors Association ethics don't require
newscasters to mention if the tapes were supplied by the subject
being mentioned, only that stations don't pass off tapes as their
own.
   ``We are not prepared to say that every time that you put
something on the air that you have not originated that you have to
name the source,'' said Schultz. ``The strength of our position is
that every editor uses his or her own judgment.''
   But broadcasting client-supported videos on news shows blurs the
line between publicity and news, critics contend. Publicity videos
allow companies to put their best visual foot forward, avoid
questions from probing reporters and promote story angles favorable
to their products.
   ``If they try to push anything corporate or push a product,
we're not going to take it,'' said Jake Wirtshafter, a news
assistant with ABC network news in Los Angeles, who fields
publicists' messages. He said they ``are lucky to get three items a
month on one of our (network) feeds.''
   ``A reporter can take information from a public relations piece
and sort it out,'' said Wirtshafter. ``But once we put it up we
can't do that. If we show something that makes their client look
good we can't balance it out.''
   Cottman averages two client-supported releases a week. She
produces both video news releases with narration that stations can
air as their own, as well as news tapes without sound for which
stations can provide their own narration from information provided
by Pro Video.
   ``In five minutes (of tape) the station gets everything it
needs,'' said Cottman. ``They can deal with the story as they
choose to show it.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   PRIESTS PREMIERE _ ``Have Faith,'' a new ABC comedy about four
dissimilar priests, is set to premiere April 18 for a brief spring
tryout, taking the place of ``Anything But Love,'' which is
completing its spring run. The series stars Joel Higgins, Frank
Hamilton, Ron Carey and Stephen Furst.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, March 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
