<DOCNO> AP890328-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Africa-Catholics Adv02-2Takes   03-28 0875</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Africa-Catholics, Adv 02-2 Takes,0898</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Catholic Church in Africa _ Special Challenges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This is the main story of a package of four</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholicism is spreading across Africa and
African influence is spreading in the church. As Pope John Paul II
prepares for yet another voyage to the continent, he faces special
challenges in melding the fundamental tenets of his church and the
unique culture of the African.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Yesterday the missionaries Christianized
Africa, today the blacks are Africanizing Christianity.'' _
Cardinal Joseph Malula of Zaire.
   When Pope John Paul II makes his fifth journey to Africa April
28-May 6, he will address a Roman Catholic flock that has grown by
22 million since his first trip in 1980.
   The pope's four-stop trip _ Madagascar, the French territory
Reunion in the Mascarene Islands, Zambia and Malawi _ dramatizes
his resolve to stimulate the fastest growing segment of his church.
   From a tiny European missionary movement a century ago, the
Catholic Church in Africa has become a powerful indigenous
institution of 75 million adherents. The Vatican expects their
numbers will increase to 100 million by the year 2,000.
   ``It is safe to say that in no other continent during the last
50 years has Christianity shown so much growth and diversity, such
a cheerful but perplexing flood of people confidently doing their
own thing, often in seemingly strange and contradictory ways,''
wrote Adrian Hastings in his book ``African Christianity.''
   The church's influence, extending far beyond the number of its
followers, is especially felt in education. Many of today's African
leaders are products of missionary schools, including the
Jesuit-educated Robert Mugabe, the Marxist president of Zimbabwe.
   Africans also play an increasingly influential role at the
Vatican, underlined by the growth in the number of African
cardinals from one to 17 in the past 30 years. Two of the cardinals
are based in Rome, including Bernardin Gantin of Benin, head of the
powerful Congregation of Bishops.
   African prelates have also made their presence felt in worldwide
church affairs. At the 1987 synod of bishops in Rome on the role of
the laity, African bishops led the way in blocking proposals by
U.S. bishops to allow women to serve in non-ordained ministries.
   But the African church also faces special problems, namely in
trying to adapt African traditions to a faith imported from Europe
while upholding its laws on polygamy, superstition and priestly
celibacy.
   The African church is also increasingly worried about the spread
of Islamic fundamentalism in countries such as Sudan and Nigeria.
   Other church-state difficulties include conflict with the
Marxist government in Mozambique and tensions with South Africa
over apartheid, which the Vatican recently called the most
systematic form of racism in the world.
   ``In spite of the problems, Africa appears as a source of joyful
hope for the church,'' the Vatican missionary agency's information
bulletin said in its 1988 review of missionary activity around the
world.
   That assessment is certainly shared by the pope, who visited 20
countries during his African pilgrimages in 1980, 1982, 1985 and
1988.
   In January, John Paul announced a special synod of Africa's 480
bishops to discuss various issues facing the church, saying he
hoped the assembly would further bolster the faith of ``those
beloved people to whom I feel so close.'' The date and site of the
synod have not yet been fixed.
   In another sign of the church's expanding presence in Africa,
the Ivory Coast is building a huge basilica, only slightly smaller
than St. Peter's in Rome, at a cost of at least $130 million.
Vatican officials, however, say the pope has no plans to attend its
inauguration later this year. Some have interpreted this as a show
of disapproval of a display of opulence.
   A dominant issue for the church has been the process of
``Africanization,'' incorporating traditional African customs and
culture in church services, liturgy, teaching, theology, music and
art.
   This movement grew out of the reforms of the Second Vatican
Council in 1962-65 and drew inspiration from the encyclical ``On
the Evangelization of Peoples'' by Pope Paul VI, who made the first
papal visit to Africa in 1969.
   The missionaries who evangelized Africa provided churches,
schools and hospitals but they often showed disdain for African
culture.
   Vatican officials say the church in recent years has gone a long
way in adopting the use of tribal drums, native dance, music and
the vernacular liturgy.
   The pope has frequently encouraged the trend but stressed that
the basic foundations of faith and teaching cannot be compromised.
   ``You are certainly aware of a danger: that of allowing the
growth of a philosophy and a theology of `Africanism' that would be
exclusively of native origin and lacking any real and profound
connection with Christ,'' he told visiting bishops from Zaire in
1983.
   One persistent problem has been polygamy, a practice outlawed by
the church but still common in much of Africa. During the pope's
tour of southern Africa last September, he lectured the 20-year-old
king of Swaziland and his four wives that family stability is based
on monogamy.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890328-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Africa-Catholics Adv02-1stAdd   03-28 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Africa-Catholics, Adv 02-1st Add,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>VATICAN CITY: on monogamy.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The church has also been hard pressed to interpret the
relationship between superstition and religion in a continent where
some church ministers have been accused of practicing witchcraft
and voodoo.
   The primate of Zambia, Archbishop Emmanuel Milingo, was recalled
to Rome in 1982 because of his faith-healing practices. He was
relieved of his position in Zambia and assigned to a low-ranking
Roman Curia post.
   According to the latest church statistics, Africa has the
highest number of catechists, religion teachers, in the world,
216,000. But it has only 18,000 priests, less than 8 percent of the
total in Europe.
   Officials say the shortage of priests is partly due to the
church's insistence on celibacy, which runs contrary to the stress
on family and children in African culture.
   To illustrate the dilemma, a Vatican official recounted how an
African cardinal was scolded by Rome for proposing three candidates
for bishop, all of whom had fathered children. The cardinal wrote
back to the Vatican: ``Finding angels is your job.''
   On a political level, the role and influence of the church often
depends on its size in each country _ ranging from Catholic
strongholds such as Zaire, Burundi and Rwanda to Sierra Leone where
they are latecomers in a Moslem majority.
   The pope and the African church have often spoken out against
human rights violations and called for peace, reconciliation and
negotiations to settle various civil wars and conflicts.
   This sometimes places the church in an adversary role. In
Mozambique, for example, the church was rebuked for urging direct
peace talks with right-wing rebels.
   In Burundi three years ago, the government nationalized some
seminaries, banned Catholic youth groups and shut down catechism
classes on grounds that the church was trying to discredit the
nation. The situation has improved since a military takeover in
1987, church officials say.
   While Islam has always been a main challenger for converts,
Moslem fundamentalism comes as a more recent threat to the church.
   The Vatican review of missionary activity listed ``fanatical
propaganda on the part of groups of radical Moslems'' as one of the
church's main challenges in Africa.
   It specifically named Sudan, where the Moslem-dominated
government in the north is fighting Christian rebels in the south,
and Nigeria, where it saw ``dangerous tension and violence created
by Islamic fanatics.''
   Fundamentalists in Sudan and Nigeria favor Islamic law. The
Vatican criticized its imposition on non-Moslems in a major
document on racism published in February.
   Nigeria's Cardinal Francis Arinze, president of the Vatican's
office for relations with non-Christians, said in a recent
interview with the Italian Catholic monthly 30 Giorni (30 Days):
``It is true that in some African countries, especially among young
converts, people don't understand why the church dedicates so much
time and effort to dialogue (with Moslems) when Islam in their own
country appears so little disposed to dialogue. I understand the
difficulties of these Christians and in a certain way I can say
they are right.''
   One of the harshest public attacks on the church came from
Libya's Col. Moammar Gadhafi.
   ``Africa is not Christian,'' he declared during a visit to
Rwanda in 1982. ``Christians are intruders to Africa. Christians
are agents of colonialism. You must wage a holy war so that Islam
may spread in Africa. God willing, Islam will triumph in Africa
over the religion of colonialism _ Christianity.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
