<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1333EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Africa-Cardinals Adv02   03-28 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Africa-Cardinals, Adv 02,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Catholics in Africa _ The Cardinals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: One of a package of four stories. With b0772-b0773.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Africa got its first native cardinal 29
years ago. Today it has 17, including the head of one of the most
powerful posts at the Vatican.
   Cardinal Bernardin Gantin of Benin, 66, is prefect of the
Congregation of Bishops, which directs the world's 4,000 Roman
Catholic bishops and plays a major role in the selection of bishops
under the guidelines of Pope John Paul II.
   Gantin, who has held the position since 1984 and is the first
black prelate to head a major Vatican office, has been mentioned as
a possible papal candidate.
   The other Vatican-based African cardinal is Francis Arinze of
Nigeria, who runs the office for relations with non-Christians, an
important issue in Africa where many Catholics live side-by-side
with Moslems.
   Another prominent African prelate at the Vatican is Archbishop
Emmanuel Milingo, the former primate of Zambia, who was recalled to
Rome in 1982 and stripped of his native post because of controversy
over his alleged faith-healing practices. He now has a post with
the Vatican office for migration and tourism.
   Pope John XXIII named the first black African cardinal, Laurean
Rugambwa of Tanzania, in 1960.
   The number of African cardinals has gradually increased under
John Paul, who last spring elevated three more prelates in
Mozambique, Cameroon and Mauritius.
   All the African cardinals are black, except for those from
Algeria and South Africa.
   Most of Africa's 480 bishops are black, reflecting the steady
Africanization of the church _ a process encouraged by the pope.
   ``It is not the church imported from outside,'' he said after
his first visit in 1980, ``it is their church, the church lived
authentically, in an African way.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 2</NOTE>
