<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sun April 2 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Catholics in Africa _ Quotations of John Paul II</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: One of a package of four stories. With b0772-b0773.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some quotations by Pope John Paul
II during four previous trips to Africa:
   ``When I see all these courageous Christians here, in Africa, I
cannot help thinking that, nowadays, Christ has many friends in
Africa, and that the church in Africa is mature to face up to all
vexations and all trials.'' _ Congo, May 1980.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Preserve carefully your African roots. Safeguard the values of
your culture. ... Remain very vigilant with regard to models of
society which are based on the selfish pursuit of individual
happiness and on the god of money, or on the class of struggle and
violent means. All materialism is a source of degradation for man
and of enslavement of social life.'' _ Ivory Coast, May 1980.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``All Africa, when allowed to take charge of its own affairs,
without being subjected to interference and pressure from any
outside powers or groups, will ... astound the rest of the world by
its achievements.'' _ Nigeria, February 1982.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Moslems and Christians have generally understood each other
badly, and sometimes, in the past, we have opposed each other and
even exhausted each other in polemics and war. ... I think God
invites us today to change our old habits.'' _ Morocco, August 1985.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Christians find that a monogamous marital union provides the
foundation upon which to build a stable family in accordance with
the original plan of God for marriage.'' _ Swaziland, September
1988.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Powerful political, economic and ideological forces endanger
the still fragile stability of countries which are only beginning
to consolidate their recently acquired independence. Those forces
impede the self-determination of peoples, they foment ideological,
ethnic and tribal conflicts, they delay the process of
development.'' _ Zimbabwe, September 1988.
</TEXT>
