<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ueberroth Discussing Deal To Buy Eastern Airlines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with quote; SUBS 13th graf, `And,
Minneapolis ...,' to UPDATE with quote on Kerkorian, restore dropped word
`banker;' picks up 14th graf, `Pohlad and ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>RONALD BLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter V. Ueberroth, the financial wizard who
made millions for the Olympics and baseball, is discussing a
purchase of strikebound Eastern Airlines, The Associated Press
learned Monday.
   An offer from Ueberroth may be presented to the board of
directors of Eastern parent Texas Air Corp. in the next few days,
airline industry and baseball sources said on condition of
anonymity. Ueberroth's term as baseball commissioner ends Saturday.
   ``I know Peter's been trying to put together a group'' to
finance a purchase of Eastern, one source said.
   Ueberroth did not wish to comment on the matter, his spokesman,
Rich Levin, said here Monday night.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell, contacted for comment at his
Miami home, said, ``I've heard about it. But we just don't comment
on rumors.''
   Texas Air's board is holding a regularly scheduled meeting
Tuesday and Wednesday, said a source close to the company.
   Texas Air spokesman Art Kent in Houston said the company would
have no comment on the matter.
   ``There are a lot of those rumors going around,'' Kent said.
``If and when any agreement is reached to sell Eastern I'm sure all
the parties involved will issue a statement.''
   Ueberroth was approached last fall by officials of Eastern's
unions to consider taking over the troubled airline, which filed
for bankruptcy protection March 9, five days after the start of a
Machinists union strike that was supported by airline pilots.
   The unions have said they would make concessions if Ueberroth
took over, possibly in return for ownership of part of the airline.
   Telephone calls for comment to the office of the Machinists
local for Eastern in Miami and union officials were not answered
Monday night.
   Since the strike began, Eastern has been flying only about 10
percent of its normally scheduled 1,040 flights. Most of those
flights have been on the shuttle between New York and Boston and
Washington, and on its Latin American routes.
   Ueberroth met with Eastern officials during baseball's winter
meetings in Atlanta last December, then traveled to Miami for
further talks, a baseball source said. In addition, Ueberroth and
California investor Kirk Kerkorian have discussed a possible buyout
with Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo, a source said.
   However, another source said it was not clear whether Kerkorian
was involved.
   Minneapolis banker Carl R. Pohlad, who owns baseball's Minnesota
Twins, is a director of Texas Air and owns 12 percent of Jet
Capital Corp., Texas Air's holding company. Lorenzo owns 48.7
percent of Jet Capital. Pohlad reportedly brought Ueberroth in to
negotiate the purchase of the airline.
   Pohlad and other Texas Air directors have urged Lorenzo to sell
Eastern since the strike began, sources said. At the time of the
bankruptcy filing, Eastern had about $300 million in cash and was
losing about $4 million a day, according to papers filed with U.S.
Bankruptcy Court in New York.
   Kerkorian, who is a friend of Ueberroth's, is majority owner of
MGM-UA Communications Co. Last fall, MGM Pictures Inc., a
subsidiary, offered to hire Ueberroth as chief executive officer,
but Ueberroth turned down the deal.
   Kerkorian also owns MGM Grand Air, a first-class-only airline
that flies primarily between New York and Los Angeles.
   A call to Kerkorian's Los Angeles office asking for comment was
not returned.
   A bid by Ueberroth could compete for Eastern's attention against
an offer by takeover strategist Carl Icahn, who has publicly
expressed interest and has been supported by Eastern's unions.
Icahn is chairman and owner of Trans World Airlines Inc.
   Ueberroth, 51, is known as an iron-willed administrator who
talked down to foreign officials during his five years as president
of the Los Angeles Olympic Organizing Committee and then bullied
baseball's owners.
   The 1984 Los Angeles Olympics, expected to lose money or at best
break even, made $230 million.
   He was elected baseball commissioner in March 1984, and took
office that October. Baseball lost money for 11 consecutive years
before he took office but then made $209 million in his four full
seasons, according to financial statements obtained by the AP.
   During his time in baseball, Ueberroth stayed active in
business. He is a director of several major corporations and as a
board member of E.F. Hutton Inc. engineered the company's sale to
Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc., earning $850,000 in fees.
   Ueberroth was vice president of Trans International Airlines for
two years when in 1963 he founded a small travel agency in Southern
California. Eventually, he built First Travel Corp. into the
second-largest business of its kind in North America.
</TEXT>
