<FIRST>r f PM-Ford-Mazda     03-28 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ford-Mazda,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Automakers Purchase Shares In Japanese Sales Network</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese car dealer Autorama Inc. will use fresh
capital from Ford Motor Co. and Mazda Motor Corp. to strengthen its
sales network, Ford and Mazda announced.
   Autorama plans to increase its 200 sales outlets in Japan to 500
in the next four years, Mazda spokesman Jim Gill said Monday.
   The company will issue 8,000 shares of stock, increasing its
capital to $10.7 million from the current $7.6 million.
   Ford will purchase a 34 percent share of the $10.7 million in
capital and Mazda will purchase a 39 percent share, the companies
said. Ford owns 25 percent of Mazda, a Japanese automaker.
   Autorama was established in 1982 to distribute Mazda-made
products under the Ford name in Japan, including the Festiva
automobile, also sold in the United States, and the Laser and
Telstar cars, not sold on the U.S. market.
   Since last year, Autorama also has distributed the Ford Probe,
made by Mazda at Flat Rock, Mich., and the Ford-made Taurus
automobile. This year it began distributing the Lincoln Continental
in Japan.
</TEXT>
