<FIRST>u f AM-TankerSpill 3rdLd-Writethru f0259 03-28 1325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0259,1368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winds Hamper Oil Cleanup Effort; Exxon `Overwhelmed'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-9, `Hazelwood, whose ...,' with 7 grafs to UPDATE
with New York Times report on New Hampshire conviction; picks up 10th graf,
`A National ...' SUBS 25th graf, `Workers continued ...' Minor editing
throughout to tighten. No pickup. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos AGX2-5; LaserGraphic NY28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong winds Monday delayed efforts to
control a huge oil spill in Prince William Sound, and the president
of Exxon Shipping said the company was ``a little overwhelmed'' by
the magnitude of the cleanup.
   Federal investigators piecing together the sequence of events
leading up to the spill said they planned to interview the captain
and other bridge officers of the tanker Exxon Valdez.
   The captain, Joseph Hazelwood, was not on the bridge when the
vessel left shipping lanes to avoid ice, rammed a charted reef and
ran aground early Friday. The third mate, who did not have proper
certification, was in charge, Exxon Shipping Co. President Frank
Iarossi said.
   Investigators said at a news conference that the results of drug
and alcohol tests on crew members will be made public when
officials receive them, possibly in two or three days.
   Hazelwood, of Huntington, N.Y., has had drinking problems in the
past, according to reports.
   ``Yes, there's a previous history going back five years or
more,'' Iarossi said Sunday in response to reporters' questions
about alcohol abuse by Hazelwood. ``Personally, what happened five
years ago to somebody is not germane to this accident.
   However, The New York Times reported Tuesday that Hazelwood was
convicted last September in New Hampshire of drunken driving and
that his license was revoked a second time.
   The New York Department of Motor Vehicles said his license
remains revoked.
   In 1984, Hazelwood was arrested in Suffolk County, N.Y., on Long
Island on a drunken driving charge, two sources connected with law
enforcement who spoke on condition of anonymity told The Associated
Press.
   Hazelwood pleaded guilty in 1985 to driving while intoxicated,
and received a conditional discharge and a fine of about $510, the
sources said. Under a conditional discharge, a person's criminal
record is cleared if there are no other arrests over a certain
period.
   Suffolk County Police Officer Peter Kelley confirmed the
essential details of the sources' account.
   Hazelwood's license was revoked then, but was restored in 1986
after he completed a state program, the Times said.
   Telephone calls to Hazelwood's home Monday were not answered.
   A National Transportation Safety Board spokewoman in Washington,
D.C., said Hazelwood, third mate, quartermaster and bridge lookout
are among those who will be questioned.
   NTSB officials said it was questionable whether the drug and
alcohol tests will be of much value.
   Drucella Anderson, an NTSB spokeswoman, said there were
indications the tests may have been administered as long as 10
hours after the accident.
   ``I don't know how good the (tests) will be,'' said Rachel
Halterman, another spokeswoman for the NTSB in Washington. The
board plans to open a formal inquiry in Anchorage sometime in the
next three weeks.
   The 987-foot tanker, carrying 1.2 million barrels of North Slope
crude oil, apparently struck a glancing blow against a rock, kept
going and hit rocks a second time, then ran aground, Iarossi said.
   About 240,000 barrels spilled through the hull, creating an oil
slick that has since covered about 100 square miles, according to
the Coast Guard. The oil is slowly heading south toward the Gulf of
Alaska, but must pass numerous islands before it reaches open sea.
   At about 10.1 million gallons, the spill is the biggest such
accident on record in the United States.
   The spill closed the Port of Valdez, the southern terminus of
the Alaska Pipeline, and crude oil prices rose sharply on Monday.
   Meanwhile, gusts up to 50 mph idled most aircraft, including one
that was to spray chemicals to break up the oil slick.
   Four- to six-foot waves whipped the slick into a frothy mix that
Coast Guard Cmdr. Steve McCall called ``chocolate mousse.''
   The spreading oil stained another island as it stretched 40
miles southwest of Bligh Reef. The beaches on at least three
islands ``just got clobbered,'' McCall said.
   As the oil washes into inlets along the islands, it poses a
greater danger to animals and micro-organisms, but also will make
cleanup easier, McCall said.
   And as the oil gets whipped up, chemical dispersants may no
longer be useful, McCall said. Instead, cleanup crews intend to
rely on containment booms and skimmers and burning.
   Iarossi said the wind damaged some of the containment booms used
to corral the oil, including some around the stricken tanker.
   The vessel remained stuck on Bligh Reef, about 25 miles from
Valdez. Iarossi said the wind pivoted the ship 12 degrees to the
north, and that the crew said the new position felt much more
stable.
   Workers continued pumping operations to remove the 1 million
barrels of oil left on board the Exxon Valdez. By Monday evening,
about 120,000 barrels had been transferred to the Exxon Baton
Rouge. Iarossi said Exxon hoped to have about 95 percent of the
remaining oil off the vessel in three or four days.
   He said he cannot guarantee that all the oil will be removed
from the tanker nor that all of the slick will be cleaned up.
   ``Frankly, we are a little overwhelmed,'' Iarossi said. ``We
still have a major problem ahead of us, but we feel we are
gaining.''
   McCall said the Port of Valdez will be reopened to limited
traffic Tuesday. To get to the port, vessels will have to operate
outside normal shipping channels to avoid the spill, he said.
   To help them steer through unfamiliar waters, ships will be
required to take on local pilots farther offshore than normal, he
said.
   Nearly a dozen oil tankers were anchored more than 30 miles from
Valdez, waiting to be allowed in.
   The Alyeska Pipeline Service Co. has reduced the normal daily
flow in the trans-Alaska oil pipeline from 2 million barrels to
about 800,000 barrels because of limited storage capacity in
Valdez. The port has been closed since the Exxon tanker ran aground.
   Gov. Steve Cowper was critical of the time it took Exxon and
Alyeska Pipeline Service Co. to begin the cleanup. Alyeska operates
the oil-loading terminal at Valdez.
   ``People should have anticipated such a spill as this,'' Cowper
said at a news conference in Juneau.
   Fishermen held a news conference earlier in the day to complain
that Exxon was not taking adquate steps to warn cleanup workers and
nearby villagers about the health threat from the oil and new plans
to burn it with jelled gasoline.
   A spokeswoman for the Cordova District Fishermen's Union said
use of chemicals to disperse the oil is accceptable only under
limited conditions, and that burning the oil should be ruled out.
   The fishing industry objected to the two methods on
environmental grounds, but Iarossi said conventional methods such
as containment booms and skimmers are inadequate to deal with such
a large spill.
   A man from Tatitlek said many of the nearby village's 100
residents suffered nausea and severe headaches after burn tests
were conducted last week.
   ``The whole village is getting sick,'' said Norman Vlasoff.
   Cowper declared Prince William Sound, ordinarily teeming with
fish, marine mammals and birds, a disaster area. He said he would
seek federal money to help with the spill.
   Pamela Bergman, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Department of
Interior, said at least 90 contaminated birds and two sea otters
had been spotted. But wildlife officials feared there were many
more that went undetected, she said.
   ``I think sorting out the money is something that will occupy
lawyers for years to come,'' Cowper said, adding that Alyeska and
Exxon should share the blame and all costs and that damages should
include any loss of income suffered by fishermen.
</TEXT>
