<FIRST>r f PM-NuclearSafety Bjt   03-28 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Safety, Bjt,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>10 Years After TMI, Nuclear Plants Still Unsafe, Group Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release at 10 a.m. EST; Time set by source.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 33,000 nuclear plant mishaps _
ranging from stuck valves to radioactive leaks _ have been reported
by utilities to the Nuclear Regulatory Commission in the 10 years
since the partial meltdown at Three Mile Island, according to a
study released today.
   ``A decade after the accident at Three Mile Island, the Nand the
nuclear industry have forgotten the lesson of TMI,'' saan
Claybrook, president of PublCitizen, the advocacy group whicred the
report. ``The plants pose a continuing danger to the public's
health and safety.''
   But NRC spokesman Joseph Fouchard, who characterized the study
as ``pinging the industry,'' said nuclear powerlants are safer than
they were ago.
   ``There have been fewer challenges to the system, fewer
automatic shutdowns, the amount of waste geneed at these plants has
gone down, they're cleaner, and the amount of cumulative radiation
exposure to employees has gone down,'' Fouchard said. ``All of the
fety indicators are going in a positive direction.''
   The study, ``Nuclear Power Safety: 1979-1989,'' chartsincrease
at the beginning of the decade in the ner of reported nuclear plant
mishaps. These are or breakdowns of plant systems and procedures
which may pose a threat to public safety. The operating
utilitycidents to the NRC by filing a ``Licensee Event Report,'' or
LEThe NRC has a system for grading the severity ofc Citizen did not
take this into account.
   In 1979, there were 2,310 reported mishaps at the nation's 67
nuclear reactors, including the partial meltdown r increased to
3,804 in 1980, to 4,060 in 1981, and to 4,500 in 1982. By 1983, e
number of reported incidents exceeded 5,000 at 82 operating plants,
the group found.
   In 1984, however, the NRC changed its system for reporting such
events, and the tonumber of LERs dropped to 2,460 that year,
according to Public Citizen. 1985, with 3,050 LERs, was described
by the NRC as one of the worst years in the history of the nuclear
power industrarked by 645 emergency plant shutdowns and 38 fines
totaling nearly $4 million levied against utilities.
   Since then, the number of nuclear plant mishaps has apparently
leveled off, although ``even the NRC's data is incomplete and thus
these figures probably do not reflect the entmishaps each year,''
the report said.
   For example, in 1984, the first year that the new repting
requirements were in effect, the NRC estimated that betweeent of
reportable mishaps were not reported, the study said.
   If the NRC's assessment is correct, the LER counsimply reflects
the mishaps which the industry chooses to report, while the actual
number of poy significant safety events may be much higher,''
Public Citize The number of LERs has remaine relatively constant
since 1985:60 in 1986 and 2,955 in 1987. Incomplete data for 1988
reveled 2,296 mishaps at the nation's 108 licensed-to-operate
reactors.
   Total mishaps for the 10 years: 33,475.
   The report is findings from Public Citizen's annual nuclear
power safety reports and preliminary data being e group's
forthcoming 1988 report. The data were obtained under Information
act requests and from other NRC sources.
</TEXT>
