<FIRST>r f PM-GTE     03-28 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GTE,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>GTE Announces Layoffs, Reconsideration Of Headquarters Move</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IRVING, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $59 million telephone rate cut and $138
million refund ordered by state regulators prompted GTE Corp.'s
General Telephone Southwest to annouce it will eliminate about 600
jobs in Texas and defer filling 400 vacancies.
   In addition, a spokesman from GTE's corporate headquarters in
Stamford, Conn., said Monday the cutback means the regional
division will put off plans to relocate the headquarters of its
telephone operations division.
   Al Galletly, a GTE spokesman in Stamford, said the reassessment
of the $40 million headquarters decision was for financial reasons
and declined to comment when asked if it was in retaliation for the
rate decision.
   Plans called for about 2,500 GTE employees to be relocated to
the North Dallas area by the end of 1989, with another 1,500 hired
locally or transferred from other facilities by the project's
completion.
   E.L. ``Buddy'' Langley, president of General Telephone
Southwest, said that in addition to cutting regular employees, the
phone company will release more than 100 people who are working for
GTE as contractors and reduce its capital investment budget by more
than $100 million.
   He said the company would defer or eliminate further
modernization of its telephone switching centers and networks in
Texas that had been scheduled for completion in 1989.
   The company also will abandon plans for buying another facility
in Irving for $40, reduce vehicle orders $5 million and defer or
reduce expenses for training, building repairs and other items by
up to $3 million, he added.
   Langley said GTE has petitioned for a rehearing of the Public
Utility Commission rate decision, and that a hearing on the motion
is set for April 5 in Austin.
   The PUC in February voted to lower GTE Southwest's rates by $59
million and require the telephone company to refund $138 million to
customers over two years.
   The refund resulted because the commission set the effective
date of the rates retroactively to Jan. 1, 1987.
   GTE had requested an $81.4 million rate increase.
   GTE Southwest said the commission failed to recognize its
aggressive efforts to improve service and modernize, and that
``could have a chilling effect'' on future utility investment in
the state.
   A $59 million annual reduction would decrease residential rates
by an average of more than 17 percent, according to PUC figures.
   GTE Southwest serves 1.2 million residential and business
customers in Texas, Arkansas, Oklahoma and New Mexico.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
