<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 0246EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Sears-ColdwellBanker     03-28 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sears-Coldwell Banker,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Figures Invest In Purchase Of Coldwell Banker Unit From Sears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci and
former presidential aide Frederic V. Malek are among the investors
buying the Coldwell Banker commerical real-estate business from
Sears, Roebuck and Co.
   Carlucci, who ended a stint as defense secretary in January, is
co-chairman of the Carlyle Group, a Washington-based merchant
banking firm that is participating in the transaction announced
Monday.
   Carlucci also served as chairman of Sears World Trade Inc., a
Sears subsidiary, from 1983 to 1986.
   Malek, the former president of the Marriott Hotels division of
Marriott Corp., is a longtime Republican party activist and friend
of President Bush who now is affiliated with the Carlyle Group as
an independent merchant banker.
   He served as a special assistant to President Richard M. Nixon
and as a deputy director of the Office of Management and Budget in
the Nixon administration.
   But the largest shareholders in the Los Angeles-based company
will be its nearly 5,000 employees, officials said. They will own
50 percent of Coldwell Banker stock, which Sears is selling for
more than $300 million.
   Officials would not disclose the exact purchase price of the
unit, which is one of the nation's largest commercial real-estate
operations, with 1988 gross revenues of about $460 million.
   Bill Hinckley, a spokesman for the unit in Los Angeles, said the
price was between $300 million and $400 million.
   Chicago-based Sears said it would retain the residential
real-estate operations of Coldwell Banker and the Coldwell Banker
name. The new owners of the commercial unit have up to three years
to settle on a new name and logo.
   Sears, the nation's largest retailer and a major player in the
financial-services industry, announced last fall that it planned to
sell the Coldwell Banker unit as part of a corporate restructuring
that also includes the planned sale of its headquarters, the
world's tallest building, in Chicago.
   Hinckley said other investors in the company include the Mellon
family of Virginia and other prominent U.S. and Japanese investors.
   Financing for the transaction is being arranged by Sumitomo Bank
and Bankers Trust Co., officials said.
   James J. Didion, chairman of the unit, said the ``enthusiasm and
commitment'' of the employee-owners would strengthen the firm's
``entrepreneurial direction.''
   The employees participating in the transaction include former
UCLA football star and 1967 Heisman Trophy winner Gary Beban,
president of one of the organization's three divisions.
</TEXT>
