<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 0849EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GM-Bias     03-28 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GM-Bias,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black GM Workers Debate Out-of-Court Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several hundred salaried General Motors Corp.
workers are trying to block a proposed racial discrimination
settlement, calling it inadequate.
   About 600 employees met Monday to discuss their dissatisfaction
and sign petitions asking U.S. District Judge John Feikens to
refuse to approve the settlement. Feikens had asked members of the
suit to respond to the settlement by March 31.
   The recent settlement would cover more than 10,000 current and
former salaried workers in Michigan, Ohio and Indiana who sued the
automaker in 1983, claiming they were denied raises and promotions
given to white colleagues with similar jobs.
   The offer could cost the automaker $20 million to $40 million,
attorneys said. It includes payments to former employees and raises
for some current GM workers.
   GM would acknowledge no wrongdoing under the proposed settlement.
   ``The settlement is entirely, totally inadequate,'' said
Napoleon Quick, a leader of Concerned Black Salaried Employees,
which organized Monday's meeting.
   Members of the group said the settlement, among other things,
doesn't provide money for damages or lost salary, which affects
fringe benefits and requires individuals to file claims to be
eligible for settlement payments.
</TEXT>
