<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 0909EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Unisys-Settlement     03-28 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Unisys-Settlement,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settlement Reached In Defense Contractor Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN THOMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials hailed a cash
settlement between the government and Unisys Corp. on fraud
charges, but the nation's second largest computer company said it
felt vindicated by the dismissal of charges.
   U.S. Attorney James Wilson announced Monday that Unisys made a
$700,000 payment to the government in return for federal
authorities throwing out the indictment.
   The charges last October against Unisys and its predecessor,
Sperry Corp., stemmed from a $526 million contract to upgrade the
Air Force's worldwide computer system. It followed a four-year
investigation by authorities.
   As part of the settlement, the company also agreed to abandon a
claim against the government by Sperry for more than $800,000 in
disputed unpaid invoices, Wilson said.
   ``We feel this is an overall victory, an outstanding victory,''
he said about the settlement.
   Convictions in the case would only have resulted in maximum
fines of $50,000, Wilson said. He said the settlement was not an
admission of guilt on the part of the companies.
   A spokesman for Unisys said the settlement was a ``business
decision'' reached to avoid continuing litigation and the company
continued to deny any wrongdoing. J. Peter Hynes said the dismissal
of charges vindicates the company.
   ``We have said all along that there was no criminality
involved,'' said Hynes in a telephone interview from the company's
Blue Bell, Pa., headquarters.
   He said the settlement was ``just a convenience to get the whole
situation behind us and continue working with the Air Force, which
is a valuable customer.''
   Unisys and Sperry were accused of overcharging the government in
1983 for an unspecified portion of a $500,000 invoice involving the
computer contract.
   Unisys was formed as a result of a merger of Burroughs Corp. and
Sperry in September 1986.
   Wilson said uncertainty about the criminal liability of
successor corporations following mergers played a part in the
government choosing to settle. Government prosecutors appealed
after U.S. District Judge Joel Dubina dismissed the case against
Unisys in December because the company did not exist until 1986.
   In the settlement filed March 21, Dubina's dismissal order was
thrown out as part of the legal work leading to the agreement to
drop charges against both companies.
   The death of a key government witness also was a factor in
dismissing the indictment, Wilson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
