<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     03-28 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0267</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rose in early trading today
amid government efforts to knock down the value of the dollar.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 10.35 to 2,268.21
as of 10 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones nearly 2 to 1, with
588 stocks higher, 302 lower and 518 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 24.26 million in the first
half-hour of trading.
   European central banks and the Federal Reserve joined in selling
dollars, but the intervention appeared to have little immediate
effect on the currency.
   Stock investors were paying close attention to the credit
markets. Bond prices were little changed today, while short-term
interest rates edged higher, providing an attractive alternative to
stocks.
   Meanwhile, oil futures prices fell today after running up Monday.
   Among actively traded issues, American Telephone &amp; Telegraph was
unchanged at 31], General Electric was up { at 44{, Anheuser Busch
was up { at 34~, and Texaco was up { at 53{.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 0.44 at 163.76.
   On the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was up
0.33 at 325.83.
   On Monday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 14.82 points to
2,257.86.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 4 on the
NYSE, with 773 up, 628 down and 537 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 112.96 million shares, against 153.75
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
