<FIRST>u f PM-Fruehauf     03-28 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fruehauf,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Terex Unit Buys Fruehauf Trailer Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>wsbmam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fruehauf Corp., struggling with indebtedness and
weak earnings, today announced plans to sell operations that
include its truck trailer manufacturing business to Terex Corp. for
$232.5 million, while retaining its Kelsey-Hayes Co. auto
components subsidiary.
   A Terex subsidiary, FRH Acquisition, will pay $169.4 million
cash and assume about $63.1 million in long-term debt in a
transaction expected to be closed May 15, Fruehauf said.
   FRH Acquisition will acquire the truck-trailer manufacturing
operations, a maritime refinishing products business and Fruehauf's
80 percent interest in CEMCO, a company that makes loading cranes
for shipping.
   Fruehauf then will consist primarily of Kelsey Hayes, which
manufactures wheels, brake components, anti-lock braking systems
and other components.
   The purchase price is subject to adjustment based on changes in
the net assets of the businesses to be acquired before the closing
date, Fruehauf said.
   Company spokesman David A. Hladik said Fruehauf had been
reviewing several acquisition proposals in addition to one from
Varity Corp., a Toronto farm equipment maker, that was withdrawn
Feb. 27.
   Fruehauf said it expects to receive acquisition proposals for
the remainder of the company, minus the trailer and other
operations being sold, in the near future.
   The company had battled high debts, interest payments and
operating losses since its managers avoided a hostile takeover
attempt by acquiring control of the company in a debt-financed
takeover in December 1986.
   Fruehauf managers arranged the buyout with the financial help of
Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., which obtained a 31 percent voting interest,
to avoid a takeover bid by New York investor Asher Edelman. Merrill
Lynch Capital Markets and Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. are acting as
financial advisers in the current transaction, Fruehauf said.
   Fruehauf, which employs about 15,800 people, reported losses of
$41.5 million on revenue of $1.96 billion in 1987 and losses of
$56.5 million on revenue of $2.09 billion in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
