<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   03-28 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Steady On Reported Soviet Interest In Corn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mixed in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid rumors that
Monday's sharp price break had stirred some Soviet interest in
buying U.S. corn.
   Prices tumbled on Monday as rain began falling in the Great
Plains and Midwest, where dryness from last year's drought lingers.
   Rain continued to fall this morning but trading was more heavily
influenced by the unconfirmed talk of a Soviet bid for U.S. corn
and by a National Weather Service forecast issued late Monday that
predicted dry weather in the Midwest for the latter half of next
week.
   Traders also are jockeying for position ahead of Friday's
quarterly grain stocks report and annual spring planting estimate
from the Agriculture Department.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent lower to 1} cents higher with
the contract for delivery in May at $4.29 a bushel; corn was { cent
to 2\ cents higher with May at $2.73} a bushel; oats were 2} cents
to 3} cents higher with May at $1.99 a bushel; soybeans were \ cent
to 1\ cents lower with May at $7.68 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .12 cent lower to .05 cent higher with April at
78.07 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .38 cent
higher with April at 82.20 cents a pound; live hogs were unchanged
to .27 cent lower with April at 42.27 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .05 cent to .27 cent lower with May at 36.90 cents a
pound.
   Cattle futures settled mostly higher on Monday while pork
futures were mostly lower.
</TEXT>
