<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 0029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv29   03-28 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv29,0798</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Massive Myth of The Green Eyeshade</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Wednesday, March 29</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nonsense, said the professor, ``pure myth, the
myth of the green eyeshade.''
   He was referring to repeated stories in the business press that
the financially-oriented executive, a once popular breed of
manager, is about to become a management fossil.
   The truth, he said, is that the breed is alive, well and
multiplying. The misunderstanding, he said, is based on inaccurate
assumptions and superficial analyses _ as well as on old-fashioned
notions of financial people.
   To begin, said Professor Eugene Jennings, who pioneered studies
of routes to executive success, it is assumed that the heyday of
the financially oriented executive was in the 1950s, when it
actually was in the `70s.
   Those with an understanding of numbers came into their own, he
says, when corporations discovered, somewhat belatedly, that they
were in the business of enhancing shareholder value. That was even
more of a factor than was the rise of computers.
   In the 1950s and 1960s, he says, fewer than 15 percent of chief
executive officers were financially trained. Companies then were
functionally organized _ around manufacturing or sales, for example
_ rather than around finances.
   In the 1970s there developed a corporate culture more oriented
to numbers. Chief financial officers, controllers and the like
proliferated, one reason being that corporations divided themselves
into smaller business units.
   Hewlett Packard, for example, now has 50 business units.
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph has 19. And some corporations such
as General Electric have more than 100 units of varying
independence, all needing financial leadership.
   The financial groundswell continues, says Jennings, a professor
of business at Michigan State University.
   Even plant managers today are aware of such data as the real
return on invested capital, he says. ``Once they worked only
against a budget; now they work against a financial plan. They
understand cash and capital needs.''
   Jennings, who often serves as adviser to top officers and
boards, tells of a very large corporation that surveyed 39 plant
managers in 1979 to determine their understanding of elementary
accounting and finance.
   Fewer than 30 percent achieved what he calls a decent score,
spurring the company to send all plant managers to an extensive
financial seminar. In addition, it added to their objectives a high
return on invested capital.
   Result: In 1986 the same plants were surveyed and more than 70
percent of the managers received a decent score.
   ``In our largest corporations today you cannot tell what plant
and general managers were formally educated in accounting and
finance from those whose college major was engineering or
marketing,'' said Jennings.
   He calls this the institutionalization of numbers and he
provides some numbers from his own research to document the
phrasing.
   _The number of individuals holding the title chief financial
officer in large corporations has more than doubled since 1979.
   _The number of titled controllers has nearly tripled.
   _There are one-quarter more chief executive officers with
financial background and experience than in 1979.
   _The number of chief financial officers with formal education in
accounting has doubled in 10 years.
   Keeping tabs on such things is the professor's life work. He
began his studies of what he calls corporate mobility patterns in
the late 1940s, when he published his first book, ``The Mobile
Manager,'' now considered a basic reference.
   It is for this reason, among others, that he feels compelled to
set the record straight on the premature demise of the
financially-oriented breed of corporate executive. And he seeks to
deflate these other popular myths:
   _Financially-oriented executives are in place strictly for the
short run, to correct immediate or temporary problems.
   If this is so, he says, how do you explain the reign of Roger
Smith as chief executive officer of General Motors, who has been
entrusted with a $65 billion rebuilding program?
   _Financial executives are not creative, do not make good general
managers, and are risk-averse.
   All wrong, he says, none more so than the last. ``Because they
know the numbers they are in fact more apt to understand prudent
risk,'' says the professor.
   _They have tunnel vision _ they see all through a narrow prism.
   ``Unfounded,'' he says. He maintains that about half the very
largest companies with new, advanced product lines in electronics,
consumer goods, fast foods, chemicals and retailing are headed by
financially-oriented executives.
   All such notions are old-fashioned and dated, he said. All, that
is, are part of the the massive, master myth of the green eyeshade.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Wednesday, March 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
