<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     03-28 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0275</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rose in morning trading today
as the dollar surged higher in spite of government efforts to
restrain it.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 16.25 to 2,274.11
as of noon on Wall Street.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones about 3 to 2, with
754 stocks higher, 493 lower and 542 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 74.18 million shares by noon
EST, up from 50.72 million shares at the same time Monday.
   European central banks and the Federal Reserve joined in selling
dollars, but the intervention failed to prevent the U.S. currency
from shooting upward.
   Stock investors were paying close attention to the credit
markets, and the dollar's strength helped buoy bond prices.
Short-term interest rates, which provide an attractive alternative
to stocks, were little changed.
   Meanwhile, oil futures prices fell today after running up Monday.
   NWA, parent of Northwest Airlines, soared 9{ to 70{. An
investment group that has acquired 4.9 percent of NWA is interested
in taking it over, the company disclosed today.
   Pan Am led the list of most actively traded New York Stock
Exchange issues, up \ at 4{.
   Among other actively traded issues, American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph was unchanged at 31], General Electric was up ] at 44],
and Anheuser Busch was up ~ at 35\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 0.67 at 163.99.
   On the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was up
0.09 at 325.59.
