<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Names Bjt   03-28 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Names, Bjt,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Saga Attracting Big Names, Big Egos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baseball bosses, casino kings, astronauts and
corporate raiders _ the saga that is Eastern Airlines now features
a virtual honor roll of big names and big egos from the big leagues.
   From baseball commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth and developer
Donald Trump to former Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci and
takeover artist Carl Icahn, glamour names from business and
politics are being mentioned for key roles in either saving or
buying the beleaguered carrier.
   The cast of characters isn't surprising for an airline that has
been run by a World War I flying ace, an Apollo astronaut and its
current high-profile chairman, who has been reviled by unions as
the Boris Badenov of the airline industry.
   The name-dropping potential has grown almost daily during the
25-day Eastern strike as the soap opera of the 60-year-old airline
has moved from boardroom to picket line to bankruptcy court.
   ``There's a little emotional, sentimental factor in it,'' said
Robert Serling, an aviation historian in Tuscon, Ariz., trying to
explain part of Eastern's allure. ``It is an old, very respected
carrier that's played a part in the country's air transportation
history since the '20s.''
   Ueberroth, who steps down as baseball commissioner Saturday, is
being mentioned as a possible Eastern buyer. A former vice
president of Trans International Airlines, Ueberroth also founded a
small travel agency that later grew into giant First Travel Corp.,
the continent's second largest such business.
   Ueberroth has turned around unprofitable operations before _
leading the 1984 Olympics to an unprecedented $230 million profit
and boosting baseball's drooping attendance and earnings.
   Trump, the multimillionaire casino and real estate developer,
made an artful $365 million deal last year for Eastern's Northeast
shuttle. Since the strike, Trump has said he wants to cut his price
by a third.
   Icahn already owns Trans World Airlines and is a union favorite
to acquire Eastern. Talks between Eastern and Icahn were held last
year and Icahn has restarted negotiations with unions.
   Carlucci, whom President Reagan appointed national security
adviser after the Iran-Contra debacle and later became defense
secretary, is among the candidates for a different kind of cleanup
job, the bankruptcy examiner who would scrutinize deals between
Eastern and its parent, Texas Air Corp.
   Another candidate for examiner is Leon Silverman, an attorney
for jailed stock speculator Ivan Boesky.
   The board of Texas Air itself includes Carl Pohlad, owner of
baseball's Minnesota Twins and a longtime business associate of
Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo. Pohlad reportedly brought in
Ueberroth to negotiate an Eastern sale.
   Eastern, once one of the world's four largest carriers, always
has been a place for glamour names. It was run by Eddie
Rickenbacker, the World War I flying ace, from 1935 until he was
ousted by the company's board in 1964.
   Later piloting Eastern was Frank Borman, an Air Force colonel
who commanded the Apollo 8 moon orbital mission. Borman, who
appeared in the company's television ads, governed Eastern at a
time it ran up huge debts and later oversaw the sale of the airline
to Texas Air in 1986.
   As Eastern's fate emerges in bankruptcy court and business
deals, some analysts say even bigger fish may emerge.
   ``You don't know who's the real money behind it right now,''
said Robert Joedicke of Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc. ``They may
not want to surface yet.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890328-0212 </DOCNO>
