<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   03-28 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Prices Slide Again As Rain Soaks Midwest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rumored Soviet purchase of U.S. corn helped
boost grain futures prices Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade
but soybean futures fell for the third straight day as rain soaked
the Midwest.
   The modest rally in the grain markets followed a sharp,
across-the-board drop in prices in the previous session.
   Traders said Monday's price break apparently brought the Soviet
Union into the cash market.
   ``Most guesses are that they bought 2 million tons for April
through June shipment,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago. ``There are all the earmarks of
business actually being done; the only real question is how much
was done.''
   Rainfall in the Midwest, where dryness from last year's drought
still lingers, kept pressure on soybean prices.
   Soybean oil futures fell sharply on selling inspired by
weakening chart signals. The contract for May delivery of soybean
oil closed .54 cent lower at 22.88 cents a pound.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent lower to 2 cents higher with May
at $4.28} a bushel; corn was \ cent to 2{ cents higher with May at
$2.74 a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to 2{ cents higher with May at
$1.96} a bushel; soybeans were { cent to 7\ cents lower with May at
$7.62 a bushel.
