<FIRST>r f AM-Pickens-CorporateList     03-28 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pickens-Corporate List,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Raider Lists Top `Shareholder-Friendly' Companies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover specialist T. Boone Pickens,
countering such size-based corporate rankings as the Fortune 500
and Business Week 1000, on Tuesday released his own list of
companies rated by shareholder friendliness.
   United Shareholders Association, a group formed by Pickens to
lobby in favor of ``shareholders' rights'' and against takeover
defenses, rated 1,000 companies based on their lack of obstacles to
takeover, price and dividend performance and degree of management
ownership.
   The group claims managers with a personal stake in a company
perform better and it claims companies without such anti-takeover
devices as poison pills and golden parachutes represent better
values than those with them.
   ``USA's Corporate 1000 ratings point out which managements are
attuned to shareholder interests. Sort of the good, the bad and the
ugly of corporate America,'' Pickens said.
   The Texas oilman, who has chased some big companies like
Phillips Petroleum Co. and Newmont Mining Corp. and is considering
running for governor, said the list wasn't intended to be a stock
tip sheet, but he is billing it as a ``consumer guide'' and
``owners manual for corporate America.''
   Kathryn Rudie Harrigan, a professor at Columbia Business School,
criticized Pickens' emphasis on stock price and dividend
performance.
   ``Companies that do things to pretty up their stock prices are
not necessarily managing for the long run. They are probably
cutting into not just the fat, but also the muscle they need for
long-run competitiveness,'' she said.
   According to Pickens, the 20 best companies are: Price, Circle
K, Aon, Southwest Airlines, TCA Cable TV, Gap, Autodesk,
Systematics, Applied Biosystems, Russell, EMC, Berkshire Hathaway,
20th Century Industries, 3 Com, Ohio Mattress, Intel, GAF,
Walgreen, Wal-Mart Stores and Tyco Laboratories.
   The 20 worst, according to the list, are: Allegheny
International, Maxus Energy, USG, LTV, Hercules, Manville, Home
Group, Robertston (H.H.), National Intergroup, Asarco, Goodyear
Tire &amp; Rubber, Pittston, Tektronix, Andarko Petroleum, Bowater,
Caterpillar, Navistar International, Texas Air, USX and Western
Union.
</TEXT>
