<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     03-28 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Gains; Gold Loses</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar advanced broadly during a busy
session Tuesday despite efforts by central banks to check its
movement.
   Gold prices sank. The Republic National Bank of New York quoted
a bid of $383 for a troy ounce of gold at 4 p.m. EST, down $7 from
Monday's late bid.
   Victor Polce, a vice president at Bear, Stearns &amp; Co., said
traders bought dollars actively throughout the day, undeterred by
central banks selling dollars in a concerted round of intervention.
   ``I think the intervention did absolutely nothing,'' said Polce.
``Traders were saying `Give me some dollars, make my day' because
they believed they would be able to sell them higher in the
future.''
   Foreign exchange dealers in Europe said the U.S. currency
recovered quickly from concerted dollar-selling by the central
banks of West Germany and other countries. Traders estimated the
central banks sold nearly $200 million.
   The absence of the influential Bank of Japan from the markets
may have caused currency dealers to ignore what the other central
banks were doing.
   ``Traders are getting tired of the old names,'' Polce
said.``They really want to see the Bank of Japan in the market.''
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7030 late Tuesday, cheaper
for buyers than Friday's $1.7190. Later in New York, sterling
fetched $1.6855 compared to $1.7085 on Monday.
   Earlier in Tokyo the dollar closed at 132.30 Japanese yen, up
0.60. In London late Tuesday the dollar traded higher at 132.48 and
at 133.105 yen later in New York.
   Most European markets were closed Friday and Monday for the
Easter holiday but Rome was open for business.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Monday's late
rates included: 1.89525 West German marks, up from 1.8834; 1.65325
Swiss francs, up from 1.6415; 1.19525 Canadian dollars, up from
1.19305; 6.4010 French francs, up from 6.36375; and 1,388.025
Italian lire, up from 1,381.25.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with Friday's
late rates included: 1.8850 West German marks, up from 1.8733;
1.6415 Swiss francs, up from 1.6252; 6.3625 French francs, up from
6.3350; 2.1215 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1138; 1,379.50 Italian
lire, up from 1,376.10; and, 1.1925 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1895.
   Gold bullion prices sagged by around $7 an ounce in active
European trading.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $383 a troy ounce, down from $391.10 on Monday.
   Gold closed in London, the major market, at a bid $387.50 a troy
ounce, down from $394.75. The Zurich closing bid price was $388,
down from $395.
   Traders said the price fell sharply when the New York market
opened and began selling. They said the dollar's strength in the
face of central banks selling dollars and lower prices for crude
oil in New York helped to drive down the price of gold.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold closed at $392.64 bid, down from
$396.14.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.91 bid a troy ounce,
down from $6.08. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery finished at $5.794 a troy ounce, down from Monday's
settlement of $5.946.
</TEXT>
