<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-28 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Price Plunges As Dollar Flexes Muscle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold futures prices plunged to a 5{-week low Tuesday as
investors, reacting to a surging dollar, moved their money out of
precious metals and into interest-bearing instruments.
   On other markets, energy futures fell sharply, reversing most of
the previous day's gains; soybeans slipped while grain futures
advanced; cattle futures were lower; and pork futures were mixed.
   Gold settled $8.10 to $9.30 lower on New York's Commodity
Exchange with the contract for delivery in April at $383.50 a troy
ounce. It was the lowest settlement price for a gold contract on
the exchange since Feb. 17, when gold finished at $380.80 an ounce
after trading that day as low as $380, a 27-month low.
   Silver futures settled 15.2 cents to 17.4 cents lower with May
at $5.848 a troy ounce.
   Gold prices typically rise and fall with inflation fears,
reflecting the metal's tendency to hold its worth even as the
dollar falls in value.
   A stronger dollar is viewed as anti-inflationary. It makes U.S.
goods more expensive overseas and makes foreign-made goods cheaper
in this country, reducing demand for U.S.-made goods and slowing
the economy's growth.
   The rapid rise of short-term interest rates during the first
quarter of this year has contributed to the dollar's strength and
drawn investment dollars into government-backed securities and
certificates of deposit.
   Several recent government reports on wholesale and retail prices
seemed to suggest that inflation was on the rise. But Tuesday's
activity in the currency and precious-metals markets indicates
confidence among investors that the Federal Reserve Board is
succeeding in stifling inflation by forcing interest rates up.
   ``I think the market's perception is that these high, real rates
of return on the dollar are going to continue and may even
increase, and I don't think that's real positive for the gold
market,'' said John Norris, the head of precious-metals trading for
Citibank in New York.
   A further drop in gold's price below the Feb. 17 low of $380 an
ounce would likely trigger an even steeper sell-off, analysts said.
   ``But I don't think that's going to happen,'' said Peter
Cardillo, commodity trading adviser with Josephthal &amp; Co., a New
York-based futures brokerage. ``I think there's enough support to
hold at this level and we should begin to see some European bargain
hunting.''
   Oil prices fell sharply on the New York Mercantile Exchange on
profit-taking off of Monday's strong gains, which had pushed crude
oil to its highest price in 19 months.
   Monday's runup was linked to the massive Alaskan oil spill and
the shutdown of the Port of Valdez, the southern terminus of the
Alaska pipeline. The port was reopened on Tuesday.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 44 cents to 69 cents
lower with May at $19.91 a barrel; heating oil was 1.31 cents to
2.54 cents lower with April at 55.04 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .30 cent to 1.07 cents lower with April at 58.68 cents
a gallon.
   A rumored Soviet purchase of U.S. corn helped boost grain
futures prices on the Chicago Board of Trade but soybean futures
fell for the third straight day as rain soaked the Midwest.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 2 cents higher with May at $4.28} a
bushel; corn was \ cent to 2\ cents higher with May at $2.73} a
bushel; oats were 1{ cents to 2{ cents higher with May at $1.96} a
bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 6} cents lower with May at
$7.62} a bushel.
   Cattle and hog futures retreated modestly in technically
inspired selling on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange while
pork-belly futures advanced.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent to .38 cent lower with April at
77.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .32 cent lower
with April at 81.85 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent lower to
.17 cent higher with April at 42.12 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .60 cent to .87 cent higher with May at 38.02 cents a
pound.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
