<FIRST>r f AM-Giuliani-Japan     03-28 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Giuliani-Japan,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former U.S. Attorney To Visit Japan On Insider Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Manhattan U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani,
who led a crackdown on white-collar crime during his five-year
tenure, said Tuesday he will travel to Japan next month to offer
advice on prosecuting insider trading and other securities fraud.
   The Japanese government is currently embroiled in a stock
scandal of its own that has implicated government officials and is
putting pressure on Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita.
   Giuliani, whose office brought about 50 securities fraud
indictments in his term that ended in January, said he was
contacted by private attorneys in Japan and will lecture to
officials in Tokyo April 13-14.
   ``I think it's very, very important for the United States that
in other countries that are part of the world market that we have a
similar set of rules,'' he said. ``Otherwise we're at a competitive
disadvantage.''
   Giuliani, a possible New York mayoral candidate now in private
practice, said he will meet with more than 10 Japanese investment
firms and U.S. firms with offices there, as well as government
agencies, securities officials and law enforcement organizations.
He said he will discuss U.S. insider trading and other securities
fraud laws and cases.
   Japan, home to the world's biggest stock market, modeled its
postwar laws on securities fraud after those in the United States
but rarely enforced them. Markets in some European countries and
Hong Kong are loosely regulated, and insider trading and other
financial scandals recently hit France and Mexico.
   ``Many of them have statutes and laws, some similar to ours,
some a little different,'' Giuliani said.
   ``The major problem they're undergoing is the same problem we
were undergoing in the '40s, '50s and '60s _ not enforcing them,
not knowing how to enforce them and not having educated the
institutions on the importance of the rules,'' he said.
   The current scandal in Japan involves the sale of thousands of
shares of unlisted stock by the Recruit Co. to politicians and
other prominent people at bargain prices. The buyers reaped
windfalls when the shares were publicly traded later.
   At least 17 senior politicians, including Takeshita and former
Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone, have been linked to the scandal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
