<DOCNO> AP890328-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 2205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-BusinessExpectations     03-28 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Expectations,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Business Executives Forecast Strong Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business executives are forecasting a strong
second quarter, with profit expectations for the three months
starting Saturday at their highest level since 1984, according to
survey results released Tuesday.
   ``Business executives' plans to increase prices are clearly
having at least a short-term impact on profit expectations,'' said
Joseph W. Duncan, corporate economist and chief statistician for
The Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp., which conducted the poll of 1,500
executives.
   ``Order books are strong, but the ability to maintain high
profit expectations throughout 1989 is questionable,'' he said in a
statement.
   Nearly half those polled said they planned to increase prices in
the second quarter.
   In the survey, conducted Feb. 8-27, the executives in
manufacturing, retailing and wholesaling were asked if they
expected an increase, decrease or no change in second-quarter
sales, profits, prices, inventories, employment and new orders.
   Expectations for higher second-quarter profits climbed to the
highest level since 1984, rising nine points to 69 on Dun &amp;
Bradstreet's index of profit expectations.
   The survey's indexes are calculated by subtracting the
percentage of respondents predicting decreases from the percentage
of those expecting increases.
   The sales-optimism index rose six points to 74 from 68 in the
first quarter, and five points from the second quarter of 1988.
   The index of companies expecting to increase prices rose to 46
from 41 in the first quarter.
   ``Inflationary pressures are now pushing prices up, after
remaining fairly consistent for the past five quarters,'' Duncan
said.
   The employment-optimism index decreased one point to 23 from the
first quarter, mostly due to a two-point drop in expectations among
wholesalers, Dun &amp; Bradstreet said.
   The index of companies' exepectations for increased inventories
rose three points to 29, a finding that Duncan said could prove a
problem later in the year if increased prices make it difficult to
move goods.
   The optimism index for new orders among manufacturers of
non-durable goods rose six points to 71, while the index for
durable goods manufacturers increased five points to 70.
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet is a leading marketer of business information.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
