<DOCNO> AP890328-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 1952EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-FSX 1stLd-writethru a0647 03-28 0833</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FSX, 1st Ld-writethru, a0647,0856</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: To update with comment from Matsunaga, adds 2 grafs after 3rd
graf previous ``It is''; edits grafs 15-16 to comply. Also moved on general
news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Tuesday he is still
seeking clarifications from Japan on building the advanced FSX jet
fighter and that efforts to nail down an agreement are ``going back
and forth a little.''
   Administration officials said the final go-ahead on the joint
project is being delayed by haggling with Japan over who will own
the technology and how many planes would be U.S.-built.
   It is possible that a Japanese-set Friday deadline for a final
decision may be missed, said the officials, speaking on condition
of anonymity. However, officials also sought to dispel the idea the
project is unraveling and said a deal was still considered likely.
   Japanese Ambassador Nobuo Matsunaga, who had requested a Tuesday
afternoon meeting with Secretary of State James A. Baker III, said
afterwards that no final agreement had been reached, but the two
sides ``agreed to continue to talk. That was the firm objective.''
   But Matsunaga added that no decision had been made on the timing
of new meetings. The ambassador said Seiki Nishihiro, the deputy
director general of the Japanese defense agency who had also taken
part in the discussions, was returning to Japan.
   Under the agreement, originally negotiated last year by the
Reagan administration, the new plane would be built jointly by
General Dynamics and Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy Industries. The plane
would be modeled on the American-made F-16 fighter.
   Bush, who disclosed last week that he had decided to go ahead
with the project, told reporters Tuesday that the United States is
pressing for more clarity in the revised agreement to be submitted
to Congress.
   ``It's going back and forth a little bit. All I want to know is
that the agreement is clear. No point in having an unclear
agreement,'' Bush said.
   ``We have a lot at stake here,'' the president added, ``a lot at
stake in terms of the common defense; we have a lot at stake in
terms of commerce; we have a lot at stake in terms of technology.
And all I'm asking is to be clear.''
   The project has encountered stiff opposition in Congress, where
critics have called it a $8 billion high-technology giveaway to
Japan. They say Tokyo should purchase American-made planes to help
offset the $50 billion U.S. trade deficit with Japan.
   Even with within the administration, there have been skeptics at
high levels, including Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher and U.S.
Trade Representative Carla Hills. They have argued that without
careful safeguards the deal could give Japan free help in
developing an aerospace industry of its own to compete with U.S.
companies.
   Bush suggested he still wants to go ahead with the project so
long as there are necessary safeguards.
   ``The United States will keep its word, properly, insisting on
clarity in the agreement. And that's about where we stand right
now,'' Bush said. He spoke after a meeting in the Oval Office to
discuss the oil spill in Alaska.
   A U.S. negotiating group, made up of officials from the
Commerce, Defense and State departments, have been meeting all week
with Japanese officials in an effort to come up with a final
agreement.
   Matsunaga met Tuesday morning with Deputy Secretary of State
Lawrence Eagleburger, the first official meeting between the sides
since a negotiating session last Thursday.
   But State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the FSX
fighter was discussed only briefly because the meeting was a
courtesy call planned before the controversy erupted.
   One U.S. official close to the negotiations denied Tuesday that
the agreement was unraveling, suggesting that Japanese officials
were treating the talks more as a trade negotiation than a
defense-related one _ and doing a considerable amount of
maneuvering for home consumption.
   ``I feel we'll still get a deal,'' said the official, who
insisted upon anonymity.
   ``The Japanese negotiate differently on trade. On trade
negotiation. On trade negotiations, they always go right up to the
wall _ they set a deadline and then they negotiate past it, to show
they've gone the extra mile,'' the official said.
   White House sources said that the president could move on the
agreement with an announcement in a matter of hours once the final
document has been readied.
   The Japanese say they need to have the agreement by Friday to
include the project in the budget for the new fiscal year that
begins April 1.
   Asked if that deadline would be met, Bush said: ``I don't know
whether it will be done by then, or not.''
   The Reagan administration began negotiations on the fighter
after Japan refused to buy F-16s off the shelf and indicated it
wanted to build its own jet fighter.
   The agreement reportedly will seek to protect sophisticated U.S.
computer codes that enable the plane's computer software to fly the
plane and control its sophisticated weaponry.
