<FIRST>u f BC-Seagram     03-28 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Seagram,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seagram To Drop Rights To 17 Brands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph E. Seagram &amp; Sons Inc. said Tuesday it
will divest of trademark or sales and marketing rights to 17 brands
of distilled spirits in the United States.
   Seagram, the U.S. subsidiary of The Seagram Co. Ltd. of Canada,
said it decided to drop rights to the non-essential spirits last
November. Terms of the deals were not disclosed.
   Seagram said in a statement that Heaven Hill Distilleries Inc.
of Bardstown, Ky., will acquire Harwood Canadian Whiskey, Wilson
Blend, Paul Jones Blend, Mattingly &amp; Moore Bourbon, Henry McKenna
Bourbon and Vandermint Liquor.
   It also will acquire marketing rights to Burnett's Gin and 100
Pipers, Queen Anne and Something Special Scotches. Heaven Hill also
will be able market Mattingly &amp; Moore Bourbon internationally.
   Sazerac Co., a New Orleans producer and importer, acquired the
U.S. trademark rights to Nikolai Vodka, James Foxe Canadian Whisky,
Carstairs Blend and Benchmark and Eagle Rare Bourbons.
   It also obtained some U.S. marketing rights to Crown Russe Vodka
and Dr. McGillicuddy's Schnapps. Sazerac also obtained the right to
market Carstairs Blend and Benchmark and Eagle Rare Bourbons
internationally.
   The Seagram Co. produces distilled spirits, wines, coolers and
juices including Chivas Regal, Crown Royal Seagram's V.O. Canadian
Whiskies, Martell Cognac, Barton &amp; Guestier Wines and Tropicana
Pure Premium Orange Juice.
   Seagram on Monday entered the soda market when it acquired
American Natural Beverge Corp., the small New York-based maker of
Soho Natural Sodas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
