<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Songs 1stLd-Writethru   03-28 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Songs, 1st Ld-Writethru,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Idle Eastern Workers Write `Songs for the Picket Line' ^With AM-Eastern,
Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf to RECAST; picks up 4th graf pvs bg'ng, Entries
include ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some employees of strike-bound Eastern Airlines,
idled for nearly four weeks, have turned their attention to
immortalizing boss Frank Lorenzo in songs ranging from ``King of
the Raid'' to ``If I Had A Pilot.''
   They have written about 20 strike jingles, collected in a new
brochure called ``The Eastern Shuffle: Songs for the Eastern Picket
Line.'' It's published by the Labor Heritage Foundation in
Washington, and comes with a 60-minute cassette recording of
employees crooning the numbers.
   What tune did Eastern spokesman Robin Matell sing when he heard
about the songbook? ``No Comment.''
   Entries include ``King of the Raid,'' sung to the tune of ``King
of the Road'' and targeted at Lorenzo:
   ``Airline for sale or rent
   Millions I've already spent
   I own controlling shares
   Now I'm a billionaire
   And I can't wait till I acquire
   More of my airline empire
   I'm a man of greed by all means
   King of the Raid!''
   
   ``I own every worker on every plane
   I know every trick in the corporate game
   I know every company in every town
   And how to buy them out when the prices are down''
   Etc.
   
   Then there's ``If I Had a Pilot,'' to the tune of the folk
classic ``If I Had a Hammer.''
   ``If I had a pilot
   I'd be flying in the morning
   I'd be flying in the evening
   All over this land
   I don't care about the danger
   I don't care about the warnings
   All I want to do is steal the workers' wages and their pensions
   All over this land.''
   
   Further verses: ``If I had mechanics, If I had flight
attendants,'' etc.
   
   Other numbers include ``Don't Fly the Eastern Shuttle When You
Come.'' (Tune: ``She'll Be Comin' Round the Mountain''); ``The
Picket Boogie'' (to the tune of ``The Hokey Pokey''); ``Give Me
That New Union Contract'' (``Old Time Religion''), ``Ten Little
Airplanes Grounded'' (``Ten Little Indians''), ``Lorenzo Don't
Allow'' (``Mama Don't Allow'') and ``Don't Worry, Be Union''
(``Don't Worry, Be Happy'').
</TEXT>
